text: Progressive myoclonus epilepsy 1A (EPM1A) is a type of autosomal recessive disease and an Unverricht-Lundborg syndrome, which is characterized by a material basis in some autosomal recessive inheritance. This condition is defined by its association with homozygous or compound heterozygous mutations in the CSTB gene located on chromosome 21q22.3.

2-Aminoadipic 2-oxoadipic aciduria is a type of autosomal recessive disease and an amino acid metabolic disorder that essentially has its material basis in autosomal recessive inheritance. It is characterized by defects in L-lysine degradation, which leads to variable neurological symptoms; however, many patients remain asymptomatic. This condition has its material basis in homozygous or compound heterozygous mutation in the DHTKD1 gene on chromosome 10p14. Furthermore, 2-aminoadipic 2-oxoadipic aciduria is exactly synonymous with AMOXAD and alpha-aminoadipic aciduria.

Short syndrome is a type of autosomal dominant disease and syndrome that has its material basis in some autosomal dominant inheritance. It is defined as a syndrome of multiple anomalies characterized by short stature, hyperextensibility of joints, ocular depression, Rieger anomaly, and teething delay, along with mild intrauterine growth restriction, partial lipodystrophy, delayed bone age, hernias, and a progeroid appearance. This condition is caused by a heterozygous mutation in the PIK3R1 gene on chromosome 5q13. Short syndrome is also known by its exact synonyms: Aarskog-Ose-Pande syndrome, Lipodystrophy-Rieger anomaly-diabetes syndrome, Rieger anomaly-partial lipodystrophy syndrome, and short stature, hyperextensibility, hernia, ocular depression, Rieger anomaly, and teething delay.

Gracile syndrome is a type of disease that falls under both autosomal recessive and mitochondrial metabolism categories, indicating that it has a material basis in some autosomal recessive inheritance. It is defined as a mitochondrial disorder characterized by a series of symptoms including fetal growth restriction, aminoaciduria, cholestasis, iron overload, lactocidosis, and early death, which result from homozygous or compound heterozygous mutations in the BCS1L gene located on chromosome 2q35. Additionally, Gracile syndrome is known by several exact synonyms, including FLNMS (Finnish Lactic acidosis with hepatic hemosiderosis), Fellman disease, Finnish lethal neonatal metabolic syndrome, and a descriptive term that encompasses its main features: growth delay-aminoaciduria-cholestasis-iron overload-lactic acidosis-early death syndrome, also expressed as growth restriction-aminoaciduria-cholestasis-iron overload-lactic acidosis-early death syndrome, or succinctly as growth retardation, amino aciduria, cholestasis, iron overload, lactic acidosis, and early death.

Kaufman oculocerebrofacial syndrome is a type of autosomal recessive disease and syndromic intellectual disability characterized by developmental delay, growth retardation with a small head circumference, facial dysmorphisms, and low cholesterol levels. This condition has a material basis in homozygous or compound heterozygous mutation in the UBE3B gene on chromosome 12q24.11. It is also noted for having a phenotype that includes neurodevelopmental delay. Furthermore, Kaufman oculocerebrofacial syndrome has exact synonyms: KOS, blepharophimosis ptosis intellectual disability syndrome, and oculocerebrofacial syndrome, Kaufman type.

Sting associated vasculopathy with onset in infancy (SAVI) is a type of disease that is both autosomal dominant and an autoimmune disease of the cardiovascular system. It is characterized by autoinflammatory vasculopathy that leads to severe skin lesions, particularly affecting the face, ears, nose, and digits. This condition results in ulceration, eschar formation, necrosis, and, in some cases, amputation. The onset of SAVI occurs during infancy, and its development is at least partially due to a heterozygous gain of function mutation in the TMEM173 gene located on chromosome 5q31. This disease's manifestations include symptoms such as necrosis, and its genetic basis involves some form of autosomal dominant inheritance.

Galactose epimerase deficiency is a type of autosomal recessive disease and a type of galactosemia, which at least has a material basis in some autosomal recessive inheritance. It is defined as a galactosemia that has a material basis in homozygous or compound heterozygous mutation in the GALE gene on chromosome 1p36.11. Galactose epimerase deficiency is also known by several exact synonyms, including GALE deficiency, GALE-D, UDP-galactose-4-epimerase deficiency, epimerase deficiency galactosemia, galactosemia III, galactosemia type 3, and uridine diphosphate galactose-4-epimerase deficiency.

Classic galactosemia is a type of galactosemia and an autosomal recessive disease, which specifically has its material basis in autosomal recessive inheritance. It is defined as a galactosemia that has its material basis in homozygous or compound heterozygous mutation in the GALT gene on chromosome 9p13.3. Classic galactosemia is exactly synonymous with GALT deficiency, galactose-1-phosphate uridyltransferase deficiency, and galactosemia type 1.

Cardiofaciocutaneous syndrome 1 is a type of autosomal dominant disease and a type of cardiofaciocutaneous syndrome, specifically something that at least has a material basis in some autosomal dominant inheritance. It is defined as a cardiofaciocutaneous syndrome that has its material basis in a heterozygous mutation in the BRAF gene on chromosome 7q34. Additionally, cardiofaciocutaneous syndrome 1 has the exact synonym CFC1.

Cardiofaciocutaneous syndrome 2, also known exactly as CFC2, is a type of autosomal dominant disease and a specific form of cardiofaciocutaneous syndrome. It is characterized by having a material basis in some form of autosomal dominant inheritance. Furthermore, the syndrome is defined by a heterozygous mutation in the KRAS gene located on chromosome 12p12.1.

Cardiofaciocutaneous syndrome 3 is a type of autosomal dominant disease and a specific type of cardiofaciocutaneous syndrome, characterized by having a material basis in autosomal dominant inheritance. It is defined as a cardiofaciocutaneous syndrome that originates from a heterozygous mutation in the MAP2K1 gene located on chromosome 15q22.31. Furthermore, cardiofaciocutaneous syndrome 3 is exactly synonymous with CFC3.

Cardiofaciocutaneous syndrome 4 (CFC4) is a subtype of cardiofaciocutaneous syndrome and an autosomal dominant disease. It is characterized by a specific type of inheritance that involves a material basis in autosomal dominant inheritance. The definition of cardiofaciocutaneous syndrome 4 includes it being a cardiofaciocutaneous syndrome that originates from a heterozygous mutation in the MAPK2K2 gene located on chromosome 19p13.3.

Combined oxidative phosphorylation deficiency 35 (COXPD35) is a form of autosomal recessive disease and a specific type of combined oxidative phosphorylation deficiency. It is characterized by a condition that inherently has a material basis in autosomal recessive inheritance. COXPD35 is defined as a combined oxidative phosphorylation deficiency that is marked by global developmental delay with intellectual disability, microcephaly, and early-onset seizures. This condition arises from homozygous or compound heterozygous mutation in the TRIT1 gene located on chromosome 1p34.2.

Combined Oxidative Phosphorylation Deficiency 21 (COXPD21) is a type of autosomal recessive disease, which also falls under the category of combined oxidative phosphorylation deficiencies. It is defined by conditions such as axial hypotonia, limb hypertonia, psychomotor delay, and hyperlactatemia. These symptoms are due to homozygous or compound heterozygous mutations in the TARS2 gene located on chromosome 1q21.2. Additionally, it is characterized as a condition that at least has a material basis in some autosomal recessive inheritance.

Combined Oxidative Phosphorylation Deficiency 38 (COXPD38) is a specific type of autosomal recessive disease and falls under the broader category of combined oxidative phosphorylation deficiencies. It is characterized by having a material basis in autosomal recessive inheritance. The definition of COXPD38 is that it is a combined oxidative phosphorylation deficiency which results from homozygous or compound heterozygous mutations in the MRPS14 gene located on chromosome 1q25.1.

Combined Oxidative Phosphorylation Deficiency 13 (COXPD13) is a type of autosomal recessive disease and a specific form of combined oxidative phosphorylation deficiency. It is characterized by a severe neurological impairment that develops in the first months of life, which has its material basis in homozygous or compound heterozygous mutations in the PNPT1 gene located on chromosome 2p16.1. This condition is also known to be associated with autosomal recessive inheritance.

Combined Oxidative Phosphorylation Deficiency 25 (COXPD25) is a type of autosomal recessive disease and falls under the broader category of combined oxidative phosphorylation deficiencies. It is characterized by a material basis in autosomal recessive inheritance. Specifically, COXPD25 is defined by a combined oxidative phosphorylation deficiency that occurs due to homozygous or compound heterozygous mutations in the MARS2 gene located on chromosome 2q33.1.

Combined Oxidative Phosphorylation Deficiency 16 (COXPD16), also known as infantile hypertrophic cardiomyopathy due to MRPL44 deficiency, is a specific form of autosomal recessive disease. It falls under the broader category of combined oxidative phosphorylation deficiencies and is characterized by having a material basis in autosomal recessive inheritance. The definition of COXPD16 includes being a combined oxidative phosphorylation deficiency that arises from homozygous or compound heterozygous mutations in the MRPL44 gene located on chromosome 2q36.1.

Combined Oxidative Phosphorylation Deficiency 28 (COXPD28), also known as neonatal severe cardiopulmonary failure due to mitochondrial methylation defect, is an autosomal recessive disease. It falls under the broader category of combined oxidative phosphorylation deficiencies and is characterized by autosomal recessive inheritance. This specific deficiency has its material basis in homozygous or compound heterozygous mutations in the SLC25A26 gene located on chromosome 3p14.1.

Combined oxidative phosphorylation deficiency 30 (COXPD30) is a type of autosomal recessive disease and a type of combined oxidative phosphorylation deficiency. It is characterized as something that at least has a material basis in autosomal recessive inheritance. COXPD30 is defined as a combined oxidative phosphorylation deficiency that has its material basis in homozygous or compound heterozygous mutations in the TRMT10C gene on chromosome 3q12.3.

Combined Oxidative Phosphorylation Deficiency 9 (COXPD9) is a type of autosomal recessive disease and a specific form of combined oxidative phosphorylation deficiency. It is characterized by a material basis in autosomal recessive inheritance. COXPD9 is defined as a combined oxidative phosphorylation deficiency that arises from homozygous or compound heterozygous mutations in the MRPL3 gene located on chromosome 3q22.1.

Combined Oxidative Phosphorylation Deficiency 5 (COXPD5), also known as hypotonia with lactic acidemia and hyperammonemia, is a type of autosomal recessive disease and a specific form of combined oxidative phosphorylation deficiency. It is recognized by its severe hypotonia, lactic academia, and congenital hyperammonemia, attributed to either homozygous or compound heterozygous mutations in the MRPS22 gene located on chromosome 3q23. This condition is characterized as a disorder that fundamentally has a material basis in some form of autosomal recessive inheritance.

Combined Oxidative Phosphorylation Deficiency 1 (COXPD1) is a type of autosomal recessive disease, which belongs to the category of combined oxidative phosphorylation deficiencies. It is characterized by a material basis in autosomal recessive inheritance. This specific deficiency is defined by a homozygous or compound heterozygous mutation in the GFM1 gene located on chromosome 3q25.32. COXPD1 is also known by several exact synonyms including early fatal progressive hepatoencephalopathy, hepatoencephalopathy due to COXPD1, and hepatoencephalopathy due to combined oxidative phosphorylation defect type 1.

Combined oxidative phosphorylation deficiency 39 (COXPD39) is a type of autosomal recessive disease and falls under the broader category of combined oxidative phosphorylation deficiencies. It specifically arises from a material basis in autosomal recessive inheritance. COXPD39 is defined as a combined oxidative phosphorylation deficiency that results from homozygous or compound heterozygous mutations in the GFM2 gene located on chromosome 5q13.3.

Combined oxidative phosphorylation deficiency 19 (COXPD19), also known as severe neonatal lactic acidosis due to NFS1-ISD11 complex deficiency, is a type of autosomal recessive disease, and more specifically, it is a form of combined oxidative phosphorylation deficiency. This condition is characterized by its material basis in autosomal recessive inheritance and is defined by a combined oxidative phosphorylation deficiency that arises from homozygous or compound heterozygous mutation in the LYRM4 gene on chromosome 6p25.1.

Combined Oxidative Phosphorylation Deficiency 14 (COXPD14) is a type of autosomal recessive disease and a specific form of combined oxidative phosphorylation deficiency. It is characterized by a neonatal onset of global developmental delay, refractory seizures, and lactic acidosis. This condition fundamentally arises from either homozygous or compound heterozygous mutations in the FARS2 gene located on chromosome 6p25.1. Moreover, COXPD14 is also recognized as a condition that has its material basis in autosomal recessive inheritance.

Combined Oxidative Phosphorylation Deficiency 20 (COXPD20) is a type of disease that falls under the category of autosomal recessive diseases, and it specifically belongs to the group of combined oxidative phosphorylation deficiencies. This condition is characterized by having a material basis in autosomal recessive inheritance. Moreover, COXPD20 is defined as a combined oxidative phosphorylation deficiency that is caused by homozygous or compound heterozygous mutation in the VARS2 gene located on chromosome 6p21.33.

Combined Oxidative Phosphorylation Deficiency 8 (COXPD8) is a type of autosomal recessive disease and is categorized under combined oxidative phosphorylation deficiencies. It is defined as a combined oxidative phosphorylation deficiency characterized by lethal infantile hypertrophic cardiomyopathy, and in some instances, there is subtle involvement of the skeletal muscle and brain. This condition has a material basis in homozygous or compound heterozygous mutations in the AARS2 gene located on chromosome 6p21.1. Furthermore, COXPD8 is an entity that inherently involves some form of autosomal recessive inheritance.

Combined Oxidative Phosphorylation Deficiency 10 (COXPD10) is a type of autosomal recessive disease and also falls under the broader category of combined oxidative phosphorylation deficiencies. It is characterized by certain conditions that have a genetic basis in autosomal recessive inheritance. Specifically, COXPD10 is defined as a combined oxidative phosphorylation deficiency characterized by hypertrophic cardiomyopathy and lactic acidosis, which results from homozygous or compound heterozygous mutations in the MTO1 gene located on chromosome 6q13. Besides COXPD10, this condition is also exactly known as infantile hypertrophic mitochondrial cardiomyopathy and lactic acidosis, as well as mitochondrial hypertrophic cardiomyopathy with lactic acidosis due to MTO1 deficiency.

Combined Oxidative Phosphorylation Deficiency 11 (COXPD11), also known as infantile encephaloneuromyopathy due to mitochondrial translation defect, is a type of autosomal recessive disease and a specific category of combined oxidative phosphorylation deficiency. This condition is characterized by a material basis in some form of autosomal recessive inheritance. COXPD11 is defined as a combined oxidative phosphorylation deficiency that features neonatal hypotonia, lactic acidosis, and death in infancy, with some cases also presenting respiratory insufficiency, foot deformities, or seizures. These symptoms have a material basis in homozygous or compound heterozygous mutations in the RMND1 gene located on chromosome 6q25.1.

Combined Oxidative Phosphorylation Deficiency 36 (COXPD36) is classified as a type of autosomal recessive disease, and it falls under the broader category of combined oxidative phosphorylation deficiencies. It is characterized by having its material basis in autosomal recessive inheritance. Specifically, COXPD36 is defined by a combined oxidative phosphorylation deficiency that arises due to homozygous or compound heterozygous mutation in the MRPS2 gene located on chromosome 9q34.3.

Combined Oxidative Phosphorylation Deficiency 2 (COXPD2), also known as agenesis of corpus callosum with dysmorphism and fatal lactic acidosis, is a type of autosomal recessive disease and a specific form of combined oxidative phosphorylation deficiency. It is characterized by a material basis in autosomal recessive inheritance. The condition is defined by a combined oxidative phosphorylation deficiency that results from homozygous or compound heterozygous mutation in the MRPS16 gene located on chromosome 10q22.2.

Combined Oxidative Phosphorylation Deficiency 18 (COXPD18), also known as growth and developmental delay-hypotonia-vision impairment-lactic acidosis syndrome, is a type of autosomal recessive disease, as well as a specific form of combined oxidative phosphorylation deficiency. It is characterized by a condition that fundamentally has a material basis in autosomal recessive inheritance. COXPD18 is defined as a combined oxidative phosphorylation deficiency marked by intrauterine growth retardation, hypotonia, visual impairment, speech delay, and lactic acidosis. This condition is due to homozygous or compound heterozygous mutations in the SFXN4 gene located on chromosome 10q26.11.

Combined Oxidative Phosphorylation Deficiency 24 (COXPD24) is a type of autosomal recessive disease, which falls under the broader category of combined oxidative phosphorylation deficiencies. It is associated with conditions that have a material basis in autosomal recessive inheritance and is characterized by neurodevelopmental delay among other symptoms. Specifically, COXPD24 is typically characterized by delayed neurodevelopment, refractory seizures, hypotonia, and hearing impairment. This condition is caused by homozygous or compound heterozygous mutation in the NARS2 gene on chromosome 11q14.1.

Combined Oxidative Phosphorylation Deficiency 3 (COXPD3) is a type of autosomal recessive disease, which is also a form of combined oxidative phosphorylation deficiency. This condition is characterized by having a material basis in autosomal recessive inheritance. Specifically, COXPD3 is caused by homozygous or compound heterozygous mutation in the TSFM gene located on chromosome 12q14.1. It is known by several exact synonyms including Fatal mitochondrial disease due to COXPD3, concentric cardiomyopathy, hypotonia, and lactic acidosis, encephalomyopathy, respiratory failure, and lactic acidosis, and fatal mitochondrial disease due to combined oxidative phosphorylation defect type 3.

Combined Oxidative Phosphorylation Deficiency 7 (COXPD7) is a type of autosomal recessive disease and falls under the broader category of combined oxidative phosphorylation deficiencies. It is characterized by having a material basis in autosomal recessive inheritance. More specifically, COXPD7 is defined by a combined oxidative phosphorylation deficiency that arises from homozygous or compound heterozygous mutations in the C12orf65 gene located on chromosome 12q24.31. The condition is also precisely known by the synonyms severe C12ORF65-related COXPD and severe C12ORF65-related combined oxidative phosphorylation defect.

Combined Oxidative Phosphorylation Deficiency 31 (COXPD31), also known exactly as Lethal Left Ventricular Non-compaction-Seizures-Hypotonia-Cataract-Developmental Delay Syndrome, is a type of autosomal recessive disease, and more specifically, it is part of the combined oxidative phosphorylation deficiencies. This particular condition is characterized as a combined oxidative phosphorylation deficiency that notably features global developmental delay, severe hypotonia, and left ventricular non-compaction. Its material basis is attributed to either homozygous or compound heterozygous mutations in the MIPEP gene located on chromosome 13q12.12. Essentially, COXPD31 is a disorder that inherently has an autosomal recessive inheritance pattern.

Combined oxidative phosphorylation deficiency 27 (COXPD27) is a specific type of autosomal recessive disease, which falls under the broader category of combined oxidative phosphorylation deficiencies. It is characterized by having a material basis in autosomal recessive inheritance. Specifically, COXPD27 is defined by a combined oxidative phosphorylation deficiency that results from homozygous or compound heterozygous mutations in the CARS2 gene located on chromosome 13q34.

Combined Oxidative Phosphorylation Deficiency 26 (COXPD26) is a type of autosomal recessive disease and a specific form of combined oxidative phosphorylation deficiency. It is characterized by a material basis in autosomal recessive inheritance. The definition of COXPD26 is a combined oxidative phosphorylation deficiency that originates from homozygous or compound heterozygous mutation in the TRMT5 gene located on chromosome 14q23.1.

Combined Oxidative Phosphorylation Deficiency 15 (COXPD15) is a type of autosomal recessive disease and a specific form of combined oxidative phosphorylation deficiency. It is characterized by having a material basis in some autosomal recessive inheritance. COXPD15 is defined by a combined oxidative phosphorylation deficiency that has a material basis in homozygous or compound heterozygous mutation in the MTFMT gene on chromosome 15q22.31.

Combined Oxidative Phosphorylation Deficiency 32 (COXPD32) is a type of autosomal recessive disease and falls under the broader category of combined oxidative phosphorylation deficiencies. It is defined as a combined oxidative phosphorylation deficiency characterized by its onset in infancy, manifesting as delayed psychomotor development and developmental regression. This condition specifically arises due to homozygous or compound heterozygous mutations in the MRPS34 gene located on chromosome 16p13.3. Moreover, it is identified as a condition that inherently has a material basis in some form of autosomal recessive inheritance.

Combined Oxidative Phosphorylation Deficiency 12 is a type of autosomal recessive disease, combined oxidative phosphorylation deficiency, and something that at least has a material basis in some autosomal recessive inheritance. It is characterized by infantile onset of hypotonia and delayed psychomotor development or developmental regression, with its material basis in homozygous or compound heterozygous mutation in the EARS2 gene on chromosome 16p12.2. This condition is also known by its exact synonyms: COXPD12, LTBL, leukoencephalopathy with thalamus and brainstem involvement and high lactate, and leukoencephalopathy-thalamus and brainstem anomalies-high lactate syndrome.

Combined Oxidative Phosphorylation Deficiency 4 (COXPD4) is a type of autosomal recessive disease and a specific form of combined oxidative phosphorylation deficiency. It is characterized as something that fundamentally arises from autosomal recessive inheritance. The definition of COXPD4 is a combined oxidative phosphorylation deficiency that results from homozygous or compound heterozygous mutation in the TUFM gene located on chromosome 16p11.2.

Combined Oxidative Phosphorylation Deficiency 33 (COXPD33) is a type of autosomal recessive disease and falls under the broader category of combined oxidative phosphorylation deficiencies. It is characterized by having a material basis in autosomal recessive inheritance. COXPD33 is defined as a combined oxidative phosphorylation deficiency that results from homozygous or compound heterozygous mutations in the C1QBP gene located on chromosome 17p13.2.

Combined Oxidative Phosphorylation Deficiency 17 (COXPD17) is a type of autosomal recessive disease and also falls under the category of combined oxidative phosphorylation deficiencies. It is defined as a combined oxidative phosphorylation deficiency characterized by the onset in the first years of life of severe hypertrophic cardiomyopathy, which is based on homozygous or compound heterozygous mutation in the ELAC2 gene on chromosome 17p12. This condition exemplifies something that at least has a material basis in some form of autosomal recessive inheritance.

Combined Oxidative Phosphorylation Deficiency 34 (COXPD34) is a type of autosomal recessive disease, which falls under the broader category of combined oxidative phosphorylation deficiencies. This condition is characterized by a material basis in autosomal recessive inheritance and is associated with symptoms such as hepatic dysfunction. COXPD34 is specifically defined as a combined oxidative phosphorylation deficiency typically marked by congenital sensorineural deafness, increased serum lactate, and both hepatic and renal dysfunction. This is due to homozygous or compound heterozygous mutations in the MRPS7 gene located on chromosome 17q25.1. Additionally, COXPD34 is exactly synonymous with syndromic sensorineural deafness due to COXPD, syndromic sensorineural deafness due to combined oxidative phosphorylation defect, and syndromic sensorineural hearing loss due to COXPD.

Combined Oxidative Phosphorylation Deficiency 22 (COXPD22) is a type of autosomal recessive disease and a specific form of combined oxidative phosphorylation deficiency. It is characterized by a condition that fundamentally arises from autosomal recessive inheritance. The definition of COXPD22 is a combined oxidative phosphorylation deficiency that originates from either homozygous or compound heterozygous mutations in the ATP5A1 gene located on chromosome 18q21.1.

Combined Oxidative Phosphorylation Deficiency 37 (COXPD37) is a type of autosomal recessive disease and a specific form of combined oxidative phosphorylation deficiency. It is characterized as something that at least has a material basis in some autosomal recessive inheritance. The definition of COXPD37 includes it being a combined oxidative phosphorylation deficiency characterized by symptoms such as hypotonia, failure to thrive, liver dysfunction, and neurodegeneration. This condition has its material basis in homozygous or compound heterozygous mutation in the MICOS13 gene located on chromosome 19p13.3.

Combined Oxidative Phosphorylation Deficiency 23 (COXPD23) is a type of autosomal recessive disease, which falls under the broader category of combined oxidative phosphorylation deficiencies. It is characterized by a material basis in autosomal recessive inheritance and presents symptoms such as delayed psychomotor development. COXPD23 is defined as a combined oxidative phosphorylation deficiency that manifests in early childhood with hypertrophic cardiomyopathy and/or neurologic symptoms, including hypotonia and delayed psychomotor development. This condition is caused by homozygous or compound heterozygous mutations in the GTPBP3 gene located on chromosome 19p13.11.

Combined oxidative phosphorylation deficiency 29 is a type of disease that falls under the broader category of combined oxidative phosphorylation deficiencies and is characterized by autosomal recessive inheritance. Specifically, this condition has a material basis in homozygous or compound heterozygous mutations in the TXN2 gene located on chromosome 22q12.3. It is also known by its exact synonym, COXPD29.

Combined Oxidative Phosphorylation Deficiency 6 (COXPD6) is a type of combined oxidative phosphorylation deficiency and is also characterized as an X-linked recessive disease. This condition is specifically understood to have a material basis in some X-linked recessive inheritance. Moreover, COXPD6 is defined by a combined oxidative phosphorylation deficiency that results from a hemizygous mutation in the AIFM1 gene located on chromosome Xq26.1. Additionally, COXPD6 is known by several exact synonyms, including Mitochondrial Encephalomyopathy due to COXPD6, Mitochondrial Encephalomyopathy due to Combined Oxidative Phosphorylation Defect 6, and Severe X-linked Mitochondrial Encephalomyopathy.

Li-Fraumeni syndrome 1 is a type of Li-Fraumeni syndrome, which is defined as a Li-Fraumeni syndrome that has a material basis in heterozygous mutation in the TP53 gene on chromosome 17p13.1. Furthermore, Li-Fraumeni syndrome 1 is exactly synonymous with LFS1.

Li-Fraumeni syndrome 2 is a specific type of Li-Fraumeni syndrome, which is defined as a Li-Fraumeni syndrome that has its material basis in a heterozygous mutation in the CHEK2 gene on chromosome 22q12.1. Furthermore, it is exactly synonymous with LFS2.

Palmoplantar keratoderma deafness syndrome is a type of syndrome that is classified as an autosomal dominant disease, which suggests it at least has a material basis in some form of autosomal dominant inheritance. This syndrome is defined as a condition characterized by sensorineural hearing loss and progressive hyperkeratosis of the palms and soles, which is caused by a heterozygous mutation in the GJB2 gene on chromosome 13q12.11. It is also known by several exact synonyms, including PPK-deafness syndrome, keratoderma palmoplantar deafness, palmoplantar hyperkeratosis-deafness syndrome, palmoplantar hyperkeratosis-hearing loss syndrome, palmoplantar keratoderma with deafness, and palmoplantar keratoderma-hearing loss syndrome.

Palmoplantar Keratoderma Esophageal Carcinoma Syndrome is a type of syndrome and an autosomal dominant disease, which at least has a material basis in some autosomal dominant inheritance. This syndrome is characterized by palmoplantar keratoderma and esophageal cancer, with its material basis in a heterozygous mutation in the RHBDF2 gene on chromosome 17q25.1. It is also known by several exact synonyms, including Bennion-Patterson Syndrome, Howell-Evans Syndrome, TOC, Keratosis Palmaris et Plantaris with Esophageal Cancer, Keratosis Palmoplantaris-Esophageal Carcinoma Syndrome, Palmoplantar Hyperkeratosis-Esophageal Carcinoma Syndrome, Palmoplantar Keratoderma with Esophageal Cancer, Tylosis with Esophageal Cancer, and Tylosis-Oesophageal Carcinoma Syndrome.

Lenz Majewski Hyperostotic Dwarfism is a syndrome that is considered a type of autosomal dominant disease and is associated with autosomal dominant inheritance. It is characterized by intellectual disability, sclerosing bone dysplasia, distinct craniofacial, dental, cutaneous, and distal-limb anomalies, which have a material basis in a heterozygous mutation in the PTDSS1 gene on chromosome 8q22.1. Lenz Majewski Hyperostotic Dwarfism is also exactly synonymous with Lenz-Majewski syndrome.

Torrance type platyspondylic dysplasia is a type of osteochondrodysplasia, characterized by decreased ossification of the skull base, disc-like platyspondyly, short thin ribs, hypoplastic pelvis with wide sacrosciatic notches and flat acetabular roof, and short tubular long bones with metaphyseal cupping. This condition has a material basis in heterozygous mutation in the COL2A1 gene on chromosome 12q13.11. It is also known by several exact synonyms including PLSD-T, PLSDT, lethal short-limbed platyspondylic dwarfism, Torrance type, platyspondylic dysplasia, Torrance-Luton type, platyspondylic lethal skeletal dysplasia, Torrance type, and thanatophoric dysplasia, Torrance variant.

Lymphedema distichiasis syndrome is a type of syndrome and a specific kind of autosomal dominant disease, which means it is something that at least has its material basis in autosomal dominant inheritance. It is characterized by lymphedema of the limbs and double rows of eyelashes due to a heterozygous mutation in the FOXC2 gene on chromosome 16q24.1. Moreover, it has exact synonyms: LPHDST and lymphedema with distichiasis.

Marshall syndrome is a type of ectodermal dysplasia with a definition as an ectodermal dysplasia characterized by the underdevelopment (hypoplasia) of the maxilla, nasal bones, and frontal sinuses, as well as thickening of the calvaria, myopia, early-onset cataracts, and sensorineural hearing loss. This condition has its material basis in either heterozygous or homozygous mutations, most frequently affecting splice sites, in the COL11A1 gene located on chromosome 1p21.1. Such mutations, which are typically null, in the COL11A1 gene may also lead to Stickler syndrome. Additionally, Marshall syndrome is exactly synonymous with MRSHS and also known as deafness, myopia, cataract, saddle nose-Marshall type.

Melanoma and neural system tumor syndrome, also precisely known as melanoma-astrocytoma syndrome, is a type of autosomal dominant disease and syndrome. This condition is characterized by a predisposition to cutaneous melanoma and neural tumor (typically astrocytomas) development, which has its material basis in heterozygous mutation in the CDKN2A gene on chromosome 9p21.3. Additionally, this syndrome can be classified as something that at least has a material basis in some form of autosomal dominant inheritance.

Metachondromatosis is a type of autosomal dominant disease and osteochondrodysplasia that has its material basis in autosomal dominant inheritance. It is characterized as an osteochondrodysplasia by the presence of both multiple enchondromas and exostoses, resulting from a heterozygous mutation in the PTPN11 gene on chromosome 12q24.13. Additionally, metachondromatosis is exactly synonymous with METCDS.

Metaphyseal dysplasia maxillary hypoplasia brachydactyly syndrome is a type of autosomal dominant disease and osteochondrodysplasia. It is considered a condition that at least has a material basis in some form of autosomal dominant inheritance. This syndrome is characterized by an osteochondrodysplasia that features metaphyseal flaring of long bones, enlargement of the medial halves of the clavicles, maxillary hypoplasia, variable brachydactyly, and dystrophic teeth. The condition's material basis is linked to a heterozygous duplication of the RUNX2 gene on chromosome 6p21.1. Furthermore, metaphyseal dysplasia maxillary hypoplasia brachydactyly syndrome has exact synonyms, including metaphyseal dysplasia maxillary hypoplasia brachydactyly and metaphyseal dysplasia with maxillary hypoplasia with or without brachydactyly.

Metatropic dysplasia, which is also exactly synonymous with metatropic dwarfism, is a type of autosomal dominant disease, spondyloepimetaphyseal dysplasia, and a condition that at least has a material basis in some form of autosomal dominant inheritance. It is defined as a spondyloepimetaphyseal dysplasia characterized by short limbs with limitation and enlargement of joints, usually severe and progressive kyphoscoliosis, severe platyspondyly, and severe metaphyseal enlargement, all of which have a material basis in a heterozygous mutation in the TRPV4 gene on chromosome 12q24.11.

Autosomal recessive progressive external ophthalmoplegia with mitochondrial DNA deletions 2 (PEOB2) is a type of autosomal recessive disease and chronic progressive external ophthalmoplegia. It is characterized by having a material basis in autosomal recessive inheritance and exhibits symptoms such as muscle weakness and features like dementia. Specifically, it is a chronic progressive external ophthalmoplegia distinguished by the adult onset of progressive external ophthalmoplegia, exercise intolerance, muscle weakness, and signs and symptoms of spinocerebellar ataxia. This condition is caused by homozygous or compound heterozygous mutations in the RNASEH1 gene on chromosome 2p25.3. PEOB2 is also exactly synonymous with adult-onset CPEO with mitochondrial myopathy, adult-onset chronic progressive external ophthalmoplegia with mitochondrial myopathy, and autosomal recessive progressive external ophthalmoplegia 2.

Autosomal recessive progressive external ophthalmoplegia with mitochondrial DNA deletions 4, also known exactly as PEOB4, adult-onset multiple mitochondrial DNA deletion syndrome due to DGUOK deficiency, adult-onset multiple mtDNA deletion syndrome due to DGUOK deficiency, and autosomal recessive progressive external ophthalmoplegia 4, is a type of autosomal recessive disease, chronic progressive external ophthalmoplegia, and conditions that have a material basis in autosomal recessive inheritance and exhibit symptoms such as muscle weakness. This condition is characterized by adult onset of eye muscle weakness and proximal limb muscle weakness that results from homozygous or compound heterozygous mutation in the DGUOK gene on chromosome 2p13.1.

Autosomal dominant progressive external ophthalmoplegia with mitochondrial DNA deletions 2, also exactly known as PEOA2 and autosomal dominant progressive external ophthalmoplegia 2, is a type of disease that falls into several categories. It is an autosomal dominant disease, a type of chronic progressive external ophthalmoplegia, and belongs to the category of diseases that have a material basis in autosomal dominant inheritance. This specific condition is defined as a chronic progressive external ophthalmoplegia characterized by a heterozygous mutation in the SLC25A4 gene on chromosome 4q35.1.

Autosomal Dominant Progressive External Ophthalmoplegia with Mitochondrial DNA Deletions 5 (ADPEO5) is a type of autosomal dominant disease, chronic progressive external ophthalmoplegia, and a condition that inherently has a material basis in autosomal dominant inheritance. It is defined as a chronic progressive external ophthalmoplegia that results from a heterozygous mutation in the RRM2B gene located on chromosome 8q22.3. Furthermore, ADPEO5 is precisely synonymous with PEOA5 and Autosomal Dominant Progressive External Ophthalmoplegia 5.

Autosomal dominant progressive external ophthalmoplegia with mitochondrial DNA deletions 6 is a type of disease that falls under several categories: it is a type of autosomal dominant disease, chronic progressive external ophthalmoplegia, and is characterized by having a material basis in autosomal dominant inheritance and symptoms including muscle weakness. Specifically, it is defined as a chronic progressive external ophthalmoplegia characterized by muscle weakness, mainly affecting the lower limbs, external ophthalmoplegia, exercise intolerance, and mitochondrial DNA (mtDNA) deletions, resulting from a heterozygous mutation in the DNA2 gene on chromosome 10q21.3. This condition is also known by several exact synonyms: DNA2-related mitochondrial DNA deletion syndrome, PEOA6, autosomal dominant progressive external ophthalmoplegia 6, mitochondrial DNA deletion syndrome with limb-girdle weakness, mitochondrial DNA deletion syndrome with progressive myopathy, mtDNA deletion syndrome with limb-girdle weakness, and mtDNA deletion syndrome with progressive myopathy.

Autosomal dominant progressive external ophthalmoplegia with mitochondrial DNA deletions 3, also known as PEOA3 or autosomal dominant progressive external ophthalmoplegia 3, is categorized as a type of autosomal dominant disease, chronic progressive external ophthalmoplegia, and a condition that fundamentally arises from autosomal dominant inheritance. It is specifically defined as a chronic progressive external ophthalmoplegia that develops due to a heterozygous mutation in the TWNK gene located on chromosome 10q24.31.

Autosomal dominant progressive external ophthalmoplegia 1 (PEOA1) is a type of autosomal dominant disease, chronic progressive external ophthalmoplegia, and something that at least has a material basis in some autosomal dominant inheritance. It is defined as a chronic progressive external ophthalmoplegia that has its material basis in a heterozygous mutation in the POLG gene on chromosome 15q26.1.

Autosomal recessive progressive external ophthalmoplegia 1 is a type of autosomal recessive disease, chronic progressive external ophthalmoplegia, and something that at least has a material basis in some autosomal recessive inheritance. It is defined as a chronic progressive external ophthalmoplegia that has a material basis in homozygous or compound heterozygous mutation in the POLG gene on chromosome 15q26.1. Additionally, autosomal recessive progressive external ophthalmoplegia 1 has the exact synonym PEOB1.

Autosomal recessive progressive external ophthalmoplegia with mitochondrial DNA deletions 3, also known precisely as PEOB3 or autosomal recessive progressive external ophthalmoplegia 3, is classified as a type of autosomal recessive disease, chronic progressive external ophthalmoplegia, and something that inherently has its material basis in autosomal recessive inheritance. This condition is defined as a chronic progressive external ophthalmoplegia that originates from homozygous or compound heterozygous mutation in the TK2 gene located on chromosome 16q21.

Autosomal recessive progressive external ophthalmoplegia with mitochondrial DNA deletions 5 (PEOB5), also known as autosomal recessive progressive external ophthalmoplegia 5, is classified as a type of autosomal recessive disease, chronic progressive external ophthalmoplegia, and a condition that fundamentally has a material basis in autosomal recessive inheritance. It is defined as a chronic progressive external ophthalmoplegia characterized by a material basis in homozygous or compound heterozygous mutation in the TOP3A gene on chromosome 17p11.2.

Autosomal dominant progressive external ophthalmoplegia with mitochondrial DNA deletions 4, also known exactly as PEOA4 and autosomal dominant progressive external ophthalmoplegia 4, is a type of autosomal dominant disease, chronic progressive external ophthalmoplegia, and something that at least has a material basis in autosomal dominant inheritance. It is defined as a chronic progressive external ophthalmoplegia that has a material basis in a heterozygous mutation in the POLG2 gene on chromosome 17q23.3.

Mullerian aplasia and hyperandrogenism is a type of autosomal dominant disease, a disorder of sexual development, and something that at least has a material basis in some autosomal dominant inheritance. It is defined as a disorder of sexual development characterized by primary amenorrhea, an underdeveloped or absent uterus, and clinical hyperandrogenism that has a material basis in heterozygous mutation in the WNT4 gene on chromosome 1p36.12. Additionally, Mullerian aplasia and hyperandrogenism has exact synonyms: Mullerian duct failure and hyperandrogenism, and WNT4 deficiency.

Spinal muscular atrophy with progressive myoclonic epilepsy (SMA-PME) is a type of autosomal recessive disease, which is also a form of spinal muscular atrophy. It is characterized as a condition that, at the very least, has a material basis in some form of autosomal recessive inheritance. Specifically, it is a motor neuron disease marked by severe and progressive myoclonic epilepsy and lower-motor-neuron disease, with its material basis being homozygous or compound heterozygous mutations in the ASAH1 gene on chromosome 8p22. SMA-PME is also known by several exact synonyms, including Jankovic-Rivera syndrome, SMA-PME, SMAPME, and hereditary myoclonus-progressive distal muscular atrophy syndrome.

Naegeli-Franceschetti-Jadassohn syndrome is a type of autosomal dominant disease, ectodermal dysplasia, and something that at least has a material basis in some autosomal dominant inheritance. It is characterized by reticulate hyperpigmentation that may fade with age, palmoplantar keratoderma, the absence of dermatoglyphics, abnormal sweat function, and dental anomalies. These characteristics have a material basis in a heterozygous mutation in the KRT14 gene on chromosome 17q21.2. Additionally, Naegeli-Franceschetti-Jadassohn syndrome has exact synonyms, including NFJ syndrome and Naegeli syndrome.

Familial multiple nevi flammei is a type of capillary disease characterized by dark red to purple, nonelevated, sharply circumscribed patches which blanch on pressure with a glass, do not spontaneously regress, and have normal rates of endothelial cell turnover. It is also exactly synonymous with CMC, congenital capillary malformations, and familial multiple port-wine stains.

@prefix rdfs: <http://www.w3.org/2000/01/rdf-schema#> .

:linear_nevus_sebaceous_syndrome rdfs:subClassOf :syndrome ;
    :has_definition "A syndrome characterized by sebaceous nevi typically on the face and associated with variable ipsilateral abnormalities of the central nervous system, ocular anomalies, and skeletal defects that has_material_basis_in somatic mosaic mutations in the NRAS, HRAS, or KRAS genes on chromosomes 1p13.2, 11p15.5, or 12p12.1, respectively." ;
    :has_exact_synonym "JNP"@en,
        "Jadassohn nevus phakomatosis"@en,
        "SFM syndrome"@en,
        "Schimmelpenning Feuerstein Mims syndrome"@en,
        "Schimmelpenning syndrome"@en,
        "Solomon syndrome"@en,
        "nevus sebaceus of Jadassohn"@en,
        "nevus sebaceus syndrome"@en,
        "organoid nevus phakomatosis"@en,
        "organoid nevus syndrome"@en .
text: Linear Nevus Sebaceous Syndrome is a type of syndrome characterized by sebaceous nevi typically on the face and associated with variable ipsilateral abnormalities of the central nervous system, ocular anomalies, and skeletal defects. This syndrome's material basis lies in somatic mosaic mutations in the NRAS, HRAS, or KRAS genes on chromosomes 1p13.2, 11p15.5, or 12p12.1, respectively. It is also known by several exact synonyms: JNP, Jadassohn Nevus Phakomatosis, SFM syndrome, Schimmelpenning Feuerstein Mims syndrome, Schimmelpenning syndrome, Solomon syndrome, Nevus Sebaceus of Jadassohn, Nevus Sebaceus Syndrome, Organoid Nevus Phakomatosis, and Organoid Nevus Syndrome.

Bilateral optic nerve hypoplasia (ONH), also known exactly as familial bilateral optic nerve hypoplasia and isolated optic nerve hypoplasia/aplasia, is a type of autosomal dominant disease as well as a specific optic nerve disease. Furthermore, it is characterized by a condition that necessarily has a material basis in some form of autosomal dominant inheritance. Specifically, this optic nerve disease is defined by isolated optic nerve hypoplasia or aplasia, which has a material basis in a heterozygous mutation in the PAX6 gene located on chromosome 11p13.

Osteoglophonic dysplasia is an autosomal dominant disease that falls under the category of osteochondrodysplasia. It is characterized by a specific type of inheritance that has a material basis in autosomal dominant inheritance. The disease is defined as an osteochondrodysplasia characterized by features such as rhizomelic dwarfism, craniosynostosis, a prominent supraorbital ridge, a depressed nasal bridge, nonossifying bone lesions, and multiple unerupted teeth. These characteristics are due to a heterozygous missense mutation in the FGFR1 gene located on chromosome 8p11.23. Additionally, osteoglophonic dysplasia is also known by exact synonyms including Fairbank-Keats syndrome, OGD, and osteoglophonic dwarfism.

Gnathodiaphyseal dysplasia is a type of autosomal dominant disease and also falls under the category of osteochondrodysplasia. It is characterized by conditions that have a material basis in autosomal dominant inheritance. Specifically, it is an osteochondrodysplasia characterized by cementoosseous lesions of the jawbones, bone fragility, bowing/cortical thickening of tubular bones, and diaphyseal sclerosis of long bones, which is due to heterozygous mutation in the ANO5 gene on chromosome 11p14.3. This condition is exactly synonymous with several other names, including GDD, Levin syndrome 2, gnathodiaphyseal sclerosis, osteogenesis imperfecta with unusual skeletal lesions, and osteogenesis imperfecta, Levin type.

Multicentric carpotarsal osteolysis syndrome is a type of autosomal dominant disease and syndrome, which is characterized by a progressive loss of bone, typically involving the carpal and tarsal bones, and in many cases, chronic renal failure. This condition has a material basis in heterozygous mutation in the MAFB gene on chromosome 20q12. It is also known by several exact synonyms, including MCTO, autosomal dominant multicentric osteolysis, hereditary osteolysis of carpal bones with or without nephropathy, idiopathic multicentric osteolysis with or without nephropathy, multicentric carpo-tarsal osteolysis with or without nephropathy, and multicentric osteolysis nephropathy.

Progressive osseous heteroplasia is a type of autosomal dominant disease, syndrome, and something that at least has a material basis in some autosomal dominant inheritance. It is defined as a syndrome characterized by the infantile onset of dermal ossification followed by progressive bone formation in skeletal muscle and deep fascia. This condition has a material basis in the heterozygous loss of function mutation in the Gs-alpha isoform of the GNAS gene on chromosome 20q13.32. Progressive osseous heteroplasia is exactly synonymous with POH, ectopic ossification familial type, familial ectopic ossification, and osteoma cutis.

Buschke Ollendorff Syndrome (BOS), also known by its exact synonyms dermatofibrosis lenticularis disseminata with osteopoikilosis, dermatoosteopoikilosis, disseminated dermatofibrosis with osteopoikilosis, and osteopathia condensans disseminata, is a type of syndrome that is classified as an autosomal dominant disease. It is a condition that fundamentally has a material basis in autosomal dominant inheritance. BOS is characterized by multiple subcutaneous nevi or nodules and osteopoikilosis, which is due to a heterozygous mutation in the LEMD3 gene located on chromosome 12q14.3.

Paroxysmal Extreme Pain Disorder (PEPD), also known exactly as PEXPD, familial rectal pain, and submandibular, ocular, and rectal pain with flushing, is a type of disease that falls under several categories: it is an autosomal dominant disease, an autonomic nervous system disease, and is characterized by its material basis in some autosomal dominant inheritance. Specifically, PEPD is defined as an autonomic nervous system disease that begins in the neonatal period or infancy, featuring paroxysms of rectal, ocular, or submandibular pain accompanied by flushing. This condition is caused by a heterozygous mutation in the SCN9A gene located on chromosome 2q24.3.

Paramyotonia congenita of von Eulenburg is classified as a type of autosomal dominant and neuromuscular disease. It is characterized by having a material basis in autosomal dominant inheritance and presenting symptoms such as muscle weakness. The condition is specifically defined as a neuromuscular disease that manifests in infancy or early childhood with episodes of myotonia and muscle weakness, which worsen with exposure to cold. This condition is caused by a heterozygous mutation in the SCN4A gene located on chromosome 17q23.3. Paramyotonia congenita of von Eulenburg is also known by several exact synonyms, including Eulenburg disease, PMC, Von Eulenburg paramyotonia congenita, myotonia congenita intermittens, paralysis periodica paramyotonica, and simply paramyotonia congenita.

Parastremmatic dwarfism is a type of autosomal dominant disease, osteochondrodysplasia, and is something that at least has a material basis in some autosomal dominant inheritance. It is characterized by severe dwarfism, kyphoscoliosis, stiffness of large joints, and bowing and twisting of lower limbs due to a heterozygous mutation in the TRPV4 gene on chromosome 12q24.11. Additionally, parastremmatic dwarfism is exactly synonymous with parastremmatic dysplasia.

Prolidase deficiency is a type of autosomal recessive disease and an amino acid metabolic disorder that has a material basis in autosomal recessive inheritance. This condition is characterized by massive imidodipeptiduria, chronic and slowly healing ulcerations, recurrent infections, dysmorphic facial features, variable cognitive impairment, splenomegaly, and either a lack of or reduced prolidase activity. This is due to homozygous or compound heterozygous mutations in the PEPD gene located on chromosome 19q13.11. Moreover, prolidase deficiency is also exactly synonymous with hyperimidodipeptiduria, imidodipeptidase deficiency, and peptidase deficiency.

Pigmented paravenous chorioretinal atrophy (PPRCA) is a type of eye disease that is also an autosomal dominant disease. This condition specifically has a material basis in some autosomal dominant inheritance and is characterized by the presence of bone corpuscle pigmentation in a paravenous distribution in the ocular fundus. The underlying cause of pigmented paravenous chorioretinal atrophy is a heterozygous mutation in the CRB1 gene located on chromosome 1q31.3.

Familial expansile osteolysis is a type of autosomal dominant disease, bone remodeling disease, and something that at least has a material basis in some autosomal dominant inheritance. It is characterized by increased bone remodeling with osteolytic lesions mainly affecting the appendicular skeleton, bone pain, pathological fractures, childhood onset of conductive hearing loss, and premature tooth loss, resulting from a heterozygous mutation in the TNFRSF11A gene on chromosome 18q21.33. Furthermore, familial expansile osteolysis is also known by its exact synonyms: FEO, McCabe disease, and hereditary expansile polyostotic osteolytic dysplasia.

Juvenile Polyposis Hereditary Hemorrhagic Telangiectasia Syndrome (JP-HHT) is a type of syndrome classified as an autosomal dominant disease. It is characterized by features that include hamartomatous polyps in the gastrointestinal tract, telangiectases of the skin, and oral and nasal mucosa, epistaxis, and arteriovenous malformations of the lungs, liver, brain, and gastrointestinal tract. The material basis for this syndrome is at least in part due to autosomal dominant inheritance, and its existence typically begins during young adult onset. This syndrome is specifically linked to a heterozygous mutation in the SMAD4 gene located on chromosome 18q21.2.

Guttmacher Syndrome is a type of syndrome and an autosomal dominant disease, which is characterized by a specific set of features. These features include preaxial deficiencies of the hands and feet, postaxial polydactyly of the hands, and hypospadias. This condition has a material basis in a heterozygous mutation in the HOXA13 gene located on chromosome 7p15.2. Furthermore, Guttmacher Syndrome is exactly synonymous with autosomal dominant preaxial deficiency, postaxial polydactyly, and hypospadias, as well as with preaxial deficiency-postaxial polydactyly-hypospadias syndrome.

Familial Male Limited Precocious Puberty (FMPP), also known as familial gonadotropin-independent male-limited sexual precocity, male-limited precocious puberty, and testotoxicosis, is a type of disease that falls under three categories: an autosomal dominant disease, an endocrine system disease, and a condition that has at least a material basis in some form of autosomal dominant inheritance. It is characterized by an onset in early childhood of accelerated growth, early development of secondary sexual characteristics, and reduced adult height in males only, which has its material basis in a heterozygous mutation in the LHCGR gene on chromosome 2p16.3.

Currarino syndrome is a type of syndrome and an autosomal dominant disease, which specifically has a material basis in autosomal dominant inheritance. It is defined as a syndrome characterized by anorectal malformations, a presacral mass, and partial sacral agenesis with an intact first sacral vertebra, resulting from a heterozygous mutation in HLXB9 on chromosome 7q36.3. Additionally, Currarino syndrome is exactly synonymous with Currarino triad.

Retinal arterial tortuosity is a type of autosomal dominant and artery disease, which at least has a material basis in some autosomal dominant inheritance. It is defined as an artery disease characterized by pronounced tortuosity of second- and third-order retinal arteries with normal first-order arteries and venous system, and this condition has a material basis in a heterozygous mutation in the COL4A1 gene on chromosome 13q34. Retinal arterial tortuosity is also exactly synonymous with RATOR, retinal arteriolar tortuosity, retinal hemorrhage with vascular tortuosity, and tortuosity of retinal arteries.

Ring dermoid of cornea (RDC), also known as ring dermoid syndrome, is a type of corneal disease and an autosomal dominant disease. It specifically falls under the category of diseases that have a material basis in some form of autosomal dominant inheritance. The definition of ring dermoid of cornea is a corneal disease characterized by annular limbal dermoids with corneal and conjunctival extension that is caused by a heterozygous mutation in the PITX2 gene on chromosome 4q25.

Aplasia of lacrimal and salivary glands is a condition categorized as an autosomal dominant disease, a syndrome, and is described as having a material basis in some form of autosomal dominant inheritance. It is defined as a syndrome characterized by irritable eyes, epiphora, xerostomia, and variable aplasia or hypoplasia of the lacrimal, parotid, submandibular, and sublingual glands, including the absence of the lacrimal puncta, which is caused by a heterozygous mutation in the FGF10 gene on chromosome 5p12. This condition is also known by its exact synonyms: ALSG and congenital absence of lacrimal puncta and salivary glands.

Scalp ear nipple syndrome, also known exactly as Finlay-Marks syndrome, SENS, Sen Syndrome, and hereditary syndrome of lumpy scalp, odd ears and rudimentary nipples, is a type of autosomal dominant disease, ectodermal dysplasia, and something that at least has a material basis in autosomal dominant inheritance. It is defined as an ectodermal dysplasia characterized by cutis aplasia of the scalp, breast anomalies that range from hypothelia or athelia to amastia, and minor anomalies of the external ears. This syndrome has its material basis in a heterozygous mutation in the KCTD1 gene on chromosome 18q11.2.

Neurogenic scapuloperoneal syndrome Kaeser type is a type of autosomal dominant disease and a type of myopathy. It is characterized by a material basis in autosomal dominant inheritance and presents symptoms such as muscle weakness. This condition is defined as a myopathy characterized by adult onset of foot dorsiflexor weakness, peroneal muscle weakness, scapuloperoneal weakness, and shoulder girdle muscle atrophy, resulting from a heterozygous mutation in the DES gene on chromosome 2q35. Neurogenic scapuloperoneal syndrome Kaeser type is also known by its exact synonyms: Kaeser syndrome, Stark-Kaeser syndrome, scapuloperoneal syndrome type Kaeser, and scapuloperoneal syndrome, neurogenic, Kaeser type.

Scapuloperoneal spinal muscular atrophy (SPSMA) is a type of autosomal dominant disease and motor neuron disease, which has a material basis in some autosomal dominant inheritance and exhibits symptoms such as muscle weakness. It is characterized by progressive scapuloperoneal atrophy and weakness, laryngeal palsy, congenital absence of muscles, and in some cases, developmental abnormalities of the bones. This condition is caused by heterozygous mutation in the TRPV4 gene on chromosome 12q24.11. Scapuloperoneal spinal muscular atrophy is also known by its exact synonyms: neurogenic scapuloperoneal amyotrophy, New England type, and scapuloperoneal neuronopathy.

Spondyloepiphyseal dysplasia Maroteaux type is classified as a type of spondyloepiphyseal dysplasia and is also known as an autosomal dominant disease. Additionally, it is identified as a condition that inherently has a material basis in some form of autosomal dominant inheritance. This disease is defined as an osteochondrodysplasia characterized by dysplastic epiphyses, short stature that becomes apparent in infancy, a short neck, short and stubby hands and feet, platyspondyly, severe brachydactyly, and pelvic abnormalities, all of which are due to a heterozygous mutation in the TRPV4 gene on chromosome 12q24.11. Furthermore, Spondyloepiphyseal dysplasia Maroteaux type is exactly synonymous with Brachyolmia Type 2, Pseudo-Morquio Syndrome Type 2, SED Maroteaux type, and spondyloepiphyseal dysplasia of Maroteaux, indicating the variety of names by which this disease is recognized.

Spondylometaphyseal dysplasia Kozlowski type is a form of spondylometaphyseal dysplasia and an autosomal dominant disease, which essentially has a material basis in some form of autosomal dominant inheritance. It is characterized by vertebral platyspondyly, overfaced pedicles, scoliosis, and mild metaphyseal abnormalities in the pelvis, resulting from a heterozygous mutation in the TRPV4 gene on chromosome 12q24.11. This condition is also known by several exact synonyms, including Jequier Kozlowski skeletal dysplasia, Jequier-Kozlowski syndrome, SMD Kozlowski type, dysmorphism arthrogryposis skeletal maturation advanced, and skeletal dysplasia Jequier-Kozlowski type.

Alkuraya Kucinskas syndrome is a type of syndrome that is also an autosomal recessive disease and has a material basis in autosomal recessive inheritance. It is defined as a syndrome characterized by arthrogryposis, cerebral parenchymal underdevelopment, clubfoot, and global developmental delay, with severe cases being incompatible with life. This condition has its material basis in homozygous or compound heterozygous mutations in the KIAA1109 gene on chromosome 4q27. Additionally, Alkuraya Kucinskas syndrome has the exact synonym ALKKUCS.

Steatocystoma multiplex is a type of disease that is autosomal dominant, relates to sebaceous gland conditions, and has a material basis in autosomal dominant inheritance. It is defined as a sebaceous gland disease characterized by the presence of multiple benign sebaceous cysts, which results from a heterozygous mutation in the KRT17 gene on chromosome 17q21.2. Additionally, steatocystoma multiplex is exactly synonymous with multiple sebaceous cysts and sebocystomatosis.

Charcot Marie Tooth disease type 2A2B is a subtype of Charcot Marie Tooth disease type 2 and is classified as an autosomal recessive disease. This particular type of disease is rooted in autosomal recessive inheritance that specifically involves a material basis. Charcot Marie Tooth disease type 2A2B is characterized by the onset of peripheral neuropathy within the first years of life, which results from homozygous or compound heterozygous mutation in the MFN2 gene located on chromosome 1p36.22. It is known by several exact synonyms including AR-CMT2, Ouvrier type; CMT2A2B; Charcot-Marie-Tooth disease, axonal, type 2A2B; SEOAN due to MFN2 deficiency; autosomal recessive Charcot-Marie-Tooth disease, Ouvrier type; and severe early-onset axonal neuropathy due to MFN2 deficiency.

Charcot Marie Tooth disease type 2DD is a subtype of Charcot Marie Tooth disease type 2 and also falls under the category of autosomal dominant diseases. This specific condition is characterized by a neuropathy that predominantly affects the lower limbs, which is due to a heterozygous mutation in the ATP1A1 gene located on chromosome 1p13.1. It is synonymous with several terms, including ATP1A1-related CMT2, ATP1A1-related autosomal dominant Charcot-Marie-Tooth disease type 2, CMT2DD, Charcot-Marie-Tooth disease, axonal, type 2DD, and Charcot-Marie-Tooth neuropathy, type 2DD.

Charcot Marie Tooth disease type 2EE is a subtype of Charcot Marie Tooth disease type 2 and falls under the broader category of autosomal recessive diseases. It is characterized by a specific type of inheritance, which is at least partially based on autosomal recessive genetics. This disease is defined as a Charcot-Marie-Tooth disease type 2 that is marked by a slowly progressive axonal neuropathy primarily affecting the lower limbs, with the onset occurring in the first or second decades of life. This condition is caused by homozygous or compound heterozygous mutations in the MPV17 gene located on chromosome 2p23.3. Charcot Marie Tooth disease type 2EE is also known by its exact synonyms, CMT2EE and Charcot-Marie-Tooth disease, axonal, type 2EE.

Charcot Marie Tooth disease type 1G is a subtype of Charcot Marie Tooth disease type 1 and an autosomal dominant disease characterized by specific traits. These traits include a material basis in autosomal dominant inheritance and symptoms such as muscle weakness. Specifically, Charcot Marie Tooth disease type 1G is defined as a Charcot-Marie-Tooth disease type 1 characterized by distal muscle weakness and atrophy, which begins in the first or second decade of life. This condition has a material basis in a heterozygous mutation in the PMP2 gene on chromosome 8q21.13. Moreover, Charcot Marie Tooth disease type 1G is also known by several exact synonyms: CMT1G, PMP2-related CMT1, PMP2-related Charcot-Marie-Tooth disease type 1, PMP2-related Charcot-Marie-Tooth neuropathy type 1, and PMP2-related hereditary motor and sensory neuropathy type 1.

Stiff skin syndrome (SSKS) is a type of skin disease that falls under the category of autosomal dominant diseases and is specifically characterized by autosomal dominant inheritance. It is defined as a skin disease marked by hard, thick skin that typically covers the entire body, which limits joint mobility and leads to flexion contractures. This condition is caused by a heterozygous mutation in the FBN1 gene located on chromosome 15q21.1.

Overhydrated hereditary stomatocytosis (OHS), also known as potassium sodium disorder of erythrocyte or stomatocytosisIOHST, is a type of autosomal dominant disease, macrocytic anemia, and is characterized by a condition that inherently has a material basis in some form of autosomal dominant inheritance. It is defined as a macrocytic anemia characterized by macrocytic hemolytic anemia and a monovalent cation leak from red blood cells, attributing this condition to a heterozygous mutation in the RHAG gene located on chromosome 6p12.3.
