@prefix rdfs: <http://www.w3.org/2000/01/rdf-schema#> .

:sturge_weber_syndrome rdfs:subClassOf :vascular_disease ;
    :has_definition "A vascular disease characterized by intracranial vascular anomaly, leptomeningeal angiomatosis, facial cutaneous vascular malformations, and glaucoma that has_material_basis_in somatic mutation in the GNAQ gene on chromosome 9q21.2." ;
    :has_exact_synonym "SWS"@en,
        "Sturge-Weber-Dimitri syndrome"@en,
        "Sturge-Weber-Krabbe angiomatosis"@en,
        "Sturge-Weber-Krabbe syndrome"@en,
        "encephalofacial angiomatosis"@en,
        "encephalotrigeminal angiomatosis"@en,
        "fourth phacomatosis"@en,
        "leptomeningeal angiomatosis"@en,
        "meningeal capillary angiomatosis"@en .
text: Sturge-Weber syndrome is a type of vascular disease characterized by an intracranial vascular anomaly, leptomeningeal angiomatosis, facial cutaneous vascular malformations, and glaucoma. This condition has a material basis in a somatic mutation in the GNAQ gene located on chromosome 9q21.2. It is exactly synonymous with several terms, including SWS, Sturge-Weber-Dimitri syndrome, Sturge-Weber-Krabbe angiomatosis, Sturge-Weber-Krabbe syndrome, encephalofacial angiomatosis, encephalotrigeminal angiomatosis, fourth phacomatosis, leptomeningeal angiomatosis, and meningeal capillary angiomatosis.

Hypoplastic or aplastic tibia with polydactyly, also known as Werner mesomelic syndrome, absence of tibia with polydactyly, absent tibia-polydactyly syndrome, hypoplastic tibiae-postaxial polydactyly syndrome, and tibial hemimelia-polysyndactyly-triphalangeal thumb syndrome, is identified as a type of autosomal dominant disease, syndrome, and something that fundamentally has a material basis in autosomal dominant inheritance. This condition is defined as a syndrome characterized by preaxial polydactyly of the hands and feet and hypoplasia or aplasia of the tibia, which is caused by a heterozygous mutation in the SHH regulatory region (ZRS) located in intron 5 of the LMBR1 gene on chromosome 7q36.3.

Trichodontoosseous syndrome, also known exactly as TDO syndrome or tricho-dento-osseous syndrome, is a type of autosomal dominant disease and a syndrome that has its material basis in autosomal dominant inheritance. It is defined as a syndrome characterized by curly kinky hair at birth, enamel hypoplasia, taurodontism, thickening of cortical bones, and variable expression of craniofacial morphology, which is caused by a heterozygous mutation in the DLX3 gene on chromosome 17q21.33.

Familial isolated trichomegaly, which has the exact synonyms TCMGLY and long eyelashes, is a type of disease that falls under the categories of autosomal recessive disease, eyelid disease, and anything that at least has a material basis in some form of autosomal recessive inheritance. It is defined as an eyelid disease characterized by a prolonged anagen phase of the eyelash hairs, resulting in extremely long eyelashes. This condition has its material basis in homozygous or compound heterozygous mutations in the FGF5 gene on chromosome 4q21.21.

Retinal vasculopathy with cerebral leukodystrophy (RVCL) is a type of disease that is both autosomal dominant and vascular in nature. It can also be described as something that at least has a material basis in autosomal dominant inheritance. RVCL is defined as a vascular disease characterized by adult onset of microvascular endotheliopathy leading to central nervous system degeneration with progressive loss of vision, stroke, motor impairment, and cognitive decline. This condition has its material basis in a heterozygous mutation in the TREX1 gene located on chromosome 3p21.31. RVCL is known by several exact synonyms including CRV, RVCL-S, hereditary cerebroretinal vasculopathy, retinal vasculopathy and cerebral leukoencephalopathy, retinal vasculopathy with cerebral leukoencephalopathy and systemic manifestations, and retinopathy, vascular, with cerebral and renal involvement and Raynaud and migraine phenomena.

Congenital vertical talus is a type of autosomal dominant disease, a physical disorder, and a connective tissue disease. It is characterized by a condition that fundamentally has a material basis in autosomal dominant inheritance and involves abnormalities of prenatal development or birth. Specifically, this disease is defined by the dislocation of the talonavicular joint with a vertical orientation of the talus and rigid dorsal dislocation of the navicular, equinus deformity of the calcaneus, abduction deformity of the forefoot, and contracture of the soft tissues of the hind- and mid-foot. This condition is caused by a heterozygous mutation in the HOXD10 gene on chromosome 2q31.1. Congenital vertical talus is also known by several exact synonyms, including CVT, congenital convex foot, congenital convex pes valgus, congenital rocker-bottom foot, and rocker-bottom foot deformity.

Autosomal dominant vitreoretinochoroidopathy (ADVIRC) is a type of autosomal dominant disease and also falls under the category of hereditary retinal dystrophy. It is characterized as a condition that inherently has a material basis in autosomal dominant inheritance. Specifically, ADVIRC is defined as a hereditary retinal dystrophy that features abnormal chorioretinal hypopigmentation and hyperpigmentation typically situated between the vortex veins and the ora serrata for 360 degrees, along with other ocular developmental anomalies. These anomalies have their material basis in a heterozygous mutation in the BEST1 gene on chromosome 11q12.3. The condition is known by several exact synonyms, including VRCP autosomal dominant, vitreoretinochoroidopathy dominant, vitreoretinochoroidopathy with microcornea, glaucoma, and cataract, as well as vitreoretinochoroidopathy, autosomal dominant, with nanophthalmos.

Snowflake vitreoretinal degeneration is a type of autosomal dominant disease, eye degenerative disease, and something that at least has a material basis in some autosomal dominant inheritance. It is characterized by fibrillar degeneration of the vitreous humor, early-onset cataract, minute crystalline deposits in the neurosensory retina, and retinal detachment, which has a material basis in a heterozygous mutation in KCNJ13 on chromosome 2q37.1. Furthermore, snowflake vitreoretinal degeneration has exact synonyms SVD and vitreoretinal degeneration, snowflake type.

Weyers acrofacial dysostosis is an autosomal dominant disease and a type of acrofacial dysostosis that stems from autosomal dominant inheritance. Specifically, it is characterized by dental anomalies, nail dystrophy, postaxial polydactyly, and mild short stature, resulting from heterozygous mutations in the EVC2 or EVC genes located on chromosome 4p16.2. This condition is also known by several exact synonyms: Curry-Hall syndrome, WAD, Weyers acrodental dysostosis, and acrofacial dysostosis, Weyers type.

Familial woolly hair syndrome is a type of hair disease characterized by fine and tightly curled hair that grows slowly and stops growing after a few inches, with hair shafts that display trichorrhexis nodosa and tapered ends. It is also known by exact synonyms including familial wooly hair syndrome, hereditary woolly hair syndrome, hereditary wooly hair syndrome, woolly hair, and wooly hair.

Autosomal dominant woolly hair is a type of autosomal dominant disease and a form of familial woolly hair syndrome, which is characterized by at least having a material basis in some autosomal dominant inheritance. It is defined as a familial woolly hair syndrome that has its material basis in a heterozygous mutation in the KRT74 gene located on chromosome 12q13.13. Additionally, autosomal dominant woolly hair is exactly synonymous with ADWH.

Autosomal recessive woolly hair 3 is a type of autosomal recessive disease and is also a type of familial woolly hair syndrome. It is characterized by a condition that has its material basis in autosomal recessive inheritance. Specifically, autosomal recessive woolly hair 3, which has the exact synonym ARWH3, is defined as a familial woolly hair syndrome that originates from homozygous or compound heterozygous mutations in the KRT24 gene located on chromosome 17q21.2.

Dehydrated hereditary stomatocytosis is a type of hemolytic anemia, which is defined as a hemolytic anemia characterized by altered intracellular cation content and cellular dehydration of erythrocytes. This results in increased mean corpuscular hemoglobin concentrations and altered cell shapes. It is also exactly synonymous with hereditary desiccytosis and hereditary xerocytosis.

Dehydrated hereditary stomatocytosis 1 (DHS1) is a type of autosomal dominant disease and also a specific form of dehydrated hereditary stomatocytosis. It is characterized by having a material basis in autosomal dominant inheritance. DHS1 is defined by a heterozygous mutation in the PIEZO1 gene located on chromosome 16q24.3. Furthermore, DHS1 is known by several exact synonyms, including PSHK1, dehydrated hereditary stomatocytosis 1 with or without pseudohyperkalemia and/or perinatal edema, pseudohyperkalemia Edinburgh, and pseudohyperkalemia familial 1, due to red cell leak.

Dehydrated hereditary stomatocytosis 2 is a type of autosomal dominant disease and also a specific form of dehydrated hereditary stomatocytosis, with its nature rooted in autosomal dominant inheritance. It is defined as a dehydrated hereditary stomatocytosis that results from a heterozygous mutation in the KCNN4 gene located on chromosome 19q13.31. Furthermore, this condition is precisely known by the synonyms desiccytosis Gardos and xerocytosis Gardos.

Gillespie syndrome, a type of autosomal genetic disease and syndrome, is fundamentally linked to autosomal inheritance. It is defined as a syndrome marked by iris hypoplasia, congenital hypotonia, cerebellar hypoplasia, variably cognitive impairment, and ataxia, stemming from heterozygous, homozygous, or compound heterozygous mutations in the ITPR1 gene located on chromosome 3p26.1. This condition is also precisely known as GLSP, aniridia, cerebellar ataxia and mental deficiency, and aniridia-cerebellar ataxia-intellectual disability syndrome.

Asthma nasal polyps and aspirin intolerance is a type of respiratory system disease characterized by asthma, aspirin-induced bronchoconstriction, and nasal polyps. This condition is also exactly synonymous with ASA triad.

Behr syndrome is a type of disease that falls under the category of both an autosomal recessive disease and a nervous system disease. It specifically has a material basis in autosomal recessive inheritance. This condition is defined by a nervous system disease characterized by early-onset optic atrophy, ataxia, pyramidal signs, spasticity, and intellectual disability. These symptoms are the result of homozygous or compound heterozygous mutations in the OPA1 gene located on chromosome 3q29. Behr syndrome is known by several exact synonyms, including Abortive cerebellar ataxia (BEHRS), BEHRS, optic atrophy in early childhood associated with ataxia, spasticity, mental retardation, and posterior column sensory loss, and optic atrophy, infantile hereditary, Behr complicated form of.

C syndrome is a type of autosomal dominant disease, syndrome, and something that at least has a material basis in some autosomal dominant inheritance. It is defined as a syndrome characterized by trigonocephaly, psychomotor retardation, hypotonia, variable cardiac defects, redundant skin, and dysmorphic facial features, which has a material basis in a heterozygous mutation in the CD96 gene on chromosome 3q13.1-q13.2. Furthermore, C syndrome has several exact synonyms including OTCS, Opitz C trigonocephaly, Opitz trigonocephaly C syndrome, Opitz trigonocephaly syndrome, and trigonocephaly C syndrome.

Hereditary Arterial and Articular Multiple Calcification Syndrome is a type of syndrome that falls under the category of autosomal recessive diseases. It is characterized by adult onset of calcification of arteries in the lower extremities and of the hand and foot capsule joints, which is due to homozygous or compound heterozygous mutation in the NT5E gene on chromosome 6q14.3. This syndrome is also known by several exact synonyms: CALJA, arterial calcification and distal joint calcification, arterial calcification due to CD73 deficiency, arterial calcification due to deficiency of CD73, and calcification of joints and arteries.

Carboxypeptidase N deficiency is a type of autosomal recessive disease and a type of plasma protein metabolism disease, which also falls under a category that has at least a material basis in autosomal recessive inheritance. This condition is defined as a plasma protein metabolism disease characterized by low levels of carboxypeptidase N in the serum, which may result in episodic angioedema, chronic urticaria, asthma, and/or allergic hypersensitivity. The disease has its material basis in homozygous or compound heterozygous mutations in the CPN1 gene located on chromosome 10q24.2. Additionally, carboxypeptidase N deficiency is exactly synonymous with anaphylotoxin inactivator deficiency and deficiency of carboxypeptidase B.

Dilated cardiomyopathy hypergonadotropic hypogonadism syndrome is a type of syndrome and an autosomal dominant disease that has a material basis in autosomal dominant inheritance. This syndrome is characterized by dilated cardiomyopathy and hypergonadotropic hypogonadism, with its material basis in a heterozygous mutation in the LMNA gene on chromosome 1q22. It is also known by several exact synonyms: Malouf syndrome, Najjar syndrome, cardiogenital syndrome, cardiomyopathy with primary testicular failure, congestive cardiomyopathy with hypergonadotropic hypogonadism, dilated cardiomyopathy with hypergonadotropic hypogonadism, dilated cardiomyopathy with premature ovarian failure, and genital anomaly with cardiomyopathy.

Carnitine acylcarnitine translocase deficiency, also known precisely as CACT deficiency or CACTD, is a type of autosomal recessive disease and a specific lipid metabolism disorder. This condition is characterized by a material basis in autosomal recessive inheritance and is defined as a lipid metabolism disorder that results in impaired long-chain fatty acid oxidation. This impairment leads to fasting-induced hypoketotic hypoglycemia, hyperammonemia, elevated creatine kinase and transaminases, dicarboxylic aciduria, very low free carnitine, and an abnormal acylcarnitine profile with a marked elevation of long-chain acylcarnitines. The disorder stems from homozygous or compound heterozygous mutation in the SLC25A20 gene located on chromosome 3p21.31.

Martsolf syndrome is a type of syndrome and autosomal recessive disease that at least has a material basis in some autosomal recessive inheritance. It is characterized by intellectual deficit, congenital cataract, and hypogonadotropic hypogonadism, which has its material basis in homozygous or compound heterozygous mutation in the RAB3GAP2 gene on chromosome 1q41. Additionally, Martsolf syndrome has an exact synonym: cataract-intellectual disability-hypogonadism syndrome.

Gordon Holmes syndrome is a type of autosomal recessive disease and an inherited metabolic disorder that has a material basis in autosomal recessive inheritance. It is defined as an inherited metabolic disorder characterized by progressive cognitive decline, dementia, hypogonadotropic hypogonadism, and variable movement disorders resulting from disordered ubiquitination. This condition is caused by homozygous or compound heterozygous mutation in the RNF216 gene on chromosome 7p22.1. Gordon Holmes syndrome is also known by several exact synonyms including CAHH, GDHS, LHRH deficiency and ataxia, cerebellar ataxia-hypogonadism syndrome, and luteinizing hormone-releasing hormone deficiency with ataxia.

Greenberg dysplasia is a type of autosomal recessive disease, inherited metabolic disorder, and something that at least has a material basis in some autosomal recessive inheritance. It is defined as an inherited metabolic disorder characterized by a defect in cholesterol biosynthesis resulting in fetal hydrops, severe shortening of all long bones with a moth-eaten radiographic appearance, platyspondyly, disorganization of chondroosseous calcification, and ectopic ossification centers. This condition has its material basis in homozygous or compound heterozygous mutation in LBR on chromosome 1q42.12. Additionally, Greenberg dysplasia is known by several exact synonyms including GRBGD, Greenberg skeletal dysplasia, HEM dysplasia, Skeletal dysplasia, Greenberg type, autosomal recessive lethal chondrodystrophy with congenital hydrops, hydrops, ectopic calcification, moth-eaten skeletal dysplasia, and hydrops-ectopic calcification-motheaten syndrome.

Coach syndrome is a type of autosomal recessive disease and syndrome, which specifically has a material basis in autosomal recessive inheritance. It is defined as a syndrome characterized by autosomal recessive inheritance of cerebellar vermis hypo/aplasia, oligophrenia, ataxia, ocular coloboma, and hepatic fibrosis, resulting from homozygous or compound heterozygous mutation in one of three genes: TMEM67, CC2D2A, or RPGRIP1L. Moreover, Coach syndrome is also known by several exact synonyms, including Gentile syndrome, JS-H, Joubert syndrome with congenital hepatic fibrosis, Joubert syndrome with hepatic defect, and cerebellar vermis hypo/aplasia, oligophrenia, congenital ataxia, ocular coloboma, and hepatic fibrosis.

Cohen syndrome is a type of autosomal recessive disease and syndrome, specifically rooted in autosomal recessive inheritance. It is characterized by facial dysmorphism, microcephaly, truncal obesity, impaired intellectual development, progressive retinopathy, and intermittent congenital neutropenia, stemming from homozygous or compound heterozygous mutation in the VPS13B gene located on chromosome 8q22.2. Cohen syndrome is also precisely known as COH1, Hypotonia, obesity, and prominent incisors, and Pepper syndrome.

Congenital heart defects, hamartomas of the tongue, and polysyndactyly constitute a syndrome that is an autosomal recessive disease, a physical disorder, and is characterized by having at least a material basis in some autosomal recessive inheritance as well as a basis in some abnormality of prenatal development or birth. This syndrome is defined as a condition characterized by congenital heart defects, hamartomas of the tongue, and polysyndactyly, which has its material basis in homozygous or compound heterozygous mutation in the WDPCP gene on chromosome 2p15. Furthermore, this syndrome is also known by its exact synonyms: CHDTHP, Ostravik-Lindemann-Solberg syndrome, and heart defect-tongue hamartoma-polysyndactyly syndrome.

Plasminogen deficiency type I is a syndrome that falls under the category of autosomal recessive diseases, and it specifically involves conditions that have a material basis in autosomal recessive inheritance. It is defined as a syndrome characterized by decreased serum plasminogen activity, decreased plasminogen antigen levels, and chronic mucosal pseudomembranous lesions typically manifesting as ligneous conjunctivitis. This condition is caused by homozygous or compound heterozygous mutation in the PLG gene located on chromosome 6q26. Additionally, plasminogen deficiency type I is exactly synonymous with hypoplasminogenemia.

Distal arthrogryposis type 10 (DA10) is a type of distal arthrogryposis as well as a type of autosomal dominant disease. It is characterized by having a material basis in autosomal dominant inheritance, specifically due to a heterozygous mutation in the chromosome region 2q31.3-q32.1. This condition is also known by its exact synonyms including plantar flexion contracture, short Achilles tendon, and short tendo calcaneus.

Distal arthrogryposis type 5d (DA5D), also known as distal arthrogryposis type 5 without ophthalmoparesis or ophthalmoplegia, is a form of distal arthrogryposis. It is categorized as an autosomal recessive disease, which fundamentally has its material basis in autosomal recessive inheritance. The definition of distal arthrogryposis type 5d encompasses a distal arthrogryposis characterized by severe camptodactyly of the hands, mild camptodactyly of the toes, extension contractures of the knee, and distinctive facial features, arising from homozygous or compound heterozygous mutation in the ECEL1 gene on chromosome 2q37.1.

Congenital contractural arachnodactyly (CCA) is a type of distal arthrogryposis, an autosomal dominant disease, and a physical disorder. It falls under the category of diseases that have a material basis in autosomal dominant inheritance and are rooted in some abnormality of prenatal development or birth. CCA is specifically characterized by contractures, arachnodactyly, scoliosis, and crumpled ears, resulting from a heterozygous mutation in the FBN2 gene on chromosome 5q23.3. It is also known by several exact synonyms, including Beals syndrome, Beals-Hecht syndrome, CCA, arachnodactyly, contractural Beals type, contractures, multiple with arachnodactyly, distal arthrogryposis type 9, and ear anomalies-contractures-dysplasia of bone with kyphoscoliosis.

Distal arthrogryposis type 1 is a type of distal arthrogryposis characterized by an autosomal dominant inheritance of contractures of the distal regions of the hands and feet, with no facial involvement or other anomalies. It has exact synonyms which include DA1 and digitotalar dysmorphism.

Distal arthrogryposis type 1a, which has the exact synonym DA1A, is classified as a type of autosomal dominant disease and also falls under the category of distal arthrogryposis type 1. This specific type of condition is based on material that has autosomal dominant inheritance characteristics. Furthermore, distal arthrogryposis type 1a is defined as a distal arthrogryposis type 1 that has its material basis in a heterozygous mutation in the TPM2 gene located on chromosome 9p13.3.

Distal arthrogryposis type 1b is a subtype of distal arthrogryposis type 1, which is categorized as an autosomal dominant disease. This condition specifically has a material basis in some form of autosomal dominant inheritance. Furthermore, distal arthrogryposis type 1b is defined as a distal arthrogryposis type 1 that arises from a heterozygous mutation in the MYBPC1 gene located on chromosome 12q23.2. Additionally, it is exactly synonymous with DA1B.

Distal arthrogryposis type 2B is a specific type of distal arthrogryposis. It is characterized by contractures of the distal joints of the limbs, a triangular face, downslanting palpebral fissures, a small mouth, and a high arched palate. This condition is also referred to by its exact synonyms, including DA2B, Freeman-Sheldon syndrome variant, and Sheldon-Hall syndrome.

Distal arthrogryposis type 2b1 (DA2B1) is classified as a subtype of distal arthrogryposis type 2b and is identified as a form of autosomal dominant disease. This condition is specifically characterized by having a material basis in autosomal dominant inheritance. The definition of distal arthrogryposis type 2b1 is a distal arthrogryposis type 2B that results from a heterozygous mutation in the TNNI2 gene located on chromosome 11p15.5.

Distal arthrogryposis type 2b2, which is exactly synonymous with DA2B2, is classified as a type of autosomal dominant disease and falls under the category of distal arthrogryposis type 2b. It is characterized by a condition that fundamentally has a material basis in autosomal dominant inheritance. Specifically, distal arthrogryposis type 2b2 is defined as a distal arthrogryposis type 2B that results from a heterozygous mutation in the TNNT3 gene located on chromosome 11p15.5.

Distal arthrogryposis type 2b3 is a type of autosomal dominant disease, specifically a subtype of distal arthrogryposis type 2b, and it is characterized by having a material basis in autosomal dominant inheritance. It is defined as a distal arthrogryposis type 2B characterized by a heterozygous mutation in the MYH3 gene on chromosome 17p13.1. Furthermore, distal arthrogryposis type 2b3 is exactly synonymous with DA2B3 and distal arthrogryposis type 2B3 (Sheldon-Hall).

Distal arthrogryposis type 7, also known exactly as DA7, Dutch-Kentucky syndrome, Hecht syndrome, Hecht-Beals syndrome, mouth, inability to completely open, and short finger-flexor tendons, and trismus-pseudocamptodactyly syndrome, is a type of distal arthrogryposis, and it is also a type of autosomal dominant disease. It has a material basis in autosomal dominant inheritance, specifically characterized by the inability to open the mouth fully and pseudocamptodactyly. This condition is due to heterozygous mutation in the MYH8 gene on chromosome 17p13.1.

Freeman Sheldon syndrome is a type of distal arthrogryposis, which is defined as a distal arthrogryposis characterized by microstomia with a whistling appearance of the mouth, distinctive facies, club foot, and joint contractures. It is also known by exact synonyms such as craniocarpotarsal dysplasia, craniocarpotarsal dystrophy, whistling face syndrome, and whistling face-windmill vane hand syndrome.

Distal arthrogryposis type 2A, also known exactly as DA2A or distal arthrogryposis type 2A (Freeman-Sheldon), is a type of autosomal dominant disease, specifically a Freeman Sheldon syndrome. It is characterized by a material basis in autosomal dominant inheritance and is defined as a Freeman-Sheldon syndrome that arises from a heterozygous mutation in the MYH3 gene on chromosome 17p13.1.

Autosomal recessive whistling face syndrome is a type of autosomal recessive disease, a type of Freeman Sheldon syndrome, and a type that at least has a material basis in some autosomal recessive inheritance. Additionally, it is defined as a Freeman-Sheldon syndrome that has autosomal recessive inheritance.

Distal arthrogryposis type 3 is a type of distal arthrogryposis and is also classified as a type of autosomal dominant disease, which inherently has a material basis in some form of autosomal dominant inheritance. It is specifically characterized by distal arthrogryposis with short stature and cleft palate, a condition that arises from a heterozygous mutation in the PIEZO2 gene located on chromosome 18p11.22-p11.21. Furthermore, distal arthrogryposis type 3 is known by several exact synonyms, including DA3, Gordon syndrome, camptodactyly-cleft palate-clubfoot syndrome, and distal arthrogryposis multiplex congenita type IIA.

Distal Arthrogryposis Type 5 is a specific form of distal arthrogryposis and falls under the category of autosomal dominant diseases. It is characterized by distal arthrogryposis with ocular abnormalities, which are caused by a heterozygous gain of function mutation in the PIEZO2 gene located on chromosome 18p11.22-p11.21. This condition is uniquely identified by several exact synonyms, including DA5, DAIIB, arthrogryposis-oculomotor limitation-electroretinal anomalies syndrome, distal arthrogryposis type IIB, distal arthrogryposis with ophthalmoplegia, and oculomelic amyoplasia.

Distal arthrogryposis type 6 is a specific type of distal arthrogryposis characterized by distal arthrogryposis with sensorineural deafness. It is also known by its exact synonyms: DA6, arthrogryposis and sensorineural deafness, arthrogryposis-like hand anomaly-sensorineural deafness syndrome, and familial hand abnormality and sensori-neural deafness.

Distal arthrogryposis type 4, which is a type of distal arthrogryposis, is characterized by distal arthrogryposis with severe scoliosis. It is exactly synonymous with DA4, DAIID, arthrogryposis-severe scoliosis syndrome, and distal arthrogryposis type IID.

Autosomal recessive spinocerebellar ataxia 4 is a type of autosomal recessive cerebellar ataxia characterized by an ataxic gait with spasticity, hyperreflexia of the lower limbs, and mitochondrial defects. This condition has a material basis in homozygous or compound heterozygous mutations in the VPS13D gene located on chromosome 1p36.22-p36.21. It is also known by several exact synonyms including SCA24, SCAR4, SCASI, autosomal recessive cerebellar ataxia-saccadic intrusion syndrome, spinocerebellar ataxia 24, and spinocerebellar ataxia with saccadic intrusions.

Autosomal recessive spinocerebellar ataxia 3 is a type of autosomal recessive cerebellar ataxia, defined as an autosomal recessive cerebellar ataxia characterized by spinocerebellar ataxia with optic and cochlear degeneration. This condition has a material basis in homozygous or compound heterozygous mutation in a region on chromosome 6p23-p21. It is also exactly synonymous with SCABD, SCAR3, autosomal recessive spinocerebellar ataxia type 3, autosomal recessive spinocerebellar ataxia-blindness-deafness syndrome, and autosomal recessive spinocerebellar ataxia-blindness-hearing loss syndrome.

Autosomal recessive spinocerebellar ataxia 23 is a type of autosomal recessive cerebellar ataxia, which is characterized by epilepsy, intellectual disability, and gait ataxia. This condition has a material basis in homozygous or compound heterozygous mutation in the TDP2 gene on chromosome 6p22.3. It is exactly synonymous with SCAR23 and is also known as the autosomal recessive cerebellar ataxia-epilepsy-intellectual disability syndrome due to TUD deficiency.

Autosomal recessive spinocerebellar ataxia 22 is a type of autosomal recessive cerebellar ataxia, which has an exact synonym, SCAR22. This condition is defined as an autosomal recessive cerebellar ataxia that has its material basis in homozygous or compound heterozygous mutation in the VWA3B gene on chromosome 2q11.2.

Autosomal recessive spinocerebellar ataxia 24 is a type of autosomal recessive cerebellar ataxia, and it is defined as an autosomal recessive cerebellar ataxia that has its material basis in homozygous or compound heterozygous mutation in the UBA5 gene on chromosome 3q22.1. Additionally, it has the exact synonym SCAR24.

Autosomal recessive spinocerebellar ataxia 27 is a type of autosomal recessive cerebellar ataxia, which has an exact synonym SCAR27. It is defined as an autosomal recessive cerebellar ataxia characterized by adult onset of progressive gait difficulties and other cerebellar signs. This condition has its material basis in homozygous or compound heterozygous mutation in the GDAP2 gene on chromosome 1p12.

Autosomal recessive spinocerebellar ataxia 6 is a type of autosomal recessive cerebellar ataxia characterized by an onset in infancy of nonprogressive cerebellar ataxia without intellectual disability. This condition has a material basis in homozygous or compound heterozygous mutations in a region on chromosome 20q11-q13. It is also known by its exact synonyms SCAR6, autosomal recessive spinocerebellar ataxia type 6, and infantile-onset autosomal recessive nonprogressive cerebellar ataxia.

Autosomal recessive spinocerebellar ataxia 8, a type of autosomal recessive cerebellar ataxia, is characterized by a definition that includes it as an autosomal recessive cerebellar ataxia marked by gradually progressive neurodegeneration. This results in gait ataxia and other cerebellar symptoms, spasticity, secondary musculoskeletal abnormalities, and ocular movement anomalies. The condition has its material basis in homozygous or compound heterozygous mutation in SYNE1 on chromosome 6q25.2. It is also known by several exact synonyms, including ARCA1, Autosomal recessive cerebellar ataxia type 1, SCAR8, SYNE1-related autosomal recessive cerebellar ataxia, autosomal recessive ataxia, Beauce type, and recessive ataxia of Beauce.

Combined D 2 and L 2 hydroxyglutaric aciduria is a type of 2 hydroxyglutaric aciduria and also a type of autosomal recessive disease. It is characterized as a condition that, at the very least, has a material basis in autosomal recessive inheritance. Specifically, this form of 2-hydroxyglutaric aciduria is characterized by neonatal-onset encephalopathy accompanied by severe hypotonia, intractable seizures, respiratory distress, and a lack of psychomotor development, leading to early death. These symptoms have their material basis in homozygous or compound heterozygous mutations in the SLC25A1 gene located on chromosome 22q11.21. 

Moreover, Combined D 2 and L 2 hydroxyglutaric aciduria is known by several exact synonyms, including D,L-2-HGA, D,L-2-hydroxyglutaric acidemia, D,L-2-hydroxyglutaric aciduria, combined D,L-2-hydroxyglutaric aciduria, combined D-2-hydroxyglutaric acidemia and L-2-hydroxyglutaric acidemia, and combined D-2-hydroxyglutaric aciduria and L-2-hydroxyglutaric aciduria.

Corneal dystrophy perceptive deafness syndrome is a type of syndrome and an autosomal recessive disease that at least has a material basis in some autosomal recessive inheritance. It is characterized by congenital corneal endothelial dystrophy and progressive, postlingual sensorineural hearing loss, with its material basis in homozygous or compound heterozygous mutation in the SLC4A11 gene on chromosome 20p13. The syndrome is also exactly synonymous with CDPD, CDPD1, Harboyan syndrome, corneal dystrophy and perceptive deafness, corneal dystrophy with progressive deafness, and corneal endothelial dystrophy and perceptive deafness.

Temtamy syndrome is a type of autosomal recessive disease and syndrome, which is something that at least has a material basis in some autosomal recessive inheritance. It is characterized by variable craniofacial dysmorphism, ocular coloboma, seizures, and brain abnormalities including partial or complete absence of the corpus callosum. This syndrome has a material basis in a mutation in the C12ORF57 gene on chromosome 12p13.31. Temtamy syndrome is also known by its exact synonyms: Temtamy-Shalash syndrome, craniofacial dysmorphism with ocular coloboma absent corpus callosum and aortic dilatation, craniofacial dysmorphism-coloboma-corpus callosum agenesis syndrome, and dysmorphism, corpus callosum agenesis and colobomas.
