@prefix rdfs: <http://www.w3.org/2000/01/rdf-schema#> .

:acth_independent_macronodular_adrenal_hyperplasia rdfs:subClassOf :primary_hyperaldosteronism ;
    :has_definition "A primary hyperaldosteronism characterized by multiple bilateral adrenocortical nodules that cause a striking enlargement of the adrenal gland and production of an excess of cortisol." ;
    :has_exact_synonym "ACTH-independent macronodular adrenocortical hyperplasia"@en,
        "AIMAH"@en,
        "Cushing syndrome due to macronodular adrenal hyperplasia"@en,
        "MMAD"@en,
        "adrenocorticotropic hormone-independent macronodular adrenal hyperplasia"@en,
        "corticotropin-independent macronodular adrenal hyperplasia"@en,
        "massive macronodular adrenocortical disease"@en,
        "primary macronodular adrenal hyperplasia"@en .
text: ACTH independent macronodular adrenal hyperplasia is a type of primary hyperaldosteronism characterized by multiple bilateral adrenocortical nodules that cause a striking enlargement of the adrenal gland and production of an excess of cortisol. It has several exact synonyms, including ACTH-independent macronodular adrenocortical hyperplasia, AIMAH, Cushing syndrome due to macronodular adrenal hyperplasia, MMAD, adrenocorticotropic hormone-independent macronodular adrenal hyperplasia, corticotropin-independent macronodular adrenal hyperplasia, massive macronodular adrenocortical disease, and primary macronodular adrenal hyperplasia.

ACTH independent macronodular adrenal hyperplasia 1 is a type of ACTH independent macronodular adrenal hyperplasia. It is defined as an ACTH-independent macronodular adrenal hyperplasia that has its material basis in a somatic mutation in the GNAS gene on chromosome 20q13.32. Additionally, ACTH independent macronodular adrenal hyperplasia 1 is exactly synonymous with AIMAH1.

ACTH independent macronodular adrenal hyperplasia 2 is a type of ACTH independent macronodular adrenal hyperplasia, which is defined as an ACTH-independent macronodular adrenal hyperplasia that has a material basis in a combination of autosomal dominant and second hit somatic mutation in the ARMC5 gene on chromosome 16p11.2. Additionally, it has the exact synonym AIMAH2.

Ventriculomegaly cystic kidney disease is a syndrome that falls under the category of autosomal recessive diseases and is characterized by a type of condition that inherently has a material basis in some form of autosomal recessive inheritance. Specifically, it is defined as a syndrome that manifests in utero with symptoms including dilated cerebral ventricles and microscopic renal tubular cysts, which are caused by homozygous or compound heterozygous mutations in the CRB2 gene located on chromosome 9q33.3. Furthermore, ventriculomegaly cystic kidney disease is known by several exact synonyms: VMCKD, congenital nephrosis-cerebral ventriculomegaly syndrome, cystic kidney disease with ventriculomegaly, and ventriculomegaly with cystic kidney disease.

D-glyceric aciduria is a type of autosomal recessive disease, an inherited metabolic disorder, and something that at least has a material basis in some autosomal recessive inheritance. It is defined as an inherited metabolic disorder characterized by impaired serine and fructose metabolism resulting in elevated excretion of D-glyceric acid due to homozygous or compound heterozygous mutation in the GLYCTK gene on chromosome 3p21.2. D-glyceric aciduria has exact synonyms including D-glycerate kinase deficiency, D-glyceric acidemia, D-glycericacidemia, deficiency of glycerate kinase, and non-ketotic hyperglycinemia syndrome.

Doors syndrome is a type of syndrome and an autosomal recessive disease with a material basis in some autosomal recessive inheritance. It is characterized by sensorineural deafness, onychodystrophy, osteodystrophy, seizures, and intellectual disability, which is caused by homozygous or compound heterozygous mutation in the TBC1D24 gene on chromosome 16p13.3. Doors syndrome is also known by several exact synonyms: DOOR syndrome, DOORS, autosomal recessive deafness-onychodystrophy syndrome, deafness-onychodystrophy-osteodystrophy-intellectual disability syndrome, deafness-onychodystrophy-osteodystrophy-intellectual disability-seizures syndrome, and deafness-onychoosteodystrophy-intellectual disability syndrome.

High myopia sensorineural deafness syndrome is a type of autosomal recessive disease and a type of syndrome that at least has a material basis in some autosomal recessive inheritance. It is characterized by severe myopia and moderate to profound, bilateral, progressive sensorineural hearing loss. This syndrome has its material basis in homozygous or compound heterozygous mutation in the SLITRK6 gene on chromosome 13q31.1. Furthermore, high myopia sensorineural deafness syndrome is exactly synonymous with DFNMYP, deafness and myopia, and deafness and myopia syndrome.

Dihydropyrimidinase deficiency is a type of autosomal recessive disease and also a type of pyrimidine metabolic disorder, which at least has a material basis in some autosomal recessive inheritance. It is characterized by a defect in the degradation of uracil and thymine, resulting in elevated levels of 5,6-dihydrouracil and 5,6-dihydrothymine in urine. This condition has a material basis in homozygous or compound heterozygous mutation in the DPYS gene on chromosome 8q22.3. Moreover, dihydropyrimidinase deficiency has several exact synonyms, including DPH deficiency, DPYS deficiency, DPYSD, and dihydropyrimidinuria.

Familial erythrocytosis 8 is a type of primary polycythemia, which is characterized by erythrocytosis and, in some cases, hemolytic anemia. This condition has a material basis in homozygous or compound heterozygous mutation in the BPGM gene on chromosome 7q33. It is also known by several exact synonyms including BPGM deficiency, DPGM deficiency, ECYT8, bisphosphoglycerate mutase deficiency, bisphosphoglyceromutase deficiency, diphosphoglycerate mutase deficiency of erythrocyte, and hemolytic anemia due to diphosphoglycerate mutase deficiency.

Familial erythrocytosis 7 is a type of primary polycythemia characterized by high oxygen affinity hemoglobin and compensatory polycythemia, which has a material basis in heterozygous mutation in either the HBA2 or HBA1 gene on chromosome 16p13.3. It is exactly synonymous with ECYT7, alpha-globin type erythrocytosis, and alpha-globin type polycythemia.

Familial erythrocytosis 6 is a type of primary polycythemia, defined as a primary polycythemia characterized by high oxygen affinity hemoglobin and compensatory polycythemia that has a material basis in heterozygous mutation in HBB on chromosome 11p15.4. It is also exactly synonymous with ECYT6, beta-globin type erythrocytosis, and beta-globin type polycythemia.

Congenital sucrase isomaltase deficiency is a type of autosomal recessive disease, physical disorder, carbohydrate metabolic disorder, and it is something that at least has a material basis in autosomal recessive inheritance. It is also a type of condition that at least has disease basis in some abnormality of prenatal development or birth. This disorder is defined as a carbohydrate metabolic disorder characterized by malabsorption of oligosaccharides and disaccharides, which has its material basis in homozygous or compound heterozygous mutation in the SI gene on chromosome 3q26.1. Additionally, congenital sucrase isomaltase deficiency is exactly synonymous with CSID, SI deficiency, congenital sucrase-isomaltose malabsorption, congenital sucrose intolerance, and disaccharide intolerance.

Autosomal recessive nonsyndromic deafness 99 is a specific type of autosomal recessive nonsyndromic deafness. It is characterized by prelingual, severe to profound sensorineural hearing loss without vestibular dysfunction. This condition has its material basis in homozygous or compound heterozygous mutation in the TMEM132E gene on chromosome 17q12. Additionally, autosomal recessive nonsyndromic deafness 99 is exactly synonymous with DFNB99 and autosomal recessive deafness 99.

Autosomal recessive nonsyndromic deafness 57 is a type of autosomal recessive nonsyndromic deafness characterized by symmetric bilateral moderate to severe hearing loss. This is due to the material basis in homozygous or compound heterozygous mutation in the PDZD7 gene on chromosome 10q24.31. Additionally, autosomal recessive nonsyndromic deafness 57 is precisely synonymous with DFNB57 and autosomal recessive deafness 57.

Autosomal recessive nonsyndromic deafness 113 is a specific type of autosomal recessive nonsyndromic deafness. It is characterized by postlingual progressive hearing impairment that arises from homozygous or compound heterozygous mutations in the CEACAM16 gene located on chromosome 19q13. Additionally, autosomal recessive nonsyndromic deafness 113 is precisely referred to by two exact synonyms: DFNB113 and autosomal recessive deafness 113.

Autosomal recessive nonsyndromic deafness 112 is a type of autosomal recessive nonsyndromic deafness, characterized by postlingual progressive sensorineural hearing impairment that has its material basis in homozygous or compound heterozygous mutation in the BDP1 gene on chromosome 5q13.2. It also has the exact synonyms DFNB112 and autosomal recessive deafness 112.

Autosomal recessive nonsyndromic deafness 100 is a type of autosomal recessive nonsyndromic deafness characterized by prelingual onset of profound sensorineural deafness without vestibular involvement, which has its material basis in homozygous or compound heterozygous mutation in the PPIP5K2 gene on chromosome 5q21.1. It has the exact synonyms DFNB100 and autosomal recessive deafness 100.

Autosomal recessive nonsyndromic deafness 109 is a type of autosomal recessive nonsyndromic deafness, which is characterized by bilateral congenital severe to profound sensorineural hearing loss and vestibular dysplasia without balance or movement issues. This condition has a material basis in homozygous or compound heterozygous mutation in the ESRP1 gene on chromosome 8q22.1. Moreover, autosomal recessive nonsyndromic deafness 109 is exactly synonymous with DFNB109 and autosomal recessive deafness 109.

Autosomal recessive nonsyndromic deafness 111 is a type of autosomal recessive nonsyndromic deafness, which is defined as an autosomal recessive nonsyndromic deafness characterized by early-onset, moderate to severe sensorineural hearing loss with no vestibular involvement. This condition has its material basis in homozygous or compound heterozygous mutation in the MPZL2 gene on chromosome 11q23.33. Autosomal recessive nonsyndromic deafness 111 is exactly synonymous with DFNB111 and autosomal recessive deafness 111.

Autosomal recessive nonsyndromic deafness 94 is a type of autosomal recessive nonsyndromic deafness characterized by prelingual profound sensorineural hearing loss. This condition has its material basis in homozygous or compound heterozygous mutation in the NARS2 gene located on chromosome 11q14.1. Moreover, autosomal recessive nonsyndromic deafness 94 is exactly synonymous with DFNB94 and autosomal recessive deafness 94.

Autosomal recessive nonsyndromic deafness 114 is a type of autosomal recessive nonsyndromic deafness, which is characterized by congenital profound sensorineural hearing loss. This condition has its material basis in homozygous or compound heterozygous mutation in the GRAP gene on chromosome 17p11.2. Moreover, autosomal recessive nonsyndromic deafness 114 is exactly synonymous with DFNB114 and autosomal recessive deafness 114.

Autosomal recessive nonsyndromic deafness 115 is a specific type of autosomal recessive nonsyndromic deafness. It is characterized by the onset in early childhood of severe sensorineural hearing impairment, which has its material basis in homozygous or compound heterozygous mutation in the SPNS2 gene located on chromosome 17p13.2. This condition is also exactly known as DFNB115 and autosomal recessive deafness 115.

Autosomal recessive nonsyndromic deafness 110, also precisely known as DFNB110 or autosomal recessive deafness 110, is a type of autosomal recessive nonsyndromic deafness. It is defined as an autosomal recessive nonsyndromic deafness characterized by prelingual, bilateral hearing loss that arises from either homozygous or compound heterozygous mutation in the COCH gene located on chromosome 14q12.

Rolandic epilepsy paroxysmal exercise-induced dystonia writer's cramp syndrome, also known by its exact synonyms EPRPDC, RE-PED-WC, Rolandic epilepsy with paroxysmal exercise-induced dystonia and writer's cramp, and Rolandic-type focal motor epilepsy and exercise-induced dystonia, is a type of infancy electroclinical syndrome, autosomal recessive disease, and is characterized by having at least a material basis in autosomal recessive inheritance and beginning during infantile onset. This syndrome is defined as an infancy electroclinical syndrome characterized by the onset of focal seizures in infancy and exercise-induced dystonia in childhood, with the condition having a material basis in homozygous or compound heterozygous mutations in the TBC1D24 gene on chromosome 16p13.3.

Congenital lactase deficiency, also known by its exact synonyms CLD, congenital alactasia, congenital alactasia syndrome, congenital lactose intolerance, congenital lactose malabsorption, and disaccharide intolerance II, is a type of autosomal recessive disease, physical disorder, and carbohydrate metabolic disorder. It specifically has a material basis in autosomal recessive inheritance and is associated with an abnormality of prenatal development or birth. This disorder is defined as a carbohydrate metabolic disorder characterized by watery diarrhea in infants fed with breast milk or other lactose-containing formulas, which is caused by homozygous or compound heterozygous mutations in the LCT gene on chromosome 2q21.3.

Schopf Schulz Passarge syndrome is a type of autosomal dominant disease and ectodermal dysplasia, which is at least characterized by having a material basis in some autosomal dominant inheritance. This syndrome is defined as an ectodermal dysplasia characterized by multiple eyelid apocrine hidrocystomas, palmoplantar keratoderma, hypotrichosis, hypodontia, and nail dystrophy, with its material basis in homozygous or compound heterozygous mutation in the WNT10A gene on chromosome 2q35. It has several exact synonyms, including SSPS, eccrine tumors-ectodermal dysplasia, keratosis palmoplantaris-cystic eyelids-hypodontia-hypotrichosis syndrome, palmoplantar hyperkeratosis-cystic eyelids-hypodontia-hypotrichosis syndrome, and palmoplantar keratoderma-cystic eyelids-hypodontia-hypotrichosis syndrome.

Ectopia lentis with ectopia of pupil is a type of eye disease and also falls under the category of autosomal recessive diseases. It is defined as an eye disease characterized by the displacement of the lenses and the pupils in association with other ocular anomalies. This condition has its material basis in homozygous or compound heterozygous mutation in the ADAMTSL4 gene on chromosome 1q21.2, indicating that it at least has a material basis in some form of autosomal recessive inheritance. Additionally, ectopia lentis with ectopia of pupil has the exact synonym ectopia lentis et pupillae.

Ectodermal Dysplasia Ectrodactyly and Macular Dystrophy Syndrome, also known precisely as EEM syndrome, EEMS, and ectodermal dysplasia-ectrodactyly-macular dystrophy syndrome, is categorized as a type of autosomal recessive disease, a subset of ectodermal dysplasia, and something that invariably has a material basis in autosomal recessive inheritance. This syndrome is specifically defined as an ectodermal dysplasia characterized by the combination of ectodermal dysplasia, ectrodactyly, and macular dystrophy, arising from homozygous or compound heterozygous mutations in the CDH3 gene located on chromosome 16q22.1.

Ectodermal dysplasia 13 is a type of autosomal recessive disease and a type of ectodermal dysplasia. It is categorized as something that at least has a material basis in some autosomal recessive inheritance. This specific condition is defined as an ectodermal dysplasia characterized by severe oligodontia accompanied by anomalies of hair and skin, which has its material basis in homozygous or compound heterozygous mutation in the KREMEN1 gene on chromosome 22q12.1. Additionally, ectodermal dysplasia 13 has exact synonyms, including ECTD13 and ectodermal dysplasia 13, hair/tooth type.

Ectodermal Dysplasia 15 is a type of autosomal recessive disease and ectodermal dysplasia, which specifically has a material basis in autosomal recessive inheritance. It is characterized by an onset in early childhood of hypotrichosis and the absence of sweating except with extreme exercise, due to homozygous or compound heterozygous mutation in the CST6 gene on chromosome 11q13.1. Additionally, Ectodermal Dysplasia 15 is exactly synonymous with ECTD15 and ectodermal dysplasia 15, hypohidrotic/hair type.

Ectodermal dysplasia 12 is a type of autosomal dominant disease and a type of hypohidrotic ectodermal dysplasia, characterized by having a material basis in some form of autosomal dominant inheritance. It is defined as a hypohidrotic ectodermal dysplasia that results from a heterozygous mutation in the KDF1 gene located on chromosome 1p36.11. Additionally, ectodermal dysplasia 12 is exactly synonymous with ECTD12 and ectodermal dysplasia 12, hypohidrotic/hair/tooth/nail type.

Ectodermal dysplasia 11A (ECTD11A), also known exactly as ectodermal dysplasia 11A, hypohidrotic/hair/tooth type, autosomal dominant, is a type of autosomal dominant disease, hypohidrotic ectodermal dysplasia, and a condition that at least has a material basis in some form of autosomal dominant inheritance. It is defined as a hypohidrotic ectodermal dysplasia that arises from a heterozygous mutation in the EDARADD gene located on chromosome 1q42-q43.

Ectodermal Dysplasia 11B is a specific type of autosomal recessive disease and is also categorized under hypohidrotic ectodermal dysplasias. It is characterized by conditions that fundamentally have a material basis in autosomal recessive inheritance. Specifically, it is a hypohidrotic ectodermal dysplasia that arises from either homozygous or compound heterozygous mutations in the EDARADD gene located on chromosome 1q42-q43. Additionally, Ectodermal Dysplasia 11B is precisely synonymized as ECTD11B and ectodermal dysplasia 11B, hypohidrotic/hair/tooth type, autosomal recessive.

Pure hair and nail ectodermal dysplasia is a type of ectodermal dysplasia that is characterized by onychodystrophy and severe hypotrichosis, with the absence of nonectodermal or other ectodermal manifestations.

Ectodermal Dysplasia 9 is a type of autosomal recessive disease, which is a pure hair and nail ectodermal dysplasia, and it can also be described as a condition that has its material basis in some form of autosomal recessive inheritance. It is defined as a pure hair and nail ectodermal dysplasia that occurs due to homozygous or compound heterozygous mutation in the HOXC13 gene located on chromosome 12q13.13. Furthermore, Ectodermal Dysplasia 9 is precisely referred to by the exact synonyms ECTD9 and ectodermal dysplasia 9, hair/nail type.

Ectodermal Dysplasia 5 (ED5), which is also known precisely as ECTD5 and ectodermal dysplasia 5, hair/nail type, is identified as a type of autosomal recessive disease, specifically falling under the category of pure hair and nail ectodermal dysplasia. This condition is characterized by having its material basis in homozygous or compound heterozygous mutations located in a region on chromosome 10q24.32-q25.1. Additionally, ED5 is recognized for being a type of disorder that inherently involves autosomal recessive inheritance, highlighting its genetic underpinnings.

Ectodermal dysplasia 4 is a type of autosomal recessive disease, specifically a pure hair and nail ectodermal dysplasia, and is characterized by having a material basis in autosomal recessive inheritance. It is defined as a pure hair and nail ectodermal dysplasia that results from homozygous or compound heterozygous mutation in the KRT85 gene on chromosome 12q13.13. Moreover, ectodermal dysplasia 4 is also known by its exact synonyms ECTD4 and ectodermal dysplasia 4, hair/nail type.

Ectodermal dysplasia 6, which is also precisely known as ECTD6 and ectodermal dysplasia 6, hair/nail type, is a type of autosomal recessive disease, pure hair and nail ectodermal dysplasia, and a condition that fundamentally has a material basis in autosomal recessive inheritance. It is defined as a pure hair and nail ectodermal dysplasia that occurs due to homozygous or compound heterozygous mutations in a specific region on chromosome 17p12-q21.2.

Ectodermal dysplasia 7, also known precisely as ECTD7 or ectodermal dysplasia 7, hair/nail type, is categorized as an autosomal recessive disease. It falls under the subgroup of pure hair and nail ectodermal dysplasia and is characterized by its autosomal recessive inheritance. The condition is defined by a pure hair and nail ectodermal dysplasia that results from homozygous or compound heterozygous mutations in the KRT74 gene located on chromosome 12q13.13.

Ectodermal dysplasia 8 is a type of autosomal recessive disease and ectodermal dysplasia, which is characterized by a condition that necessarily has a material basis in some form of autosomal recessive inheritance. Specifically, it is defined as an ectodermal dysplasia characterized by hypotrichosis, hypodontia, and dystrophic toenails, and this condition has a material basis in homozygous or compound heterozygous mutation located in a region on chromosome 18q22.1-q22.3. Furthermore, ectodermal dysplasia 8 is also known by its exact synonyms: ECTD8, Fried's tooth and nail syndrome, and ectodermal dysplasia 8, hair/tooth/nail type.

Ectodermal dysplasia 14 is a type of autosomal recessive disease, which is a category of ectodermal dysplasia. It is characterized by a condition that inherently has a material basis in autosomal recessive inheritance. Specifically, ectodermal dysplasia 14 is defined as an ectodermal dysplasia characterized by scalp hypotrichosis and hypodontia, which has its material basis in homozygous or compound heterozygous mutations in the TSPEAR gene located on chromosome 21q22.3. Additionally, ectodermal dysplasia 14 is exactly synonymous with ECTN14 and ectodermal dysplasia 14, hair/tooth type with or without hypohidrosis.

Ectodermal Dysplasia 10A, also precisely known as ECTD10A or ectodermal dysplasia 10A, hypohidrotic/hair/nail type, autosomal dominant, is a type of autosomal dominant disease and falls under the category of hypohidrotic ectodermal dysplasia. It is characterized by a condition that fundamentally arises from autosomal dominant inheritance. Specifically, it is a hypohidrotic ectodermal dysplasia that results from a heterozygous mutation in the EDAR gene located on chromosome 2q13.

Ectodermal dysplasia 1 is a type of disease that falls into several categories: it is a kind of X-linked recessive disease, a type of hypohidrotic ectodermal dysplasia, and it has a material basis in some form of X-linked recessive inheritance. It is specifically defined as a hypohidrotic ectodermal dysplasia that results from an X-linked recessive mutation in the EDA gene found on chromosome Xq13.1. This condition is known by various exact synonyms, including CST syndrome, Christ-Siemens-Touraine syndrome, ED1, HED1, X-linked anhidrotic ectodermal dysplasia, XHED, XLHED, ectodermal dysplasia 1, anhidrotic, ectodermal dysplasia 1, hypohidrotic, X-linked, and ectodermal dysplasia 1, hypohidrotic/hair/tooth type, X-linked, as well as hypohidrotic ectodermal dysplasia, X-Linked, indicating its diverse but specific identification within medical terminology.

Ectodermal dysplasia 10b is classified as a type of autosomal recessive disease, hypohidrotic ectodermal dysplasia, and a condition that essentially involves autosomal recessive inheritance. It is specifically defined as a hypohidrotic ectodermal dysplasia that results from homozygous or compound heterozygous mutation in the EDAR gene located on chromosome 2q13. Additionally, ectodermal dysplasia 10b is also known by its exact synonyms ECTD10B and ectodermal dysplasia 10B, hypohidrotic/hair/nail type, autosomal recessive.

Proliferative vasculopathy and hydranencephaly hydrocephaly syndrome is a type of syndrome, autosomal recessive disease, and something that at least has a material basis in autosomal recessive inheritance. It is defined as a syndrome characterized by hydranencephaly, glomeruloid vasculopathy of the central nervous system and retinal vessels, diffuse clastic ischemic lesions of the brain stem, basal ganglia, and spinal cord with calcifications, and fetal akinesia with arthrogryposis. This condition has its material basis in homozygous or compound heterozygous mutation in the FLVCR2 gene on chromosome 14q24.3. Moreover, proliferative vasculopathy and hydranencephaly hydrocephaly syndrome has several exact synonyms: EPV, Fowler syndrome, Fowler vasculopathy, PVHH, cerebral proliferative glomeruloid vasculopathy, encephaloclastic proliferative vasculopathy, hydranencephaly, Fowler type, hydrocephaly/hydranencephaly due to cerebral vasculopathy, and proliferative vasculopathy and hydranencephaly/hydrocephaly.

Enterokinase deficiency is classified as a type of autosomal recessive disease, an intestinal disease, and is associated with autosomal recessive inheritance due to its material basis. It is defined as an intestinal disease characterized by early-onset failure to thrive, edema, hypoproteinemia, diarrhea, and fat malabsorption, which results from homozygous or compound heterozygous mutations in the TMPRSS15 gene located on chromosome 21q21.1. Additionally, enterokinase deficiency is precisely known by several synonyms, including congenital enterokinase deficiency, congenital enteropathy due to enteropeptidase deficiency, and deficiency of enteropeptidase.

Kohlschutter Tonz Syndrome is a type of syndrome that falls under the category of autosomal recessive diseases, which means it at least partly has a material basis in some form of autosomal recessive inheritance. It is characterized by severe global developmental delay, early-onset intractable seizures, spasticity, and amelogenesis imperfecta, with its material basis being in homozygous or compound heterozygous mutation in the ROGDI gene on chromosome 16p13.3. The syndrome is also known by several exact synonyms, including KTZS, Kohlschutter's syndrome, amelocerebrohypohidrotic syndrome, epilepsy and yellow teeth, epilepsy dementia amelogenesis imperfecta, and epilepsy-dementia-amelogenesis imperfecta syndrome.

Hyaline fibromatosis syndrome (HFS), also known exactly as inherited systemic hyalinosis, puretic syndrome, and systemic hyalinosis, is a type of autosomal recessive disease, which is also classified under connective tissue diseases. This syndrome is characterized by the abnormal growth of hyalinized fibrous tissue, particularly around the subcutaneous regions on the scalp, ears, neck, face, hands, and feet, as well as gingival hypertrophy, joint contractures, and osteolytic bone lesions. The material basis for HFS is linked to homozygous or compound heterozygous mutations in the ANTXR2 gene located on chromosome 4q21.21.

Primary hyperoxaluria type 1 is a specific type of primary hyperoxaluria. It is characterized by a failure to transaminate glyoxylate, leading to the accumulation of calcium oxalate in various tissues. This condition has a material basis in homozygous or compound heterozygous mutations in the AGXT gene located on chromosome 2q37.3. Additionally, primary hyperoxaluria type 1 is precisely known by several exact synonyms, including HP1, alanine-glyoxylate aminotransferase deficiency, glycolic aciduria, hepatic AGT deficiency, oxalosis I, peroxisomal alanine-glyoxylate aminotransferase deficiency, and serine pyruvate aminotransferase deficiency.

Primary hyperoxaluria type 2 is a type of primary hyperoxaluria. It is characterized by elevated urinary excretion of oxalate and L-glycerate, recurrent nephrolithiasis and nephrocalcinosis, and end-stage renal disease. This condition has a material basis in homozygous or compound heterozygous mutation in the GRHPR gene on chromosome 9p13.2. Primary hyperoxaluria type 2 is also known by several exact synonyms, including D-glycerate dehydrogenase deficiency, HP2, L-glyceric aciduria, glyoxylate reductase/hydroxypyruvate reductase deficiency, and oxalosis II.

Primary Hyperoxaluria Type 3 is a type of Primary Hyperoxaluria. It is defined as a primary hyperoxaluria characterized by recurring calcium oxalate stones that occurs due to homozygous or compound heterozygous mutation in the HOGA1 gene on chromosome 10q24.2. Moreover, it has exact synonyms including HP3, PH III, and Primary Hyperoxaluria Type III.

Saul Wilson syndrome is a type of autosomal dominant disease that is also categorized as a bone development disease, indicating that it has a material basis in some form of autosomal dominant inheritance. It is characterized by early developmental delays, particularly in speech, distinct facial features, short stature, brachydactyly, clubfoot deformities, cataracts, and microcephaly. This condition is caused by a heterozygous mutation in the COG4 gene on chromosome 16q22.1. Saul Wilson syndrome is alternatively known by its exact synonyms, SWILS and microcephalic osteodysplastic dysplasia, Saul-Wilson type.

Intellectual developmental disorder with short stature and behavioral abnormalities (IDDSSBA) is a syndrome characterized by a range of symptoms including intellectual disability, global developmental delay, short stature, aphasia, and hypotonia. This disorder is a type of autosomal recessive disease and also falls under the category of syndromes that have a material basis in autosomal recessive inheritance. Specifically, IDDSSBA has its material basis in homozygous or compound heterozygous mutations in the IQSEC1 gene located on chromosome 3p25.2-p25.1.

Neurooculocardiogenitourinary syndrome, also known exactly as NOCGUS, is a type of syndrome and an autosomal dominant disease that inherently has a material basis in autosomal dominant inheritance. It is defined as a syndrome characterized by impaired growth along with anomalies of the ocular, craniofacial, neurologic, cardiovascular, genitourinary, skeletal, and gastrointestinal systems, which has its material basis in a heterozygous mutation in the WDR37 gene located on chromosome 10p15.3.

High molecular weight kininogen deficiency is a type of autosomal recessive disease and a type of blood coagulation disease. It is also recognized as a condition that at least has a material basis in some form of autosomal recessive inheritance. This disease is defined as a blood coagulation disease characterized by a deficiency of high molecular weight kininogen but not of low molecular weight kininogen, resulting in abnormal surface-mediated activation of fibrinolysis. This is due to homozygous or compound heterozygous mutation in the KNG1 gene on chromosome 3q27.3, with both high and low molecular weight kininogen being encoded by the KNG1 gene. Additionally, high molecular weight kininogen deficiency is exactly synonymous with Fitzgerald trait, HMWK deficiency, and congenital high-molecular-weight kininogen deficiency.

Familial benign fleck retina (FRFB) is a type of retinal disease, specifically an autosomal recessive disease. It is characterized by a condition that fundamentally has a material basis in autosomal recessive inheritance. The disease is defined by a retinal disease distinguished by a unique pattern of diffuse, yellow-white, fleck-like lesions that extend to the far periphery of the retina, yet without any noticeable visual or electrophysiologic deficits. This condition is caused by homozygous or compound heterozygous mutation in the PLA2G5 gene located on chromosome 1p36.13.

Hereditary folate malabsorption is a type of vitamin metabolic disorder, autosomal recessive disease, and something that at least has a material basis in some autosomal recessive inheritance. It is defined as a vitamin metabolic disorder characterized by impaired intestinal folate absorption and impaired transport of folate into the central nervous system, resulting in megaloblastic anemia, diarrhea, immune deficiency, infections, and neurologic deficits. This condition has a material basis in homozygous or compound heterozygous mutation in the SLC46A1 gene on chromosome 17q11.2. It is also exactly synonymous with congenital defect of folate absorption and congenital folate malabsorption.

Glutamate formiminotransferase deficiency is a type of vitamin metabolic disorder and also falls under the category of autosomal recessive diseases. This condition is characterized by having a material basis in some form of autosomal recessive inheritance. Specifically, it is defined as a vitamin metabolic disorder marked by elevated formiminoglutamate levels in both urine and plasma, accompanied by variable intellectual, developmental, and hematological phenotypes due to homozygous or compound heterozygous mutation in the FTCD gene located on chromosome 21q22.3. Furthermore, this deficiency is known by several exact synonyms including Arakawa syndrome 1, FIGLUria, FTCD deficiency, formiminoglutamic acidemia, formiminoglutamic aciduria, formiminotransferase cyclodeaminase deficiency, and formiminotransferase deficiency syndrome.

Essential fructosuria is a type of autosomal recessive disease, carbohydrate metabolic disorder, and something that at least has a material basis in autosomal recessive inheritance. It is characterized by elevated fructose levels in the blood and urine following ingestion of fructose and related sugars, resulting from homozygous or compound heterozygous mutation in the KHK gene on chromosome 2p23.3. Essential fructosuria is also precisely known as fructokinase deficiency, hepatic fructokinase deficiency, and ketohexokinase deficiency.

Glutamate cysteine ligase deficiency is a type of autosomal recessive disease, which is also a type of amino acid metabolic disorder. It is characterized by something that at least has a material basis in some autosomal recessive inheritance. Specifically, this disorder is defined as an amino acid metabolic disorder characterized by decreased levels of cellular glutathione and gamma-glutamylcysteine, along with hemolytic anemia. This condition has its material basis in homozygous or compound heterozygous mutation in the GCLC gene on chromosome 6p12.1. Moreover, glutamate cysteine ligase deficiency is exactly synonymous with gamma-glutamylcysteine synthetase deficiency and hemolytic anemia due to gamma-glutamylcysteine synthetase deficiency.

Diffuse cystic renal dysplasia is a type of autosomal dominant disease, cystic kidney disease, and it is something that at least has a material basis in some form of autosomal dominant inheritance. It is characterized by nonsyndromic diffuse cystic dysplasia of the kidneys, which is due to a heterozygous mutation in the BICC1 gene on chromosome 10q21.1. This same mutation may also be found in unaffected parents, suggesting the disorder has incomplete penetrance or that additional environmental factors are required for the development of the disorder. This condition is also known by its exact synonyms: CYSRD, renal dysplasia diffuse cystic, and susceptibility to cystic renal dysplasia.

Neurofibromatosis Noonan syndrome is a type of autosomal dominant disease and also a type of RASopathy. This condition is characterized by having a material basis in autosomal dominant inheritance and exhibits phenotypes such as short stature and symptoms like muscle weakness and ptosis. It is defined as a RASopathy characterized by neurofibromatosis and manifestations of Noonan syndrome, which include short stature, ptosis, midface hypoplasia, webbed neck, learning disabilities, and muscle weakness, due to a heterozygous mutation in NF1 on chromosome 17q11.2. Neurofibromatosis Noonan syndrome is exactly synonymous with NFNS, Noonan Neurofibromatosis Syndrome, Neurofibromatosis Type 1-Noonan Syndrome, and Neurofibromatosis with Noonan Phenotype. It has exact matches in several databases, including GARD:372, MESH:C537393, OMIM:601321, ORDO:638, SNOMEDCT_US_2023_03_01:715344006, and UMLS_CUI:C2931482.

Hereditary mixed polyposis syndrome is a type of intestinal disease and has an exact synonym HMPS. It is defined as an intestinal disease characterized by a mixture of hyperplastic, atypical juvenile, and adenomatous polyps that are associated with an increased risk of developing colorectal cancer when untreated.

Hereditary Mixed Polyposis Syndrome 1 (HMPS1), also known precisely as CRAC1, HMPS1, Chromosome 15q13-q14 Duplication Syndrome, 40-KB, and Colorectal Adenoma and Carcinoma 1, is a type of Chromosomal Duplication Syndrome, as well as a type of Hereditary Mixed Polyposis Syndrome. It is characterized as a condition that intersects with entities having at least a material basis in some chromosome and entities having at least a material basis in some duplication. Specifically, HMPS1 is defined as a hereditary mixed polyposis syndrome that is caused by a heterozygous duplication of a region on chromosome 15q15.3-q22.1.

Hereditary Mixed Polyposis Syndrome 2 (HMPS2) is a type of hereditary mixed polyposis syndrome and an autosomal dominant disease. It specifically has a material basis in autosomal dominant inheritance. Furthermore, HMPS2 is defined as a hereditary mixed polyposis syndrome that results from a heterozygous mutation in the BMPR1A gene located on chromosome 10q23.2.

Potocki Shaffer Syndrome (PSS) is a type of syndrome and specifically, a chromosomal deletion syndrome. It is characterized by an intersection of conditions that have a material basis in some deletion and in some chromosome, indicating its complex nature involving chromosomal abnormalities. This syndrome is defined as a disorder marked by craniofacial abnormalities, developmental delay, intellectual disability, multiple exostoses, and biparietal foramina. It arises from heterozygosity for a contiguous gene deletion on chromosome 11p11.2. Moreover, Potocki Shaffer Syndrome is also known by exact synonyms including 11p11.2 deletion, PSS, and proximal 11p deletion syndrome, highlighting its diverse nomenclature based on its genetic characteristics.

Ayme Gripp syndrome is a type of autosomal dominant disease and a syndrome that has its material basis in autosomal dominant inheritance. It is characterized by congenital cataracts, sensorineural hearing loss, intellectual disability, seizures, brachycephaly, a distinctive flat facial appearance, and reduced growth, all of which are due to a heterozygous mutation in the MAF gene on chromosome 16q23.2. Additionally, Ayme Gripp syndrome has exact synonyms, including AYGRP and cataracts, congenital, with sensorineural deafness, Down syndrome-like facial appearance, short stature, and mental retardation.

Familial adult myoclonic epilepsy (FAME), also known as benign adult familial myoclonic epilepsy, familial cortical myoclonic tremor and epilepsy, BAFME, and FCMTE, is a type of adolescence-adult electroclinical syndrome. It is characterized by an adult-onset cortical myoclonus typically first seen as tremulous finger movements and myoclonus of the extremities. This condition is known to start during adult onset and is a form of something that at least exists from some adult onset.

Familial Adult Myoclonic Epilepsy 1 (FAME1) is a type of autosomal dominant disease and also falls under the broader category of familial adult myoclonic epilepsy. It is characterized by a material basis in some autosomal dominant inheritance and typically begins during adult onset. FAME1 is defined by a heterozygous 5-bp repeat expansion in the SAMD12 gene located on chromosome 8q24.11-q24.12. Moreover, FAME1 is known by several exact synonyms, including BAFME1, FCMTE1, benign adult familial myoclonic epilepsy 1, and familial cortical myoclonic tremor and epilepsy 1.

Familial adult myoclonic epilepsy 5 (FAME5), also known exactly as FCMTE5 and familial cortical myoclonic tremor and epilepsy 5, is a type of autosomal recessive disease that falls under the broader category of familial adult myoclonic epilepsy. It is characterized by the onset of seizures in adolescence, followed by the development of cortical myoclonic tremor. This condition specifically arises from homozygous or compound heterozygous mutation in the CNTN2 gene located on chromosome 1q32.1. Notably, FAME5's existence begins during adulthood and is attributed to some form of autosomal recessive inheritance.

Familial Adult Myoclonic Epilepsy 2 (FAME2) is a type of autosomal dominant disease and a specific form of familial adult myoclonic epilepsy. It is characterized by having a material basis in some autosomal dominant inheritance and its existence typically starts during adult onset. FAME2 is defined as a familial adult myoclonic epilepsy where the onset of tremor affects the fingers, hand, and voice in adolescence or young adulthood, followed by somewhat later onset of rhythmic myoclonic jerks and generalized tonic-clonic seizures. This condition has its material basis in a heterozygous 5-bp repeat expansion in the STARD7 gene on chromosome 2q11.2. It is also known by several exact synonyms including ADCME, BAFME2, FCMTE2, autosomal dominant cortical myoclonus and epilepsy, benign adult familial myoclonic epilepsy 2, and familial cortical myoclonic tremor and epilepsy 2.

Familial adult myoclonic epilepsy 4 (FAME4), also known exactly as FCMTE4 and familial cortical myoclonic tremor and epilepsy 4, is a subtype of autosomal dominant disease and familial adult myoclonic epilepsy. It is characterized by having a material basis in some autosomal dominant inheritance and typically begins during adult onset. The condition is defined by a heterozygous mutation in the YEATS2 gene on chromosome 3q27.1.

Familial adult myoclonic epilepsy 7 (FAME7) is a type of autosomal dominant disease and a form of familial adult myoclonic epilepsy. It is characterized by a material basis in autosomal dominant inheritance and typically begins in adulthood. The condition is defined by a familial adult myoclonic epilepsy that has a material basis in a heterozygous 5-bp repeat expansion in the RAPGEF2 gene on chromosome 4q32.1. FAME7 is also known by several exact synonyms, including BAFME7, FCMTE7, benign adult familial myoclonic epilepsy 7, and familial cortical myoclonic tremor and epilepsy 7.

Familial adult myoclonic epilepsy 3 (FAME3) is a type of autosomal dominant disease and is specifically categorized under familial adult myoclonic epilepsy. This condition is characterized by having a material basis in some autosomal dominant inheritance and its existence typically begins during adult onset. FAME3 is defined as a familial adult myoclonic epilepsy characterized by the onset between 10 and 40 years of age of cortical tremor, primarily affecting the hands and voice, which has a material basis in a heterozygous 5-bp repeat expansion in the MARCHF6 gene on chromosome 5p15.2. Additionally, FAME3 is exactly synonymous with FCMTE3 and familial cortical myoclonic tremor and epilepsy 3.

Familial Adult Myoclonic Epilepsy 6 (FAME6) is a specific type of familial adult myoclonic epilepsy and is categorized as an autosomal dominant disease. This condition is characterized by its genetic basis, which involves a heterozygous 5-bp repeat expansion in the TNRC6A gene located on chromosome 16p12.1. FAME6 typically begins during adulthood, indicating its adult onset nature. Furthermore, it is known by several exact synonyms, including BAFME6, FCMTE6, benign adult familial myoclonic epilepsy 6, and familial cortical myoclonic tremor and epilepsy 6.

Cleft palate, cardiac defects, and intellectual disability is a syndrome and a type of autosomal dominant disease, which also falls under the category of conditions that at least have a material basis in some autosomal dominant inheritance. This syndrome is characterized by a combination of congenital heart defects, variable cleft lip/palate, short stature, microcephaly, and digital anomalies, which has its material basis in a heterozygous mutation in the MEIS2 gene on chromosome 15q14. Additionally, it has the exact synonyms CPCMR, cardiac malformation, cleft lip/palate, microcephaly, and digital anomalies, as well as cleft palate, cardiac defects, and mental retardation.

Proprotein convertase 1 3 deficiency is a type of autosomal recessive disease, syndrome, and something that has a material basis in autosomal recessive inheritance. It is characterized as a syndrome marked by severe childhood obesity, hypoadrenalism, hypogonadism, reactive hypoglycaemia, and elevated circulating levels of certain prohormones, which is due to homozygous or compound heterozygous mutation in the PCSK1 gene on chromosome 5q15. Additionally, proprotein convertase 1 3 deficiency is also known by several exact synonyms including PCI deficiency, obesity and endocrinopathy due to impaired processing of prohormones, obesity due to prohormone convertase I deficiency, and obesity with impaired prohormone processing.

Van den Ende Gupta syndrome is a type of syndrome, specifically an autosomal recessive disease, which fundamentally has a material basis in autosomal recessive inheritance. It is characterized by severe contractural arachnodactyly, distinctive facial features, blepharophimosis, and the absence of neurological involvement, stemming from homozygous or compound heterozygous mutations in the SCARF2 gene on chromosome 22q11.21. This syndrome is also precisely known by several exact synonyms including Marden-Walker-like syndrome, Marden-Walker-like syndrome without psychomotor retardation, VDEGS, and blepharophimosis, arachnodactyly, and congenital contractures.

Ankyrin b related cardiac arrhythmia, also known as ankyrin-B syndrome, is a type of heart disease and autosomal dominant disease. It specifically involves a condition that at least has a material basis in some form of autosomal dominant inheritance. The disease is characterized by a broad spectrum of cardiac arrhythmias, including bradycardia, sinus arrhythmia, delayed conduction/conduction block, idiopathic ventricular fibrillation, and catecholaminergic polymorphic ventricular tachycardia. These symptoms have their material basis in a heterozygous mutation in the ANK2 gene located on chromosome 4q25-q26.

Long QT syndrome 4 is a type of long QT syndrome and is classified as an autosomal dominant disease. This classification is based on the fact that it at least has a material basis in some form of autosomal dominant inheritance. Furthermore, Long QT syndrome 4, which is exactly synonymous with LQT4, is defined by a long QT syndrome that has its material basis in a heterozygous mutation in the ANK2 gene located on chromosome 4q25-q26.

Loose anagen hair syndrome is a type of alopecia and has the definition of being an alopecia characterized by anagen phase (actively growing) hair that is easily pulled from the scalp, typically presenting in childhood in fair-haired individuals and improving with age. It also has the exact synonym "loose anagen syndrome."

Familial hypertryptophanemia is a type of autosomal recessive disease and an amino acid metabolic disorder, which essentially has a material basis in autosomal recessive inheritance. It is characterized by elevated urine and plasma tryptophan levels, resulting from homozygous or compound heterozygous mutation in the TDO2 gene located on chromosome 4q32.1. This condition is also precisely known by its synonym, HYPTRP.

:chromosome_2q37_deletion_syndrome rdfs:subClassOf :chromosomal_deletion_syndrome ;
    :has_definition "A chromosomal deletion syndrome characterized by variable features, likely resulting from different sized deletions, including; brachydactyly type E, short stature, mild to moderate intellectual disability, behavioral abnormalities, and dysmorphic facial features that has_material_basis_in heterozygosity for a contiguous deletion of several genes on chromosome 2q37.2." ;
    :has_exact_synonym "2q37 microdeletion syndrome",
        "Albright hereditary osteodystrophy type 3",
        "Albright hereditary osteodystrophy-like syndrome",
        "Albright's hereditary osteodystrophy-like syndrome",
        "BDMR",
        "Brachydactyly-intellectual disability syndrome",
        "Del(2)(q37)",
        "deletion 2q37",
        "monosomy 2q37qter" .
text: Chromosome 2q37 deletion syndrome is a type of chromosomal deletion syndrome characterized by a variety of features potentially due to deletions of different sizes. These features include brachydactyly type E, short stature, mild to moderate intellectual disability, behavioral abnormalities, and dysmorphic facial features. The syndrome's material basis is in heterozygosity for a contiguous deletion of several genes on chromosome 2q37.2. Chromosome 2q37 deletion syndrome is also known by several exact synonyms: 2q37 microdeletion syndrome, Albright hereditary osteodystrophy type 3, Albright hereditary osteodystrophy-like syndrome, Albright's hereditary osteodystrophy-like syndrome, BDMR, Brachydactyly-intellectual disability syndrome, Del(2)(q37), deletion 2q37, and monosomy 2q37qter.

Oculoectodermal syndrome is a type of ectodermal dysplasia characterized by epibulbar dermoids and aplasia cutis congenita. This condition has a material basis in somatic mosaic mutation in the KRAS gene on chromosome 12p12.1. It is also precisely known by two other names: Toriello-Lacassie-Droste syndrome and aplasia cutis congenita-epibulbar dermoids syndrome.

Oblique facial clefting 1 is a type of orofacial cleft, autosomal dominant disease, and something that at least has a material basis in some autosomal dominant inheritance. It is defined as an orofacial cleft characterized by a congenital unilateral or bilateral oculo-facial defect starting at the upper lip lateral to the Cupid's bow, extending lateral to the nasal wing, and ending at the lower eyelid lateral to the inferior punctum. This condition has its material basis in a heterozygous mutation in the SPECC1L gene on chromosome 22q11.23. Additionally, oblique facial clefting 1 has an exact synonym, Tessier number 4 facial cleft.

Bothnian type palmoplantar keratoderma (PPKB) is a specific form of nonepidermolytic palmoplantar keratoderma which is also classified as an autosomal dominant disease. It is a condition that inherently has a material basis in autosomal dominant inheritance. This particular type of keratoderma is characterized by a diffuse nonepidermolytic form where the affected areas become white and spongy upon exposure to water due to a heterozygous mutation in the AQP5 gene on chromosome 12q13.12. Additionally, it is precisely known by the exact synonyms "PPKB" and "diffuse palmoplantar keratoderma, Bothnian type."

Focal nonepidermolytic palmoplantar keratoderma is a specific type of nonepidermolytic palmoplantar keratoderma, characterized by localized areas of hyperkeratosis primarily on pressure points and sites of recurrent friction. It is also precisely known by the synonyms FNEPPK and isolated focal non-epidermolytic palmoplantar keratoderma.

Focal nonepidermolytic palmoplantar keratoderma 1 (FNEPPK1) is a type of autosomal dominant disease and a specific form of focal nonepidermolytic palmoplantar keratoderma. It is characterized by a condition that inherently has a material basis in autosomal dominant inheritance. Notably, FNEPPK1 is defined by a focal nonepidermolytic palmoplantar keratoderma that arises from a heterozygous mutation in the KRT16 gene located on chromosome 17q21.2.

Focal or diffuse nonepidermolytic palmoplantar keratoderma (PPKNEFD) is a type of nonepidermolytic palmoplantar keratoderma and falls under the category of autosomal dominant diseases. It is characterized by focal or diffuse palmoplantar keratodermas with minor or absent nail changes, which have a material basis in heterozygous mutation in the KRT6C gene on chromosome 12q13.13. This condition is an example of something that at least has a material basis in some form of autosomal dominant inheritance. Additionally, PPKNEFD is also known by the exact synonym "autosomal dominant focal non-epidermolytic palmoplantar keratoderma with plantar blistering."

Focal nonepidermolytic palmoplantar keratoderma 2 (FNEPPK2) is a type of autosomal dominant disease, specifically a subtype of focal nonepidermolytic palmoplantar keratoderma, which inherently has a material basis in some form of autosomal dominant inheritance. It is defined as a focal nonepidermolytic palmoplantar keratoderma with its material basis in a heterozygous mutation in the TRPV3 gene on chromosome 17p13.2.

Kagami Ogata Syndrome (KOS) is a type of syndrome characterized by a variety of symptoms including polyhydramnios, fetal macrosomia, abdominal wall defects, skeletal abnormalities, feeding difficulties and impaired swallowing, dysmorphic features, developmental delay, and intellectual disability. This condition has a material basis in a heterozygous mutation in an imprinting region on chromosome 14q32.

Temple syndrome is a type of syndrome defined by a range of characteristics including low birth weight, hypotonia and motor delay, feeding problems early in life, early puberty, and a significantly reduced final height. It has a material basis in a heterozygous mutation in an imprinting region on chromosome 14q32.

Mulchandani Bhoj Conlin Syndrome is a type of syndrome characterized by prenatal growth restriction, severe short stature with proportional head circumference, and profound feeding difficulty. It has a material basis in a heterozygous mutation in an imprinting region on chromosome 20q11-q13. The syndrome is also exactly known as MBCS, UPD(20)mat, maternal UPD(20), and maternal uniparental disomy of chromosome 20.

Schaaf-Yang syndrome is a type of syndrome characterized by delayed psychomotor development, impaired intellectual development, hypotonia, and behavioral abnormalities. This syndrome has its material basis in a heterozygous mutation in the maternally imprinted gene MAGEL2 on chromosome 15q11.2. Schaaf-Yang syndrome is also exactly synonymous with MAGEL2-related Prader-Willi-like syndrome (PWLS), MAGEL2-related PWLS, PWLS, and SHFYNG.
Cryptophthalmia is a type of physical disorder characterized by ocular dysplasia with eyelid malformation, and it is exactly synonymous with cryptophthalmos.

Isolated cryptophthalmia is a type of cryptophthalmia characterized by the absence of the eyelids with skin covering the eye, and often an underlying malformed eye. It is also exactly known as CRYPTOP and as unilateral or bilateral isolated cryptophthalmos.

Partial cryptophthalmia is a type of isolated cryptophthalmia characterized by an ill-defined upper eyelid that is completely fused, often over an abnormally developed globe and a keratinized cornea. It is also known as incomplete cryptophthalmos.

Complete cryptophthalmia is a subtype of isolated cryptophthalmia. It is defined as an isolated cryptophthalmia where there is a failure of the lid folds and globe to form, resulting in skin extending from the brow to the cheek without identifiable adnexal structures. Often, there is also the presence of a vestigial ocular structure or cyst within the socket.
Congenital symblepharon, a type of isolated cryptophthalmia, is defined by the fusion of the upper eyelid skin to the superior aspect of the globe, often associated with microphthalmia.

Amelogenesis imperfecta type 3 is a type of amelogenesis imperfecta characterized by soft enamel that is initially of normal thickness but is lost soon after tooth eruption. It has the exact synonyms AI3 and hypocalcified amelogenesis imperfecta.

Amelogenesis imperfecta type 3c is a type of autosomal recessive disease, specifically a subtype of amelogenesis imperfecta type 3, which is characterized by its basis in autosomal recessive inheritance. It is defined as an amelogenesis imperfecta type 3 distinguished by hypocalcified enamel affecting both the primary and secondary dentition, resulting from a homozygous mutation in the RELT gene located on chromosome 11q13. Additionally, amelogenesis imperfecta type 3c is exactly synonymous with AI3C, amelogenesis imperfecta type IIIC, and autosomal recessive amelogenesis imperfecta hypocalcification type.

Jacobsen syndrome is a type of chromosomal deletion syndrome characterized by growth retardation, psychomotor retardation, distinctive facial features, skeletal abnormalities, and isoimmune thrombocytopenia. This condition has a material basis in the deletion of the terminal chromosome 11q. It is also precisely referred to as Jacobsen distal 11q deletion syndrome, chromosome 11q deletion syndrome, and partial 11q monosomy syndrome.

Geleophysic dysplasia is a type of bone development disease characterized by short-limb dwarfism, brachydactyly, cardiac valvular disease, characteristic facial appearance, skin thickening, and laryngotracheal stenosis. It has exact synonyms including GPHYSD and geleophysic dwarfism.

Geleophysic dysplasia 1, which is exactly synonymous with GPHYSD1, is classified as a type of geleophysic dysplasia and falls under the broader category of autosomal recessive diseases. It specifically entails a condition that originates from a material basis in autosomal recessive inheritance. The definition of geleophysic dysplasia 1 includes being a geleophysic dysplasia characterized by having its material basis in homozygous or compound heterozygous mutations in the ADAMTSL2 gene located on chromosome 9q34.2.

Geleophysic dysplasia 2 is a type of geleophysic dysplasia, and it is also known as GPHYSD2. It is characterized as a type of autosomal dominant disease and something that at least has a material basis in some autosomal dominant inheritance. Specifically, geleophysic dysplasia 2 is defined as a geleophysic dysplasia that has its material basis in heterozygous mutation in exon 41 or 42 of the FBN1 gene on chromosome 15q21.1.

Geleophysic dysplasia 3, which has the exact synonym GPHYSD3, is a type of geleophysic dysplasia. It is classified as an autosomal dominant disease and is specifically a type of condition that has a material basis in autosomal dominant inheritance. The definition of geleophysic dysplasia 3 is a geleophysic dysplasia that has its material basis in a heterozygous mutation in the LTBP3 gene on chromosome 11q13.1.

Familial Episodic Pain Syndrome is a type of neuropathy with a definition as a peripheral neuropathy characterized by recurrent, stereotyped, episodic intense pain. This pain predominantly occurs in either the upper body or lower limbs and is triggered or exacerbated by fatigue, cold exposure, fasting, weather changes, and/or physical stress or exertion. Familial Episodic Pain Syndrome also has an exact synonym, FEPS.

Familial Episodic Pain Syndrome 1 (FEPS1) is a type of autosomal dominant disease and also falls under the broader category of familial episodic pain syndromes. It arises from a material basis that includes at least some aspects of autosomal dominant inheritance. FEPS1 is characterized by the onset in infancy of episodic debilitating upper body pain, which is triggered by fasting, cold, and physical stress. This syndrome has its material basis in a heterozygous mutation in the TRPA1 gene located on chromosome 8q13.

Familial Episodic Pain Syndrome 2 (FEPS2) is a type of autosomal dominant disease and a specific form of familial episodic pain syndrome, indicating it is a condition with at least a material basis in some form of autosomal dominant inheritance. It is characterized by adult-onset of paroxysmal pain, primarily affecting the distal lower extremities, and this condition has a material basis in a heterozygous mutation in the SCN10A gene on chromosome 3p22.

Familial Episodic Pain Syndrome 3 (FEPS3) is classified as a type of autosomal dominant disease, specifically falling under the broader category of familial episodic pain syndromes. It is identified by a condition that inherently has a material basis in autosomal dominant inheritance. FEPS3 is characterized by an early childhood onset of intense episodic pain predominantly affecting the distal lower extremities, and occasionally the upper extremities, with episodes of pain lasting several days and being exacerbated by fatigue. This condition is directly attributed to a heterozygous mutation in the SCN11A gene located on chromosome 3p22.

Eiken syndrome is a type of autosomal recessive and bone development disease, essentially rooted in some form of autosomal recessive inheritance. It is defined as a bone development disease characterized by severely delayed ossification primarily of the epiphyses, pelvis, hands, and feet along with abnormal bone modeling of the hands and feet, resulting from homozygous or compound heterozygous mutation in the PTHR1 gene on chromosome 3p21.31. Furthermore, Eiken syndrome is precisely synonymous with Eiken skeletal dysplasia and bone modeling defect of hands and feet.

Pancreatic hypoplasia diabetes congenital heart disease syndrome is a type of syndrome that falls under the categories of autosomal dominant disease and physical disorder. It is characterized by being a condition that at least has a material basis in some autosomal dominant inheritance and has basis in some abnormality of prenatal development or birth. Specifically, it is a syndrome characterized by partial pancreatic agenesis, diabetes mellitus, and heart anomalies, which has its material basis in a heterozygous mutation in the GATA6 gene on chromosome 18q11.2. This syndrome is also known by several exact synonyms, including HDCA, PACHD, Yorifuji-Okuno syndrome, congenital heart defects and other congenital anomalies, congenital pancreatic hypoplasia with diabetes mellitus and congenital heart disease, as well as pancreatic agenesis and congenital heart defects.

Aminoglycoside induced deafness, also known exactly as streptomycin ototoxicity or streptomycin-induced deafness, is a specific form of drug-induced hearing loss. It is defined as a hearing loss triggered by therapeutic doses of aminoglycoside antibiotics. This condition is caused by mutations in the mitochondrial genes MTRNR1 or MTCO1, in combination with a homozygous mutation in TRMU on chromosome 22q13.31.

X-linked deafness 4 is a type of X-linked nonsyndromic deafness with a definition that delineates it as an X-linked nonsyndromic deafness characterized by progressive hearing loss with postlingual onset, where the onset occurs earlier in males compared to females. This condition has a material basis in a mutation in the SMPX gene on chromosome Xp22.12. Furthermore, X-linked deafness 4 is also known by exact synonyms such as DFN6, DFNX4, X-linked progressive deafness 6, and nonsyndromic sensorineural progressive deafness 6.

X-linked deafness 3 is a type of X-linked nonsyndromic deafness characterized by congenital, bilateral, profound sensorineural hearing loss in males and bilateral, mild to moderate high-frequency sensorineural hearing impairment with later onset in heterozygous females. This condition has its material basis in a mutation in a region on chromosome Xp21.2. It is also known by its exact synonyms DFN4, DFNX3, and congenital sensorineural X-linked deafness 4.

:x_linked_deafness_2 rdfs:subClassOf :x_linked_nonsyndromic_deafness ;
    :has_definition "An X-linked nonsyndromic deafness characterized by progressive conductive and sensorineural hearing loss and pathognomonic inner ear anomalies that has_material_basis_in hemizygous or homozygous mutation in POU3F4 or upstream regulatory elements of this gene on chromosome Xq21.1." ;
    :has_exact_synonym "DFN3",
        "DFNX2",
        "Nance deafness",
        "X-linked deafness type 2",
        "X-linked mixed conductive and neurosensory deafness",
        "X-linked mixed conductive and neurosensory hearing loss",
        "X-linked mixed conductive and sensorineural deafness",
        "X-linked mixed conductive and sensorineural hearing loss",
        "X-linked sensorineural deafness",
        "X-linked stapes gusher syndrome",
        "conductive deafness 3 with stapes fixation",
        "conductive deafness with stapes fixation",
        "mixed deafness with perilymphatic gusher" .
text: X-linked deafness 2 is a type of X-linked nonsyndromic deafness characterized by progressive conductive and sensorineural hearing loss and pathognomonic inner ear anomalies. This condition has a material basis in hemizygous or homozygous mutation in the POU3F4 gene or upstream regulatory elements of this gene on chromosome Xq21.1. It is also known by several exact synonyms, including DFN3, DFNX2, Nance deafness, X-linked deafness type 2, X-linked mixed conductive and neurosensory deafness, X-linked mixed conductive and neurosensory hearing loss, X-linked mixed conductive and sensorineural deafness, X-linked mixed conductive and sensorineural hearing loss, X-linked sensorineural deafness, X-linked stapes gusher syndrome, conductive deafness 3 with stapes fixation, conductive deafness with stapes fixation, and mixed deafness with perilymphatic gusher.

X-linked deafness 7 is a type of X-linked nonsyndromic deafness, characterized by congenital, bilateral, mixed or conductive hearing loss and other ear anomalies. This condition is caused by homozygous or hemizygous mutation in the GPRASP2 gene on chromosome Xq22.1. It is also known by its exact synonyms: DFNX7 and X-linked external auditory canal atresia-dilated internal auditory canal-facial dysmorphism syndrome.

X-linked deafness 1 is a type of X-linked nonsyndromic deafness characterized by congenital profound sensorineural hearing loss in males and mild to moderate high-frequency hearing loss in heterozygous females, which has its material basis in mutation in the PRPS1 gene on chromosome Xq22.3. Furthermore, X-linked deafness 1 is exactly synonymous with DFN2, DFNX1, and X-linked sensorineural congenital deafness 2.

X-linked deafness 6 is a type of X-linked nonsyndromic deafness and has the exact synonym DFNX6. It is defined as an X-linked nonsyndromic deafness characterized by severe bilateral sensorineural hearing loss with cochlear malformation in males, and mild to moderate hearing loss in females with later onset. This condition has a material basis in a mutation in the COL4A6 gene on chromosome Xq22.3.

X-linked deafness 5 is a type of X-linked recessive disease, neuropathy, and something that at least has a material basis in some X-linked recessive inheritance. It is defined as a neuropathy characterized by childhood onset of auditory neuropathy and later onset of distal sensory impairment due to diffuse peripheral neuropathy. This condition has a material basis in hemizygous or homozygous mutation in the AIFM1 gene on chromosome Xq26.1. X-linked deafness 5 is also known by its exact synonyms: AUNX1, DFNX5, X-linked HSAN with deafness, X-linked auditory neuropathy 1 with peripheral sensory neuropathy, and X-linked auditory neuropathy with peripheral sensory neuropathy type 1.

Cerebellar ataxia type 42 is a type of autosomal dominant cerebellar ataxia that is defined as an autosomal dominant cerebellar ataxia characterized by gait instability, dysarthria, nystagmus, and saccadic pursuits with variable age of onset and severity, and slow progression. This condition has its material basis in a heterozygous mutation of the CACNA1G gene on chromosome 17q21. Additionally, cerebellar ataxia type 42 has the exact synonym SCA42.

Cerebellar ataxia type 47, which is an example of autosomal dominant cerebellar ataxia, is defined as an autosomal dominant cerebellar ataxia that typically begins in adulthood with slowly progressive cerebellar ataxia. In some instances, it may start earlier, accompanied by delayed motor development and short stature, and this condition is caused by a heterozygous mutation in the PUM1 gene located on chromosome 1p35.2. Additionally, cerebellar ataxia type 47 is precisely synonymous with SCA47.

Cerebellar ataxia type 41 is a type of autosomal dominant cerebellar ataxia and has an exact synonym SCA41. It is defined as an autosomal dominant cerebellar ataxia that has its material basis in a heterozygous mutation in the TRPC3 gene on chromosome 4q27.

Cerebellar ataxia type 43 is a type of autosomal dominant cerebellar ataxia, which is defined as an autosomal dominant cerebellar ataxia characterized by adult-onset, slowly progressive, gait and limb ataxia. This condition is often associated with peripheral neuropathy, typically affecting the motor system, and has its material basis in a heterozygous mutation in the MME gene on chromosome 3q25.2. Additionally, cerebellar ataxia type 43 has the exact synonym SCA43.

Cerebellar ataxia type 48, which has the exact synonym SCA48, is a type of autosomal dominant cerebellar ataxia. It is characterized by having at least the symptom of some ataxia. Furthermore, it is defined as an autosomal dominant cerebellar ataxia that typically begins in mid-adulthood with symptoms of gait ataxia and/or cognitive-affective issues, and its material basis is a heterozygous mutation in the STUB1 gene located on chromosome 16p13.3.

Cerebellar ataxia type 9 is a type of autosomal dominant cerebellar ataxia and has the exact synonym SCA9. It is defined as an autosomal dominant cerebellar ataxia characterized by adult onset of ataxia and imbalance, along with demyelinating lesions visible on brain MRI.

Mitochondrial complex V ATP synthase deficiency mitochondrial type 1 is a specific type of mitochondrial complex V ATP synthase deficiency. This deficiency is characterized by lactic acidemia, hypotonia, and neurodegenerative disease, which stems from a mutation in the mitochondrial gene MTATP6. Additionally, it is exactly synonymous with MC5DM1.

Mitochondrial complex V ATP synthase deficiency nuclear type 6, also precisely known as MC5DN6, is a subtype of mitochondrial complex V ATP synthase deficiency. It is defined as a mitochondrial complex V (ATP synthase) deficiency characterized by the episodic regression of gross motor skills beginning in early childhood, which has a material basis in homozygous or compound heterozygous mutation in the ATP5MD gene located on chromosome 10q24.33.

Adult onset ataxia and polyneuropathy is a type of mitochondrial metabolism disease, and it also falls into a category of conditions that begin in adulthood. It is defined as a mitochondrial metabolism disease characterized by the adult onset of ataxia and polyneuropathy, which is caused by a heteroplasmic mutation in the mitochondrial gene MTATP6.

Mitochondrial nonsyndromic sensorineural deafness is a type of sensorineural hearing loss. It is defined as a sensorineural hearing loss that has its material basis in mutation in one of several different mitochondrial genes, including MTRNR1, MTTS1, MTCO1, MTTH, MTND1, and MTTI.

Autosomal mitochondrial sensorineural deafness is a type of digenic disease, sensorineural hearing loss, and something that at least has a material basis in digenic inheritance. It is defined as a sensorineural hearing loss characterized by progressive, severe to profound deafness that has a material basis in digenic inheritance of mutations in the mitochondrial gene MTRNR1 and an unidentified nuclear gene.

Infantile hypertrophic cardiomyopathy is a type of hypertrophic cardiomyopathy characterized by isolated hypertrophic cardiomyopathy and congestive heart failure. It has a material basis in mutation in the overlapping mitochondrial genes MTATP6 and MTATP8.

Leber plus disease is a type of syndrome characterized by Leber's hereditary optic neuropathy in combination with other serious systemic or neurological abnormalities. It is also exactly synonymous with LHON plus disease.

Leber hereditary optic neuropathy and dystonia is a type of Leber plus disease characterized by Leber hereditary optic neuropathy and dystonia. This condition has a material basis in mutations in the mitochondrial genes MTND6, MTND4, MTND1, or MTND3 that make up the mitochondrial complex I. It is also known by exact synonyms such as LDYT, Leber optic atrophy and dystonia, Leber optic atrophy with dystonia, Marsden syndrome, and familial dystonia with visual failure and striatal lucencies.

Leber hereditary optic neuropathy with demyelinating disease of CNS is a type of Leber plus disease, which is defined as a Leber plus disease characterized by Leber hereditary optic neuropathy and demyelination in the central nervous system.

Y linked deafness is a type of nonsyndromic deafness, a Y linked monogenic disease, and something that at least has a material basis in some Y linked inheritance. It is defined as a nonsyndromic deafness characterized by a Y-linked inheritance mode. Additionally, Y linked deafness has an exact synonym, DFNY.

Y linked deafness 2 is a type of Y linked deafness, which is characterized by male-limited bilateral progressive sensorineural hearing loss of variable severity, with onset in the third to fifth decades of life. This condition has its material basis in a mutation in the TBL1Y gene on chromosome Yp11.2. Furthermore, Y linked deafness 2 is also known by its exact synonym, DFNY2.

Y-linked deafness 1 is a type of Y-linked deafness, which is characterized by male-limited postlingual progressive sensorineural hearing loss of variable severity, with the onset occurring in the first to third decades of life. It is also known by its exact synonym, DFNY1.

46 XX sex reversal is a type of gonadal dysgenesis, which is defined as a gonadal dysgenesis characterized by the presentation of an XX karyotype and male external genitalia that can range from normal to ambiguous. It has several exact synonyms including 46,XX testicular DSD, 46,XX testicular disorder of sex development, De la Chapelle syndrome, SRXX, and XX male syndrome.

46 XX sex reversal 1 is a type of X-linked dominant disease and a specific form of 46 XX sex reversal. This condition is characterized by a material basis in X-linked dominant inheritance. It is defined as a 46,XX sex reversal that results from the translocation of SRY onto the X chromosome. Additionally, 46 XX sex reversal 1 is exactly synonymous with SRXX1.

46 XX sex reversal 3 is a type of X linked dominant disease and also a type of 46 XX sex reversal. It is categorized under conditions that at least have a material basis in X linked dominant inheritance. Furthermore, 46 XX sex reversal 3, which has the exact synonym SRXX3, is defined as a 46,XX sex reversal that results from genomic duplications or deletions in the SOX3 regulatory region on chromosome Xq26.

46 XX sex reversal 2 is a type of autosomal dominant disease, which is a specific kind of 46 XX sex reversal and is characterized by a condition that fundamentally requires an autosomal dominant inheritance mechanism. It is defined as a 46,XX sex reversal that arises from a heterozygous duplication or triplication of a 68-kb regulatory region located -584 to -516 kb upstream of the SOX9 gene on chromosome 17q24. Additionally, 46 XX sex reversal 2 is precisely referred to by the synonyms SRXX2 and chromosome 17q24 duplication syndrome.

46 XX sex reversal 4 is a type of autosomal dominant disease and a type of 46 XX sex reversal, which at least has a material basis in some autosomal dominant inheritance. It is defined as a 46,XX sex reversal that has its material basis in a heterozygous mutation in the NR5A1 gene on chromosome 9q33.3. Moreover, 46 XX sex reversal 4 has the exact synonym SRXX4.

X-linked cardiac valvular dysplasia is a type of heart valve disease, which is also a form of X-linked monogenic disease and is related to X-linked inheritance. It is defined as a heart valve disease characterized by multivalvular dysplasia and regurgitation, showing more severe phenotypes in hemizygous males compared to heterozygous females, and is caused by a mutation in the FLNA gene on chromosome Xq28. This condition is known by several exact synonyms, including CVD1, Dystrophie valvulaire associée à FLNA, EDS 5, Ehlers-Danlos syndrome, type 5, FLNA-related X-linked myxomatous valvular dysplasia, FLNA-related valvular dystrophy, Filamin A-related X-linked myxomatous valvular dysplasia, and XMVD.

X-linked VACTERL association is a type of VACTERL association and also a type of X-linked recessive disease. It is characterized by something that at least has a material basis in some X-linked recessive inheritance. X-linked VACTERL association is defined as a VACTERL association that has its material basis in mutation in the ZIC3 gene on chromosome Xq26.3 or the FANCB gene on chromosome Xp22.2. It has exact synonyms including VACTERL association, X-linked with or without hydrocephalus, and VACTERLX.

X-linked thrombocytopenia with beta thalassemia is a type of hematopoietic system disease, which also falls under the category of X-linked recessive diseases. It is characterized by a condition that essentially has a material basis in some form of X-linked recessive inheritance. Specifically, this disease is defined as a hematopoietic system disease characterized by variable thrombocytopenia, hemolytic anemia, splenomegaly, and abnormalities in hemoglobin chain synthesis resulting in an imbalance between the alpha and beta chains. This condition is caused by homozygous or hemizygous missense mutations in the DNA binding domain of the GATA1 gene on chromosome Xp11.23. Furthermore, X-linked thrombocytopenia with beta thalassemia is known by several exact synonyms including GATA1-related X-linked cytopenia, XLTT, beta-thalassemia-X-linked thrombocytopenia syndrome, and thrombocytopenia, platelet dysfunction, hemolysis, and imbalanced globin synthesis.

X-linked properdin deficiency is a type of X-linked recessive disease, complement deficiency, and something that at least has a material basis in some X-linked recessive inheritance. It is defined as a complement deficiency characterized by decreased plasma levels of complement factor properdin and increased susceptibility to Neisseria species infections, which has its material basis in homozygous or hemizygous mutation in PFC on chromosome Xp11.23. Additionally, X-linked properdin deficiency has exact synonyms: CFPD and complement factor properdin deficiency.

46 XY sex reversal 6 is a type of autosomal dominant disease and a subtype of 46 XY sex reversal, which essentially has a material basis in autosomal dominant inheritance. This condition is characterized by an XY karyotype, phenotypically female genitalia, and the failure to develop secondary sexual characteristics at puberty, including menstruation, due to a heterozygous mutation in the MAP3K1 gene on chromosome 5q11.2. Furthermore, 46 XY sex reversal 6 is exactly synonymous with 46,XY gonadal dysgenesis, partial or complete, MAP3K1-related; 46,XY sex reversal, partial or complete, MAP3K1-related; and SRXY6.

46 XY sex reversal 9 is a type of autosomal dominant disease and a specific form of 46 XY sex reversal. It is characterized by an XY karyotype, phenotypically female genitalia, and a failure to develop secondary sexual characteristics at puberty, including menstruation. This condition has a material basis in heterozygous mutation in the ZFPM2 gene on chromosome 8q23.1. It is also known by its exact synonyms, 46,XY sex reversal, ZFPM2-related and SRXY9.
