46 XY sex reversal 4 is a type of chromosomal deletion syndrome and a specific form of 46 XY sex reversal. This condition is part of a category that intersects entities having a material basis in some form of deletion and chromosome. It is characterized by an XY karyotype, phenotypically female genitalia and the failure to develop secondary sexual characteristics at puberty, including menstruation, but without the additional features of chromosome 9p deletion syndrome. This is due to a heterozygous deletion of a region on chromosome 9p. The condition is also precisely known as 46,XY gonadal dysgenesis, partial or complete, with 9p24.3 deletion, SRXY4, and chromosome 9p24.3 deletion syndrome.

46 XY sex reversal 3 is a type of autosomal dominant disease and also a specific form of 46 XY sex reversal. This condition is an example of disorders that have a material basis in autosomal dominant inheritance. It is defined as a 46 XY sex reversal characterized by an XY karyotype, with individuals presenting phenotypically female genitalia and experiencing failure to develop secondary sexual characteristics at puberty, including menstruation. This condition is caused by a heterozygous mutation in the NR5A1 gene located on chromosome 9q33.3. Furthermore, 46 XY sex reversal 3 is known by several exact synonyms, including 46,XY gonadal dysgenesis, partial or complete, with or without adrenal failure; 46,XY sex reversal, partial or complete, NR5A1-related; SRXY3; disorder of sex development, 46,XY, NR5A1-related; and sex reversal, XY, with or without adrenal failure.

46 XY sex reversal 8 is a type of autosomal recessive disease and also falls under the broader category of 46 XY sex reversals. It is specifically a condition with a material basis in some form of autosomal recessive inheritance. The defining characteristics of 46 XY sex reversal 8 include an XY karyotype, phenotypically female genitalia, and the failure to develop secondary sexual characteristics at puberty, including menstruation. This condition is caused by homozygous or compound heterozygous mutation in the AKR1C2 gene located on chromosome 10p15.1. Additionally, 46 XY sex reversal 8 is precisely synonymous with SRXY8, TDD, and male pseudohermaphroditism due to deficiency of testicular 17,20-desmolase.

46 XY sex reversal 7 is a type of autosomal recessive disease, which is also a subtype of 46 XY sex reversal, and it specifically falls under the category of conditions with at least a material basis in autosomal recessive inheritance. This condition is characterized by an XY karyotype, phenotypically female genitalia, and the failure to develop secondary sexual characteristics at puberty, including menstruation, due to homozygous or compound heterozygous mutation in DHH on chromosome 12q13.12. Additionally, 46 XY sex reversal 7 is synonymously known as 46,XY gonadal dysgenesis, partial or complete, DHH-related; 46,XY sex reversal, partial or complete, DHH-related; GDXYM; SRXY7; and gonadal dysgenesis, XY, male limited.

46 XY sex reversal 10 is a type of autosomal dominant disease, chromosomal deletion syndrome, and 46 XY sex reversal. It is characterized as something that intersects with conditions that have a material basis in some deletion and chromosome, and it also has a basis in autosomal dominant inheritance. Additionally, 46 XY sex reversal 10 is defined as a 46 XY sex reversal characterized by an XY karyotype, phenotypically female genitalia, and failure to develop secondary sexual characteristics at puberty including menstruation due to a heterozygous deletion of a region upstream of the SOX9 gene on chromosome 17q24. This condition is also known by its exact synonyms SRXY10 and chromosome 17q24 deletion syndrome.

46 XY sex reversal 5 is a type of autosomal recessive disease, also known as 46 XY sex reversal, which is essentially a condition that has a material basis in autosomal recessive inheritance. It is characterized by an XY karyotype, phenotypically female genitalia, and the failure to develop secondary sexual characteristics at puberty, including menstruation, due to homozygous or compound heterozygous mutation in the CBX2 gene on chromosome 17q25.3. This condition is exactly synonymous with several terms including 46,XY gonadal dysgenesis, complete, CBX2-related; 46,XY sex reversal, CBX2-related; SRXY5; disorder of sex development, 46,XY, CBX2-related; and sex reversal, XY, CBX2-related.

46 XY sex reversal 2 is a type of X-linked monogenic disease, a subtype of 46 XY sex reversal, and is associated with X-linked inheritance mechanisms. It is defined as a 46 XY sex reversal characterized by an XY karyotype, phenotypically female genitalia, and failure to develop secondary sexual characteristics at puberty including menstruation, which has its material basis in hemizygous duplication of the NR0B1 gene on chromosome Xp21.2. Moreover, 46 XY sex reversal 2 is exactly synonymized with 46,XY sex reversal, DAX1-related; 46XY sex reversal 2, dosage-sensitive; DSS; SRXY2; and dosage-sensitive sex reversal.

46 XY sex reversal 1 is a type of Y linked monogenic disease, which is a specific category of 46 XY sex reversal. This condition is attributed to having at least a material basis in some Y linked inheritance. It is defined as a 46 XY sex reversal characterized by an XY karyotype, phenotypically female genitalia, and the failure to develop secondary sexual characteristics at puberty, including menstruation. This is due to a hemizygous mutation in the SRY gene on chromosome Yp11.2. Furthermore, 46 XY sex reversal 1 is precisely synonymous with 46,XY gonadal dysgenesis, complete, SRY-related; 46,XY sex reversal, SRY-related; and SRXY1.

X-linked panhypopituitarism is a type of panhypopituitarism, as well as a type of X-linked monogenic disease, and it is something that at least has a material basis in some X-linked inheritance. It is defined as a panhypopituitarism that has its material basis in duplications in the SOX3 gene on chromosome Xq27.1. Additionally, X-linked panhypopituitarism has the exact synonyms PHPX and pituitary dwarfism IV.

TARP syndrome is a type of X-linked monogenic disease and is also considered a syndrome that fundamentally has a material basis in some X-linked inheritance. It is defined as a syndrome characterized by talipes equinovarus, atrial septal defect, Robin sequence (micrognathia, cleft palate, and glossoptosis), and persistent left superior vena cava, typically resulting in late prenatal or early postnatal mortality. This syndrome has its material basis in a hemizygous mutation in the RBM10 gene on chromosome Xp11.3. TARP syndrome is also known by several exact synonyms, including Pierre Robin sequence-congenital heart defect-talipes syndrome, Pierre Robin syndrome-congenital heart defect-talipes syndrome, TARPS, and talipes equinovarus-atrial septal defect-Robin sequence-persistence of the left superior vena cava syndrome.

Waisman syndrome is identified as a type of syndrome that falls under the category of X-linked recessive diseases, indicating it has a material basis in X-linked recessive inheritance. It is characterized by delayed psychomotor development, impaired intellectual development, and early-onset Parkinson disease, stemming from hemizygous or homozygous mutations in the RAB39B gene on chromosome Xq28. Additionally, Waisman syndrome is also known by its exact synonyms: Laxova-Opitz syndrome and early-onset parkinsonism-intellectual disability syndrome.

Otopalatodigital syndrome spectrum disorder is a type of bone development disease that is characterized by typical facial anomalies and a generalized bone dysplasia with osteodysplastic changes. This includes varying combinations and degrees of undertubulation of the long bones, cortical irregularity, and campomelia. Most, but not all, subtypes of this disorder are associated with mutations in FLNA on chromosome Xq28. It is also known by exact synonyms such as OPD spectrum disorder, OPSD, and fronto-otopalatodigital osteodysplasia.

Otopalatodigital syndrome type 1 is a type of X-linked dominant disease and falls under the otopalatodigital syndrome spectrum disorder. It is categorized as a condition that fundamentally has a material basis in some form of X-linked dominant inheritance. The disorder is specifically characterized by a cleft palate, mild skeletal anomalies including digital anomalies, and conductive deafness caused by ossicular anomalies. This condition is due to heterozygous or hemizygous mutations in exon 3, 4, or 5 of the FLNA gene located on chromosome Xq28. Otopalatodigital syndrome type 1 is also known by several exact synonyms including OPD I syndrome, OPD syndrome 1, OPD1, Taybi syndrome, oto-palato-digital syndrome type 1, and otopalatodigital syndrome type I.

Otopalatodigital syndrome type 2 is a type of X-linked dominant disease and is part of the otopalatodigital syndrome spectrum disorder. It is characterized as a condition that has a material basis in X-linked dominant inheritance. This disorder is defined as an otopalatodigital syndrome spectrum disorder characterized by disabling skeletal anomalies and variable malformations in the hindbrain, heart, intestines, and kidneys. These malformations frequently lead to perinatal death in males and present less severe phenotypes in females. The condition has its material basis in hemizygous or heterozygous mutations in exons 3, 4, or 5 in males, or exons 28 or 29 in females, of the FLNA gene on chromosome Xq28. It is also known by several exact synonyms including Andre syndrome, OPD II syndrome, OPD syndrome 2, OPD2, faciopalatoosseous syndrome, oto-palato-digital syndrome type 2, and otopalatodigital syndrome type II.

Frontometaphyseal dysplasia is a type of otopalatodigital syndrome spectrum disorder characterized by abnormal ossification and skeletal patterning of the axial and appendicular skeleton, facial dysmorphism, urogenital anomalies, and hearing loss. It is also exactly synonymous with FMD.

Frontometaphyseal dysplasia 1 (FMD1) is a type of frontometaphyseal dysplasia and a specific form of X-linked recessive disease, which is characterized by a generalized skeletal dysplasia, deafness, and urogenital defects. This condition has a material basis in homozygous or hemizygous mutations in the FLNA gene located on chromosome Xq28, related to X-linked recessive inheritance.

Frontometaphyseal dysplasia 2 (FMD2) is a type of autosomal dominant disease and a specific form of frontometaphyseal dysplasia, characterized by a complex of features including generalized skeletal dysplasia, deafness, urogenital defects, and an increased tendency to form keloid scars. This condition is rooted in a material basis that involves autosomal dominant inheritance and is specifically caused by a heterozygous mutation in the MAP3K7 gene located on chromosome 6q15.

Melnick Needles Syndrome (MNS), also known as Melnick-Needles osteodysplasty or osteodysplasty of Melnick and Needles, is a type of X-linked monogenic disease, which is part of the otopalatodigital syndrome spectrum disorder. This condition arises from a material basis in X-linked inheritance, specifically due to heterozygous or hemizygous mutations in the FLNA gene on chromosome Xq28. It is characterized by short stature, facial dysmorphism, and osseous abnormalities affecting the majority of the axial and appendicular skeleton, which result in impaired speech and masticatory problems.

Frank ter Haar syndrome is a condition that falls under the category of autosomal recessive diseases and is part of the otopalatodigital syndrome spectrum disorder. This syndrome is defined as an otopalatodigital syndrome spectrum disorder characterized by features such as megalocornea, multiple skeletal anomalies, characteristic facial dysmorphism (including wide fontanels, prominent forehead, hypertelorism, prominent eyes, full cheeks, and micrognathia), and developmental delay. The material basis for Frank ter Haar syndrome is found in homozygous or compound heterozygous mutations in the SH3PXD2B gene located on chromosome 5q35.1. Furthermore, Frank ter Haar syndrome is known by several exact synonyms, including Borrone dermatocardioskeletal syndrome, FTHS, Ter Haar syndrome, autosomal recessive Melnick-Needles syndrome, and megalocornea, multiple skeletal anomalies, and developmental delay.

Congenital Nystagmus 1 is a type of autosomal genetic disease, specifically a variant of congenital nystagmus. It is characterized by having a material basis in some autosomal inheritance and is associated with abnormalities in prenatal development or birth. The condition is defined by a mutation in the FRMD7 gene located on chromosome Xq26.2. Congenital Nystagmus 1 is also known by its exact synonyms: NYS1, X-linked infantile nystagmus 1, and congenital motor nystagmus 1.

Congenital nystagmus 7 is a type of autosomal dominant disease and congenital nystagmus. It is characterized by a condition that fundamentally arises from abnormalities of prenatal development or birth and has a material basis in autosomal dominant inheritance. Specifically, congenital nystagmus 7 is defined by a heterozygous mutation in a region of chromosome 1q31.3-q32.1. Additionally, it is precisely referred to by the synonyms NYS7 and autosomal dominant congenital nystagmus 7.

Congenital Nystagmus 2, which is also precisely known as NYS2, Autosomal Dominant Congenital Nystagmus 2, and Congenital Motor Nystagmus 2, is a specific type of autosomal dominant disease. It falls within the broader category of congenital nystagmus. This condition is characterized by having its material basis in some autosomal dominant inheritance and is rooted in an abnormality of prenatal development or birth. Specifically, Congenital Nystagmus 2 is defined by a heterozygous mutation in a region of chromosome 6p12.

Congenital Nystagmus 3 is a type of autosomal dominant disease and a specific form of congenital nystagmus. It is characterized by having a material basis in autosomal dominant inheritance and is associated with abnormalities of prenatal development or birth. This condition is defined by a congenital nystagmus that results from a heterozygous mutation in a region of chromosome 7p11.2. Furthermore, it is precisely known by two exact synonyms: NYS3 and autosomal dominant congenital nystagmus 3.

Congenital nystagmus 6 is a type of congenital nystagmus and falls under the category of diseases that originate from some abnormality of prenatal development or birth. It is defined as a congenital nystagmus that has a material basis in hemizygous or homozygous mutations in the GPR143 gene on chromosome Xp22.2. Additionally, congenital nystagmus 6 is exactly synonymous with NYS6 and X-linked congenital nystagmus 6.

Congenital Nystagmus 5, also known exactly as NYS5 and X-linked Congenital Nystagmus 5, is a type of congenital nystagmus and an X-linked dominant disease. It specifically arises from conditions that have a material basis in X-linked dominant inheritance and abnormalities of prenatal development or birth. Moreover, its definition is established on the basis of a hemizygous or heterozygous mutation in a region of chromosome Xp11.4.

Autosomal recessive congenital nystagmus is a type of disease that falls under the category of autosomal recessive diseases and congenital nystagmus. It is characterized by its autosomal recessive inheritance and is linked to abnormalities of prenatal development or birth. This condition is defined as a congenital nystagmus characterized by autosomal recessive inheritance. Additionally, autosomal recessive congenital nystagmus is exactly synonymous with autosomal recessive congenital motor nystagmus.

X-linked nephrolithiasis type I is a subtype of X-linked recessive disease, renal tubular transport disease, and it is characterized by a material basis in X-linked recessive inheritance. This condition is defined as a renal tubular transport disease characterized by proximal renal tubular reabsorptive failure, hypercalciuria, nephrolithiasis, and renal insufficiency without the presence of rickets. This is due to either hemizygous or homozygous mutations in the CLCN5 gene on chromosome Xp11.23. Moreover, X-linked nephrolithiasis type I is known by several exact synonyms including NPHL1, X-linked nephrolithiasis with renal failure, X-linked recessive urolithiasis type 1, XRN, nephrolithiasis 1, and nephrolithiasis X-linked recessive type 1.

Syndromic microphthalmia 1 is classified as a type of X-linked monogenic disease, which is a specific form of syndromic microphthalmia. This condition is defined as a type of disorder that has a material basis in some form of X-linked inheritance. Specifically, syndromic microphthalmia 1 is characterized by unilateral or bilateral microphthalmia or anophthalmia along with defects in the skeletal and genitourinary system. These manifestations are due to a mutation in the NAA10 gene located on chromosome Xq28. Additionally, syndromic microphthalmia 1 is broadly synonymous with syndromic microphthalmia 4 and has exact synonyms including Lenz dysplasia, Lenz microphthalmia, Lenz type microphthalmia, and MCOPS1. Moreover, it has exact matches with MESH identifiers C537464 and C564457.

Syndromic microphthalmia 12 is a type of autosomal genetic disease, which is also a subtype of syndromic microphthalmia, and it can be characterized by its autosomal inheritance material basis. It is defined as a syndromic microphthalmia characterized by bilateral microphthalmia, pulmonary hypoplasia, and diaphragmatic hernia, with its material basis in compound heterozygous or heterozygous mutation in the RARB gene on chromosome 3p24.2. Moreover, it has exact synonyms including MCOPS12 and microphthalmia with or without pulmonary hypoplasia, diaphragmatic hernia, and/or cardiac defects.

Syndromic microphthalmia 3 is a type of autosomal dominant disease, which is also categorized under syndromic microphthalmia and is associated with autosomal dominant inheritance. This condition is defined by a syndromic microphthalmia characterized by clinical anophthalmia or microphthalmia, accompanied by various extraocular symptoms, arising from a heterozygous mutation in the SOX2 gene located on chromosome 3q26.33. It is known by several exact synonyms, including AEG syndrome, MCOPS3, SOX2 anophthalmia syndrome, anophthalmia clinical with associated anomalies, anophthalmia esophageal genital syndrome, anophthalmia microphthalmia esophageal atresia, anophthalmia/microphthalmia-esophageal atresia syndrome, microphthalmia and esophageal atresia syndrome, and syndromic microphthalmia type 3.

Syndromic microphthalmia 14 is a type of autosomal genetic disease, specifically a form of syndromic microphthalmia, and it is characterized as a condition that inherently has a material basis in some form of autosomal inheritance. It is defined as a type of syndromic microphthalmia characterized by features such as microphthalmia with coloboma or clinical anophthalmia, with or without rhizomelic skeletal dysplasia. This condition is caused by either heterozygous or homozygous mutations in the MAB21L2 gene located on chromosome 4q31.3. Syndromic microphthalmia 14 is also known by several exact synonyms, including MCOPS14, MCSKS, colobomatous microphthalmia-rhizomelic dysplasia syndrome, microphthalmia and/or coloboma with or without rhizomelic skeletal dysplasia, and microphthalmia/coloboma and skeletal dysplasia syndrome.

Syndromic microphthalmia 8 is a type of autosomal genetic disease, which is also a form of syndromic microphthalmia. It is characterized by a condition that has at least a material basis in some form of autosomal inheritance. Specifically, syndromic microphthalmia 8 is defined as a syndromic microphthalmia characterized by microcephaly, microphthalmia, ectrodactyly of the lower limbs, prognathism, and intellectual disability, with its material basis in a mutation in a region of chromosome 6q21. Additionally, it is known by several exact synonyms: MCOPS8, MMEP syndrome, Viljoen-Smart syndrome, microcephaly-microphthalmia-ectrodactyly of lower limbs-prognathism syndrome, and syndromic microphthalmia type 8.

Syndromic microphthalmia 11 is a type of syndromic microphthalmia, also known exactly as MCOPS11. It is characterized by microphthalmia, cleft lip and palate, and agenesis of the corpus callosum. This condition has a material basis in homozygous or compound heterozygous mutation in VAX1 on chromosome 10q25.3.

Syndromic microphthalmia 6 is a type of autosomal dominant disease and is also a subtype of syndromic microphthalmia. It is characterized as a condition that arises at least partially from autosomal dominant inheritance. Specifically, syndromic microphthalmia 6 is defined as a form of syndromic microphthalmia that includes clinical anophthalmia or microphthalmia, retinal dystrophy, and/or myopia, which in some cases is associated with cerebral anomalies. This condition has its material basis in a heterozygous mutation in the BMP4 gene located on chromosome 14q22.2. Syndromic microphthalmia 6 is also known by several exact synonyms, including Bakrania-Ragge syndrome, MCOPS6, anophthalmia clinical with micrognathia malformed ears digital anomalies and abnormal external genitalia, microphthalmia and pituitary anomalies, microphthalmia with brain and digit anomalies, and syndromic microphthalmia type 6.

Syndromic microphthalmia 5, also known precisely as MCOPS5, syndromic microphthalmia type 5, and syndromic microphthalmia/anophthalmia due to OTX2 mutation, is categorized under autosomal dominant diseases and syndromic microphthalmia. It specifically manifests as a type of condition that necessarily involves material basis in some form of autosomal dominant inheritance. Syndromic microphthalmia 5 is defined by a unique form of syndromic microphthalmia characterized by unilateral or bilateral microphthalmia or clinical anophthalmia along with variable additional features, which is the result of a heterozygous mutation in the OTX2 gene located on chromosome 14q22.3.

Syndromic microphthalmia 9 is a type of autosomal recessive disease and also a type of syndromic microphthalmia, characterized by a condition that has a material basis in some autosomal recessive inheritance. It is specifically defined as a syndromic microphthalmia characterized by bilateral clinical anophthalmia, pulmonary hypoplasia or aplasia, cardiac malformations, and diaphragmatic defects, resulting from homozygous or compound heterozygous mutations in the STRA6 gene on chromosome 15q24.1. Syndromic microphthalmia 9 is known by several exact synonyms including Matthew-Wood syndrome, anophthalmia-pulmonary hypoplasia syndrome, anophthalmia/microphthalmia and pulmonary hypoplasia, clinical anophthalmia mild facial dysmorphism lung heart and diaphragm malformations, pulmonary agenesis microphthalmia and diaphragmatic defect, and spear syndrome.

Linear Skin Defects with Multiple Congenital Anomalies 1 is identified as a type of X-linked dominant disease, a physical disorder, an MLS syndrome, and a condition that fundamentally has a material basis in some X-linked dominant inheritance. Additionally, it is categorized based on having its disease basis in some abnormality of prenatal development or birth. Its definition highlights it as a syndromic microphthalmia characterized by unilateral or bilateral microphthalmia and linear skin defects on the face and neck in females, and in utero lethality in males, which is due to heterozygous or hemizygous mutation in the HCCS gene on chromosome Xp22.2. This disease is precisely synonymous with MCOPS7, MIDAS syndrome, Microphthalmia with Linear Skin Defect Syndrome, microphthalmia-dermal aplasia-sclerocornea syndrome, Syndromic Microphthalmia 7, and Syndromic Microphthalmia Type 7.

Syndromic microphthalmia 2 is a type of syndromic microphthalmia, which is classified as an X-linked dominant disease. It is also recognized as a condition that must have a material basis in some form of X-linked dominant inheritance. Syndromic microphthalmia 2 is specifically characterized by dental radiculomegaly, congenital cataract, microphthalmia, facial dysmorphism, and congenital heart disease, with its material basis attributed to a heterozygous mutation in the BCOR gene located on chromosome Xp11.4. Additionally, syndromic microphthalmia 2 is known by several exact synonyms, including ANOP2, MAA2, MCOPS2, OFCD syndrome, cataract-microphthalmia-radiculomegaly-cardiac septal defect syndrome, microphthalmia cataracts radiculomegaly and septal heart defects, oculofaciocardiodental syndrome, and syndromic microphthalmia type 2.

Syndromic microphthalmia 13 is a type of X-linked monogenic disease and a specific form of syndromic microphthalmia. It involves a condition that has its material basis in some form of X-linked inheritance. This condition is characterized as a syndromic microphthalmia featuring colobomatous microphthalmia, microcephaly, short stature, and psychomotor retardation, which results from a mutation in the HMGB3 gene on chromosome Xq28. Additionally, syndromic microphthalmia 13 is known by several exact synonyms, including MCOPS13, Maine microphthalmos, X-linked colobomatous microphthalmia-microcephaly-intellectual disability-short stature syndrome, and colobomatous microphthalmia with microcephaly, short stature, and psychomotor retardation.

Syndromic microphthalmia 10 is a type of syndromic microphthalmia defined as a syndromic microphthalmia characterized by congenital microphthalmia and blindness, microcephaly, progressive spasticity, seizures, progressive atrophy of the brain, and profound intellectual disability. It has exact synonyms MCOPS10, MOBA, and microphthalmia-brain atrophy syndrome.

Syndactyly Type 8 is classified as a type of X-linked recessive disease, which falls under the broader category of syndactyly. It is specifically associated with conditions that have a material basis in X-linked recessive inheritance. This form of syndactyly is defined by the isolated fusion of the fourth and fifth metacarpals, a condition that results from either hemizygous or homozygous mutation in the FGF16 gene located on chromosome Xq21.1. Additionally, Syndactyly Type 8 is precisely identified by the exact synonyms "fusion of metacarpals 4 and 5" and "metacarpal 4-5 fusion."

Methylmalonic acidemia and homocysteinemia cblx type is a type of X-linked recessive disease, which is also a form of methylmalonic acidemia and is characterized by being a condition that inherently has a material basis in some X-linked recessive inheritance. This condition is defined as a methylmalonic acidemia that presents itself in infancy with severely delayed psychomotor development, failure to thrive, intellectual disability, and intractable epilepsy, stemming from hemizygous or homozygous mutation in the HCFC1 gene on chromosome Xq28. It is precisely known by several exact synonyms which include combined defect in adenosylcobalamin and methylcobalamin synthesis, type cblX; mental retardation, X-linked 3; and methylmalonic aciduria with homocystinuria, type cblX.

Dent disease, which is a type of low molecular weight proteinuria with hypercalciuric nephrocalcinosis, is defined by elevated levels of low molecular weight proteins in the urine, hypercalciuria, and nephrocalcinosis. This condition has a material basis in hemizygous or homozygous mutations in the CLCN5 gene located on chromosome Xp11.22.

Syndactyly type 1 is characterized as a type of autosomal dominant disease, chromosomal duplication syndrome, and syndactyly. It is described by an intersection of conditions that have a material basis in some chromosome and duplication, specifically highlighting its basis in autosomal dominant inheritance. The definition of Syndactyly type 1 is a syndactyly characterized by complete or partial webbing between the third and fourth fingers and/or the second and third toes, which is caused by a heterozygous duplication of a region on chromosome 2q34-q36. Additionally, Syndactyly type 1 is also known by its exact synonyms: SDTY1, chromosome 2q35 duplication syndrome, and syndactyly, type 1, with or without craniosynostosis.

Syndactyly type 3 is a type of autosomal dominant disease, which also falls under the broader category of syndactyly. It is defined as a syndactyly characterized by complete and bilateral syndactyly between the 4th and 5th fingers, with its material basis in a heterozygous mutation in the GJA1 gene on chromosome 6q22.31. This condition is an example of something that has a material basis in autosomal dominant inheritance. Syndactyly type 3 is also known by its exact synonyms: SDTY3, ring and little finger syndactyly, syndactyly of fingers 4 and 5, and syndactyly, type III.

Syndactyly type 4 is a form of autosomal dominant disease and a specific type of syndactyly, characterized by complete bilateral syndactyly involving all digits from 1 to 5. This condition arises from a heterozygous mutation in a Sonic Hedgehog (SHH) regulatory element located in intron 5 of the LMBR1 gene on chromosome 7q36.3. Additionally, Syndactyly type 4 is also known by its exact synonyms: Haas type syndactyly, SDTY4, and polysyndactyly, Haas type. It is described as stemming from autosomal dominant inheritance at a material basis.

Syndactyly Type 5 is a type of autosomal dominant disease and syndactyly, specifically characterized by a condition that inherently has a material basis in autosomal dominant inheritance. It is defined as a syndactyly characterized by postaxial syndactyly of the hands and feet associated with metacarpal and metatarsal fusion, typically affecting the 4th and 5th or the 3rd and 4th digits, and has its material basis in a heterozygous mutation in the HOXD13 gene on chromosome 2q31.1. Furthermore, Syndactyly Type 5 is also known by the exact synonyms SDTY5 and syndactyly with associated metacarpal and metatarsal fusion.

Zygodactyly 1 is a type of syndactyly and is also a type of condition that affects the foot. It is defined as a syndactyly characterized by webbing between the second and third toes without involving the hands.

Ichthyosis Follicularis Alopecia Photophobia Syndrome 1 (IFAP Syndrome 1) is a type of syndrome that falls under the category of X-linked recessive diseases. It manifests as a condition that not only has a material basis in X-linked recessive inheritance but also is characterized by specific phenotypes such as epidermal thickening. This syndrome is defined by a combination of ichthyosis follicularis, atrichia (absence of hair), and photophobia, which originates from either hemizygous or homozygous mutations in the MBTPS2 gene located on chromosome Xp22.12. Furthermore, IFAP Syndrome 1 is also known by its exact synonyms: IFAP Syndrome 1 with or without BRESHECK syndrome, and ichthyosis follicularis-atrichia-photophobia syndrome 1, encapsulating the diverse presentations of this genetic condition.

Child syndrome is a type of syndrome and a specific form of X-linked dominant disease. It is characterized by a condition that at least has a material basis in some X-linked dominant inheritance. The definition of Child syndrome is a syndrome characterized by congenital hemidysplasia, ichthyosiform erythroderma, and limb defects, which has a material basis in a heterozygous mutation in the NSDHL gene on chromosome Xq28. Furthermore, Child syndrome has exact synonyms, including CHILD nevus and congenital hemidysplasia with ichthyosiform nevus and limb defects.

Autosomal hemophilia A is a type of blood coagulation disease and also a type of autosomal genetic disease, which essentially has a material basis in autosomal inheritance. It is characterized by the autosomal inheritance of a Factor VIII deficiency, which is precisely defined as a blood coagulation disease. Moreover, it is exactly synonymous with autosomal Factor VIII deficiency.

Aarskog syndrome is a type of syndrome characterized by facial, limbs, and genital anomalies, along with a disproportionate acromelic short stature. It is also known by its exact synonyms: Aarskog-Scott syndrome, faciodigitogenital syndrome, and faciogenital dysplasia.

Autosomal dominant Aarskog syndrome is a type of Aarskog syndrome and a type of autosomal dominant disease. It is characterized by autosomal dominant inheritance, representing a type of condition that at least has a material basis in some autosomal dominant inheritance.

Abruzzo Erickson syndrome is a type of syndrome and an X-linked monogenic disease, which means it at least has a material basis in some X-linked inheritance. It is characterized by cleft palate, coloboma, hypospadias, deafness, short stature, and radial synostosis, resulting from a hemizygous mutation in the TBX22 gene on chromosome Xq21.1. Additionally, Abruzzo Erickson syndrome is also known by its exact synonyms: CHARGE-like syndrome, X-linked and cleft palate-coloboma-deafness syndrome.

X-linked spinal muscular atrophy 2 is a type of spinal muscular atrophy and falls under the category of X-linked recessive diseases. It is characterized by a condition that essentially has a material basis in X-linked recessive inheritance. Specifically, X-linked spinal muscular atrophy 2 is defined as a spinal muscular atrophy that is marked by neonatal onset of severe hypotonia, areflexia, and multiple congenital contractures associated with the loss of anterior horn cells and typically results in infantile death. The condition has its material basis in a hemizygous mutation in the UBA1 gene located on chromosome Xp11.3. Additionally, X-linked spinal muscular atrophy 2 is known by several exact synonyms including SMAX2, X-linked distal arthrogryposis multiplex congenita, X-linked spinal muscular atrophy type 2, infantile-onset X-linked spinal muscular atrophy, and spinal muscular atrophy with arthrogryposis.
X-linked cerebellar ataxia is a type of X-linked hereditary ataxia, which is defined as a hereditary ataxia characterized by X-linked inheritance.

X-linked spinocerebellar ataxia 1 (SCAX1), also known as X-linked progressive cerebellar ataxia, is a type of X-linked recessive disease and a type of X-linked cerebellar ataxia. It is characterized by a condition that at least has a material basis in some form of X-linked recessive inheritance. Specifically, it is defined as an X-linked cerebellar ataxia characterized by symptoms such as hypotonia at birth, delayed motor development, gait ataxia, difficulty standing, dysarthria, and slow eye movements, all of which have a material basis in a hemizygous mutation in the ATP2B3 gene on chromosome Xq28.

X-linked spinocerebellar ataxia 2 is a type of X-linked cerebellar ataxia, which is characterized by an infantile onset of ataxia, severe atrophy of the cerebellum, diffuse small cysts, pale inferior olives, and gliosis, following an X-linked inheritance pattern. It is also precisely known as SCAX2 and cerebellar ataxia with extrapyramidal involvement early-onset.

X-linked spinocerebellar ataxia 3 is a type of X-linked cerebellar ataxia, characterized by onset in infancy of hypotonia, ataxia, sensorineural deafness, developmental delay, esotropia, and optic atrophy with X-linked inheritance. It has exact synonyms: SCAX3, X-linked ataxia-deafness syndrome, and X-linked spinocerebellar ataxia type 3.

X-linked spinocerebellar ataxia 4 is a type of X-linked cerebellar ataxia, characterized by ataxia, pyramidal tract signs, and adult-onset dementia with X-linked inheritance. Furthermore, it is exactly synonymous with SCAX4, X-linked ataxia-dementia syndrome, and X-linked spinocerebellar ataxia type 4.

X-linked spinocerebellar ataxia 5 is a type of X-linked recessive disease and also falls under the category of X-linked cerebellar ataxia. It is associated with conditions that have a material basis in some form of X-linked recessive inheritance. The condition is characterized by neonatal hypotonia, delayed motor development, nonprogressive ataxia, nystagmus, and dysarthria, with its material basis in a hemizygous mutation in the region of chromosome Xq25-q27.1. This condition is known by several exact synonyms, including SCAX5, Spinocerebellar Ataxia, X-Linked 5, and X-linked nonprogressive cerebellar ataxia.

X-linked reticulate pigmentary disorder is a type of pigmentation disease, which also falls under the category of X-linked monogenic diseases and is a condition that essentially has a material basis in some form of X-linked inheritance. It is characterized by a specific set of symptoms including early onset of recurrent respiratory infections, failure to thrive due to inflammatory gastroenteritis or colitis, and distinctive reticular pigmentation abnormalities of the skin observed in hemizygous males, alongside only pigmentary abnormalities following the lines of Blaschko in heterozygous females. These clinical manifestations are the result of a mutation in the POLA1 gene located on chromosome Xp22.1-p21.3. Additionally, X-linked reticulate pigmentary disorder is known by several exact synonyms including PDR, Partington disease, and X-linked reticulate pigmentary disorder with systemic manifestations.

Congenital nongoitrous hypothyroidism 9 (CHNG9) is a type of congenital hypothyroidism and is categorized as an x-linked recessive disease. It is a condition that has a material basis in x-linked recessive inheritance and is associated with abnormalities of prenatal development or birth. The definition of congenital nongoitrous hypothyroidism 9 includes being a congenital hypothyroidism characterized by a small thyroid gland with low free T4 levels and inappropriately normal levels of thyroid-stimulating hormone, which has its material basis in a hemizygous mutation in the IRS4 gene on chromosome Xq22.3.

Congenital nongoitrous hypothyroidism 7, also exactly known as CHNG7, TRH resistance syndrome, central hypothyroidism due to TRH receptor deficiency, and resistance to thyrotropin-releasing hormone syndrome, is a type of congenital hypothyroidism and an autosomal recessive disease. This condition is characterized by a material basis in autosomal recessive inheritance and is rooted in some abnormality of prenatal development or birth. It is specifically defined as a congenital hypothyroidism characterized by normal-to-low T4 and normal-to-high thyrotropin levels, with reduced or absent pituitary responsiveness to thyrotropin-releasing hormone, which has its material basis in homozygous or compound heterozygous mutation in the TRHR gene on chromosome 8q23.1.

Congenital nongoitrous hypothyroidism 8, also precisely known as CHNG8, is a subtype of congenital hypothyroidism and an autosomal dominant disease. It is defined by a form of congenital hypothyroidism that is relatively mild in its central manifestation and results from either heterozygous or hemizygous mutations in the TBL1X gene located on chromosome Xp22.3-p22.2. This condition is linked to autosomal dominant inheritance and is characterized by abnormalities in prenatal development or birth.

Basilicata Akhtar syndrome is recognized as a type of syndromic X-linked intellectual disability, which is precisely defined as a condition characterized by global developmental delay apparent from infancy, feeding difficulties, hypotonia, and poor or absent speech. This condition's material basis is found in either hemizygous or heterozygous mutations in the MSL3 gene on chromosome Xp22.2. Moreover, Basilicata Akhtar syndrome is exactly synonymous with MRXS36, X-linked syndromic mental retardation 36, and X-linked syndromic mental retardation Basilicata-Akhtar type.

Congenital Disorder of Glycosylation ICC (CDG-Icc) is classified as a type of Congenital Disorder of Glycosylation Type I, and it also falls under the category of X-linked recessive diseases. This condition is characterized by its genetic foundation in X-linked recessive inheritance and is also recognized for its association with abnormalities in prenatal development or birth. CDG-Icc is specifically defined as a Congenital Disorder of Glycosylation Type I that is characterized by developmental delay, impaired intellectual development, and mild facial dysmorphism. This disorder is associated with abnormal serum transferrin isoelectric focusing consistent with a type 1 pattern, which is caused by a hemizygous mutation in the MAGT1 gene located on chromosome Xq21.1. Furthermore, Congenital Disorder of Glycosylation ICC is exactly synonymous with Congenital Disorder of Glycosylation Type Icc.

Van Esch-O'Driscoll syndrome is a type of syndromic X-linked intellectual disability, which is also recognized as a type of X-linked recessive disease. It is characterized by variable degrees of intellectual disability, moderate to severe short stature, microcephaly, hypogonadism, and variable congenital malformations due to a hemizygous mutation in the POLA1 gene on chromosome Xp22.1-p21.3. This condition is synonymous with MRXSVEOD, VEODS, X-linked intellectual disability, Van Esch type, and X-linked syndromic mental retardation Van Esch-O'Driscoll type.

Shukla Vernon Syndrome, also exactly known as SHUVER, is a type of syndrome that falls under the category of X-linked recessive diseases. It is described as a syndrome with a material basis in X-linked recessive inheritance. This syndrome is characterized by global developmental delay, variably impaired intellectual development, variable dysmorphic features, and behavioral abnormalities, which include autism spectrum disorder and ADHD. These characteristics are due to a hemizygous mutation in the BCORL1 gene located on chromosome Xq26.1.

Keipert syndrome, which has exact synonyms KPTS and nasodigitoacoustic syndrome, is a type of syndrome and specifically a type of X-linked recessive disease. It is characterized by a syndrome that at least has a material basis in some X-linked recessive inheritance. The definition of Keipert syndrome is a syndrome characterized by craniofacial and digital abnormalities, mild to severe congenital sensorineural hearing loss, and variable learning difficulties that has a material basis in a hemizygous mutation in the GPC4 gene on chromosome Xq26.2.

Paganini Miozzo Syndrome is a type of syndromic X-linked intellectual disability, X-linked recessive disease, and it is characterized by a condition that fundamentally has a material basis in X-linked recessive inheritance. It is defined specifically as a syndromic X-linked intellectual disability featuring global developmental delay, impaired intellectual development, high myopia, and mild dysmorphic facial features, with its material basis in hemizygous mutation in the HS6ST2 gene located on chromosome Xq26.2. Furthermore, Paganini Miozzo Syndrome is exactly synonymous with MRXSPM.

X-linked intellectual developmental disorder 108 is classified as a syndromic X-linked intellectual disability, an X-linked recessive disease, and a condition with a material basis in X-linked recessive inheritance. It is defined as a syndromic X-linked intellectual disability characterized by global developmental delay, delayed walking, and poor speech acquisition, arising from a hemizygous mutation in the SLC9A7 gene on chromosome Xp11.3. Additionally, this disorder is exactly synonymous with MRX108.

Mullegama Klein Martinez Syndrome (MKMS), also known by its exact synonyms NEDXCF and X-linked neurodevelopmental disorder with craniofacial abnormalities, is a type of syndromic X-linked intellectual disability. It is characterized by global developmental delay with impaired intellectual development and poor speech, and is commonly associated with ear abnormalities, hearing loss, and dysmorphic facial features. The syndrome has its material basis in heterozygous or hemizygous mutation in the STAG2 gene on chromosome Xq25.

X-linked congenital hemolytic anemia is a type of X-linked recessive disease and a type of congenital hemolytic anemia. It is characterized by at least having a material basis in some X-linked recessive inheritance and is a type of disease that has its basis in some abnormality of prenatal development or birth. It is defined as a congenital hemolytic anemia characterized by mild congenital hemolytic anemia without morphologic red cell abnormalities, having a material basis in a hemizygous mutation in the ATP11C gene on chromosome Xq27.1.

Osteogenesis imperfecta type 19 is a type of X-linked recessive disease and a subtype of osteogenesis imperfecta, which is characterized by having a material basis in some X-linked recessive inheritance. It is defined by prenatal fractures and generalized osteopenia, resulting in severe short stature in adulthood, variable scoliosis and pectus deformity, and notable anterior angulation of the tibia. This condition has its material basis in a hemizygous mutation in the MBTPS2 gene located on chromosome Xp22.12. Additionally, osteogenesis imperfecta type 19 is precisely referred to as OI19 and osteogenesis imperfecta type XIX.

Osteogenesis imperfecta type 18 (OI18), also known precisely as osteogenesis imperfecta, type XVIII, is categorized within the broader classification of autosomal recessive diseases and is specifically a variant of osteogenesis imperfecta. This particular type of osteogenesis imperfecta is characterized by congenital bowing of the long bones, wormian bones, blue sclerae, vertebral collapse, and multiple fractures occurring in the first years of life. The material basis for this condition is identified as being either homozygous or compound heterozygous mutations in the TENT5A gene located on chromosome 6q14.1. Furthermore, osteogenesis imperfecta type 18 exemplifies a condition that fundamentally arises from some form of autosomal recessive inheritance.

Osteogenesis imperfecta type 20 (OI20), also known exactly as osteogenesis imperfecta type XX, is a specific form of osteogenesis imperfecta and an autosomal recessive disease. It is characterized by osteopenia, skeletal deformity, and the presence of both healed and new fractures visible on radiography. The condition specifically arises from homozygous or compound heterozygous mutations in the MESD gene located on chromosome 15q25.1. This type of osteogenesis imperfecta inherently has a material basis in autosomal recessive inheritance.

Primary ciliary dyskinesia 36 is a type of primary ciliary dyskinesia characterized by the absence of outer dynein arms, defects in inner dynein arms, chronic airway disease, recurrent sinopulmonary infections, male infertility, and laterality defects in about half of the patients. This condition is attributed to a hemizygous mutation in the PIH1D3 gene located on chromosome Xq22.3. It is also known by its exact synonyms, CILD36 and X-linked primary ciliary dyskinesia 36.

Primary ciliary dyskinesia 44 (CILD44) is a type of autosomal recessive disease and a specific form of primary ciliary dyskinesia. It is defined as a primary ciliary dyskinesia characterized by recurrent sinopulmonary infections, defective mucociliary clearance, short respiratory epithelial cell motile cilia with decreased motility, and the absence of situs inversus. This condition has a material basis in homozygous or compound heterozygous mutation in the NEK10 gene on chromosome 3p24.1. Additionally, primary ciliary dyskinesia 44 is exactly synonymous with primary ciliary dyskinesia 44 without situs inversus, indicating that it is a type of condition that at least has a material basis in some form of autosomal recessive inheritance.

Primary Ciliary Dyskinesia 38 (PCD38) is a specific form of Primary Ciliary Dyskinesia and an autosomal recessive disease. It shares the characteristic of having a material basis in autosomal recessive inheritance. PCD38 is defined as a Primary Ciliary Dyskinesia characterized by significant loss of both the inner and outer dynein arms, chronic airway disease, recurrent sinopulmonary infections, and laterality defects in about half of the patients. This condition is caused by homozygous or compound heterozygous mutation in the CFAP300 gene located on chromosome 11q22.1. It is also precisely referred to as CILD38 and Primary Ciliary Dyskinesia 38 with or without situs inversus.

Primary Ciliary Dyskinesia 40 (PCD40) is an autosomal recessive disease classified under primary ciliary dyskinesia and is characterized by a specific type of material basis in autosomal recessive inheritance. It is defined as a primary ciliary dyskinesia characterized by a subtle defect in the bend of the distal portion of the cilia, reduced ciliary clearance in-vitro, a relatively mild respiratory phenotype, and laterality defects in all reported patients. This condition has its material basis in homozygous or compound heterozygous mutation in the DNAH9 gene on chromosome 17p12. PCD40 is also exactly synonymous with CILD40 and primary ciliary dyskinesia 40 with or without situs inversus.

Primary ciliary dyskinesia 39 (CILD39), also known exactly as primary ciliary dyskinesia 39 with or without situs inversus, is a type of autosomal recessive disease and a specific kind of primary ciliary dyskinesia. This condition is characterized by its autosomal recessive inheritance nature and has a material basis in homozygous or compound heterozygous mutation in the LRRC56 gene on chromosome 11p15.5. It is defined by features including ciliary kinetic defects in some patients, chronic sinopulmonary infections beginning soon after birth, and laterality defects in about half of the patients.

Primary ciliary dyskinesia 42 (CILD42), also known exactly as primary ciliary dyskinesia 42 without situs inversus, is a type of autosomal recessive disease, which falls under the broader category of primary ciliary dyskinesia. This specific condition is characterized by a severe reduction or absence of multiple motile cilia in respiratory epithelia, leading to respiratory insufficiency soon after birth, recurrent upper and lower respiratory infections, and the absence of laterality defects. This condition has its material basis in homozygous or compound heterozygous mutations in the MCIDAS gene located on chromosome 5q11.2. It is also noted as a type of disorder that inherently has a material basis in some form of autosomal recessive inheritance.

Primary Ciliary Dyskinesia 43 (PCD43), also known exactly as CILD43 and Primary Ciliary Dyskinesia 43 with or without situs inversus, is a type of autosomal dominant disease, specifically a form of Primary Ciliary Dyskinesia. It is characterized by a condition that fundamentally arises from autosomal dominant inheritance and is defined by a reduced generation of multiple motile cilia, respiratory insufficiency that begins soon after birth, recurrent upper and lower respiratory infections, variable infertility, and laterality defects in approximately half of the patients. This condition has its material basis in a heterozygous mutation in the FOXJ1 gene located on chromosome 17q25.1.

Primary Ciliary Dyskinesia 45 (PCD45) is a specific type of Primary Ciliary Dyskinesia and an autosomal recessive disease, which inherently means it has a material basis in autosomal recessive inheritance. PCD45 is defined by the absence of inner dynein arms with some axonemal disorganization in airway epithelial cells, the absence of both inner and outer dynein arms in sperm from infertile male patients, recurrent sinopulmonary infections, defective mucociliary clearance, and the absence of laterality defects. This condition is due to homozygous or compound heterozygous mutation in the TTC12 gene on chromosome 11q23.2. Moreover, PCD45 is precisely synonymous with CILD45 and also referred to as Primary Ciliary Dyskinesia 45 without situs inversus.

Primary Ciliary Dyskinesia 41 (PCD41), also known exactly as CILD41, is a specific form of Primary Ciliary Dyskinesia and falls under the broader category of autosomal recessive diseases. It is defined as a type of disorder characterized by hyperkinetic ciliary beat patterns, defects in ciliary orientation, chronic sinusitis, otitis media, and bronchiectasis. This condition has its material basis in homozygous or compound heterozygous mutations in the GAS2L2 gene located on chromosome 17q12, illustrating an autosomal recessive inheritance pattern.

Midface hypoplasia hearing impairment elliptocytosis and nephrocalcinosis is a syndrome and a type of X-linked recessive disease that is characterized by midface hypoplasia, hearing impairment, elliptocytosis, and nephrocalcinosis. It has a material basis in a hemizygous mutation in the AMMECR1 gene on chromosome Xq23. This condition is also precisely known as MFHIEN.

The Amme complex is a type of chromosomal deletion syndrome, which is a subtype of syndrome. It specifically intersects with conditions that at least have a material basis in some deletion and some chromosome. The Amme complex is defined as a syndrome characterized by Alport syndrome, mental retardation, midface hypoplasia, and elliptocytosis, having its material basis in the hemizygous deletion of multiple genes including COL4A5, FACL4, and AMMECR1 on chromosome Xq22.3. Moreover, the Amme complex is precisely synonymous with AMME syndrome, ATS-MR, Alport syndrome-intellectual disability-midface hypoplasia-elliptocytosis syndrome, and chromosome Xq22.3 telomeric deletion syndrome.

Meester Loeys Syndrome (MRLS) is a type of syndrome that falls under the category of X-linked monogenic diseases and is something that inherently has a material basis in some form of X-linked inheritance. It is defined as a syndrome characterized by an early-onset of aortic aneurysm and dissection in hemizygous males, with a variable presentation in heterozygous females ranging from unaffected to fatal aortic dissection. Additionally, individuals with this syndrome may exhibit facial dysmorphism, connective tissue anomalies, and features of Loeys-Dietz Syndrome, all of which have a material basis in a mutation in the BGN gene located on chromosome Xq28.

Congenital Bilateral Absence of Vas Deferens (CBAVD) is a type of male infertility, physical disorder, and X-linked monogenic disease. It is characterized by the bilateral absence of the vas deferens, leading to obstructive azoospermia and male infertility. This condition has a material basis at least in part in X-linked inheritance and is rooted in some abnormality of prenatal development or birth. CBAVD is also known by its exact synonyms: CAVD, congenital bilateral agenesis of vas deferens, and congenital bilateral aplasia of vas deferens. Additionally, it has an exact match in the OMIM database with the identifier PS277180.

X-linked congenital bilateral absence of vas deferens is a type of congenital bilateral absence of vas deferens and also falls under the category of diseases that have their basis in abnormalities of prenatal development or birth. It is defined as a congenital bilateral absence of vas deferens that has its material basis in a mutation in the ADGRG2 gene on chromosome Xp22.13. Additionally, it is exactly synonymous with CBAVDX.

Autosomal recessive congenital bilateral absence of vas deferens is a form of autosomal recessive disease and a specific type of congenital bilateral absence of vas deferens. It is characterized by having a material basis in autosomal recessive inheritance and is associated with abnormalities of prenatal development or birth. The condition is defined as a congenital bilateral absence of vas deferens that results from homozygous or compound heterozygous mutations in the CFTR gene located on chromosome 7q31.2.

Mend syndrome is a type of X-linked recessive disease and a lipid metabolism disorder characterized by a defect in sterol biosynthesis, resulting in variable features such as intellectual disability, short stature, scoliosis, digital abnormalities, cataracts, and dermatologic abnormalities. This disorder has its material basis in a hemizygous mutation in the EBP gene located on chromosome Xp11.23. Furthermore, Mend syndrome is also referred to by its exact synonym, "male EBP disorder with neurological defects." Additionally, it is a condition that at least has a material basis in some X-linked recessive inheritance.

Trichothiodystrophy is a type of syndrome that is characterized by sparse, brittle, sulfur-deficient hair that is easily broken and, in more severe cases, delayed development, significant intellectual disability, and recurrent infections. Moreover, trichothiodystrophy has an exact synonym, TTD.
Nonphotosensitive trichothiodystrophy is a type of trichothiodystrophy characterized by the absence of extreme sensitivity to UV radiation.

Nonphotosensitive trichothiodystrophy 5 (TTD5) is a type of X-linked dominant disease and a specific form of nonphotosensitive trichothiodystrophy. It is defined as a nonphotosensitive trichothiodystrophy characterized by sparse and brittle hair, facial dysmorphism, global developmental delays, growth deficiency, hypogonadism, and structural brain abnormalities. The condition's material basis is a hemizygous mutation in the RNF113A gene located on chromosome Xq24. Furthermore, it falls under the category of conditions that have at least a material basis in some X-linked dominant inheritance.

Photosensitive trichothiodystrophy 2, which has the exact synonym TTD2, is a type of autosomal recessive disease and a type of photosensitive trichothiodystrophy. It is characterized by a condition that fundamentally involves autosomal recessive inheritance. Specifically, photosensitive trichothiodystrophy 2 is defined as a photosensitive trichothiodystrophy that arises from homozygous or compound heterozygous mutations in the ERCC3 gene located on chromosome 2q14.3.

Nonphotosensitive trichothiodystrophy 7, also precisely known as TTD7, is categorized under autosomal recessive diseases and is a specific form of nonphotosensitive trichothiodystrophy. It is defined by its unique characteristics, including cysteine- and threonine-deficient hair, which exhibits a distinctive alternating light and dark 'tiger-tail' banding pattern when observed under polarization microscopy, and ichthyosis. The condition stems from either homozygous or compound heterozygous mutation in the TARS1 gene located on chromosome 5p13.3. This implies that nonphotosensitive trichothiodystrophy 7 fundamentally has its material basis in some form of autosomal recessive inheritance.

Photosensitive trichothiodystrophy 3, which is also exactly synonymous with TTD3 and trichothiodystrophy complementation group A, is identified as a type of autosomal recessive disease, photosensitive trichothiodystrophy, and something that inherently has a material basis in autosomal recessive inheritance. It is defined as a photosensitive trichothiodystrophy characterized by a material basis in homozygous or compound heterozygous mutation in the GTF2H5 gene located on chromosome 6q25.3.

Nonphotosensitive trichothiodystrophy 6 (TTD6) is a specific type of nonphotosensitive trichothiodystrophy and autosomal recessive disease. It is characterized by conditions that essentially have a material basis in autosomal recessive inheritance. This particular condition is defined by nonphotosensitive trichothiodystrophy that arises from homozygous or compound heterozygous mutations in the GTF2E2 gene located on chromosome 8p12.

Photosensitive trichothiodystrophy 1, which has the exact synonym TTD1, is a type of autosomal recessive disease and a specific form of photosensitive trichothiodystrophy. It is characterized by a material basis in autosomal recessive inheritance. Moreover, photosensitive trichothiodystrophy 1 is defined as a photosensitive trichothiodystrophy that has its material basis in homozygous or compound heterozygous mutation in the ERCC2 gene located on chromosome 19q13.32.

Sabinas brittle hair syndrome is a type of nonphotosensitive trichothiodystrophy characterized by congenital hypotrichosis, mild to moderate onychodysplasia, varying intellectual disability, and sterility. It is also exactly synonymous with brittle hair-mental deficiency syndrome and trichothiodystrophy type B.

MLS syndrome is a type of syndrome characterized by linear skin defects and various other congenital anomalies. The classical diagnosis of MLS syndrome consisted of unilateral or bilateral microphthalmia and/or anophthalmia and linear skin defects, but patients with a molecular diagnosis of MLS syndrome may not display eye abnormalities. It is also known by its exact synonym, linear skin defects with multiple congenital anomalies.

Linear Skin Defects with Multiple Congenital Anomalies 3 (LSDMCA3), also known as Linear Skin Defects with Cardiomyopathy and Other Congenital Anomalies, is a type of physical disorder and a form of MLS syndrome that falls under the category of X-linked dominant diseases. This condition is characterized by linear skin defects, cardiomyopathy, and various other congenital anomalies, with its material basis in a heterozygous mutation in the NDUFB11 gene on chromosome Xp11.3. It is considered a disease with its basis in some abnormality of prenatal development or birth, and it at least has a material basis in some X-linked dominant inheritance.

Linear Skin Defects with Multiple Congenital Anomalies 2 (LSDMCA2) is a type of physical disorder, also known as an X-linked dominant disease, and falls under the category of MLS syndrome. It is characterized by having a material basis in X-linked dominant inheritance and its disease basis lies in some abnormality of prenatal development or birth. Specifically, LSDMCA2 is defined by linear skin defects, microcephaly, facial dysmorphism, and other congenital anomalies due to a heterozygous mutation in the COX7B gene on chromosome Xq21.1. Additionally, LSDMCA2 is synonymous with APLCC, LSDMCA2, and Aplasia Cutis Congenita, reticulolinear, with microcephaly, facial dysmorphism, and other congenital anomalies.

Diamond Blackfan Anemia 7 (DBA7), also known as RPL11-related Diamond-Blackfan Anemia, is a type of Diamond Blackfan Anemia and an autosomal dominant disease. It is characterized by a specific type that has its material basis in autosomal dominant inheritance. DBA7 is defined by a Diamond-Blackfan Anemia that arises from a heterozygous mutation in the RPL11 gene located on chromosome 1p36.11.

Diamond Blackfan Anemia 6 is a type of Diamond Blackfan Anemia and an autosomal dominant disease that at least has a material basis in some autosomal dominant inheritance. It is defined as a Diamond-Blackfan anemia that has its material basis in a heterozygous mutation in the RPL5 gene on chromosome 1p22.1. Diamond Blackfan Anemia 6 is exactly synonymized with DBA6 and RPL5-related Diamond-Blackfan anemia.

Diamond Blackfan Anemia 17, which is an autosomal dominant disease and a type of Diamond Blackfan anemia, has a material basis in autosomal dominant inheritance. This specific anemia, DBA17, also known as RPS27-related Diamond-Blackfan anemia, is defined by a heterozygous mutation in the RPS27 gene located on chromosome 1q21.3.

Diamond Blackfan Anemia 8 (DBA8), also known as RPS7-related Diamond-Blackfan Anemia, is a type of Diamond Blackfan Anemia and an autosomal dominant disease. It specifically relates to something that fundamentally arises from autosomal dominant inheritance. DBA8 is defined by a Diamond-Blackfan Anemia that has its material basis in a heterozygous mutation in the RPS7 gene located on chromosome 2p25.3.

Diamond Blackfan Anemia 12 is a type of autosomal dominant disease and a specific form of Diamond Blackfan Anemia, which inherently has a material basis in autosomal dominant inheritance. It is defined as a Diamond-Blackfan anemia that has a material basis in a heterozygous mutation in the RPL15 gene on chromosome 3p24.2. Additionally, Diamond Blackfan Anemia 12 is exactly synonymous with DBA12 and RPL15-related Diamond-Blackfan anemia.

Diamond Blackfan Anemia 5 is a type of autosomal dominant disease and a specific form of Diamond Blackfan Anemia, characterized as a condition that inherently has a material basis in autosomal dominant inheritance. It is defined by a Diamond-Blackfan anemia that originates from a heterozygous mutation in the RPL35A gene located on chromosome 3q29. Furthermore, Diamond Blackfan Anemia 5 is exactly synonymous with DBA5 and RPL35A-related Diamond-Blackfan anemia.

Diamond Blackfan Anemia 9 (DBA9), also known as RPS10-related Diamond-Blackfan anemia, is a type of autosomal dominant disease and a specific form of Diamond Blackfan Anemia. This condition fundamentally arises from a heterozygous mutation in the RPS10 gene located on chromosome 6p21.31. Additionally, it is characterized as a type of disorder that inherently possesses a material basis in some form of autosomal dominant inheritance.

Diamond Blackfan Anemia 2 (DBA2) is a type of Diamond Blackfan Anemia and an autosomal dominant disease, which means it is a type of condition that at least has a material basis in some form of autosomal dominant inheritance. Specifically, DBA2 is defined as a Diamond-Blackfan anemia that has its material basis in a mutation in a region of chromosome 8p23.3-p22. Additionally, it has an exact synonym, DBA2.

Diamond Blackfan Anemia 19 is a type of autosomal dominant disease and a specific form of Diamond Blackfan Anemia, which inherently has a material basis in some autosomal dominant inheritance. It is defined as a Diamond-Blackfan anemia that is caused by a heterozygous mutation in the RPL35 gene on chromosome 9q33.3. This condition is exactly synonymous with DBA19 and RPL35-related Diamond-Blackfan anemia.

Diamond Blackfan Anemia 3 (DBA3), also known as RPS24-related Diamond-Blackfan anemia, is a type of autosomal dominant disease and a specific form of Diamond Blackfan anemia. It is characterized by having a material basis in autosomal dominant inheritance. DBA3 is defined by a heterozygous mutation in the RPS24 gene located on chromosome 10q22.3.

Diamond Blackfan anemia 10 is a type of Diamond Blackfan anemia and an autosomal dominant disease. It is characterized by a specific kind that has a material basis in autosomal dominant inheritance. This particular form of Diamond-Blackfan anemia, also known as DBA10 or RPS26-related Diamond-Blackfan anemia, is defined by a heterozygous mutation in the RPS26 gene located on chromosome 12q13.2.

Diamond Blackfan Anemia 13 is a type of autosomal dominant disease, which is a subtype of Diamond Blackfan Anemia and is characterized by having a material basis in autosomal dominant inheritance. It is defined as a Diamond-Blackfan anemia that has a material basis in a heterozygous mutation in the RPS29 gene on chromosome 14q21.3. Additionally, Diamond Blackfan Anemia 13 has exact synonyms, including DBA13 and RPS29-related Diamond-Blackfan anemia.

Diamond Blackfan Anemia 4 (DBA4), also known as RPS17-related Diamond-Blackfan anemia, is a type of Diamond Blackfan anemia and an autosomal dominant disease. It is characterized by a heterozygous mutation in the RPS17 gene located on chromosome 15q25.2. This condition is a specific instance of a broader category of diseases that have a material basis in some form of autosomal dominant inheritance.

Diamond Blackfan Anemia 20 (DBA20) is a type of Diamond Blackfan Anemia and an autosomal dominant disease that at least has a material basis in some autosomal dominant inheritance. It is specifically defined as a Diamond-Blackfan anemia that has a material basis in heterozygous mutation in the RPS15A gene on chromosome 16p12.3. Additionally, DBA20 has exact synonyms, including "DBA20" and "RPS15A-related Diamond-Blackfan anemia."

Diamond Blackfan Anemia 11 (DBA11) is a type of Diamond Blackfan Anemia and an autosomal dominant disease, which specifically has a material basis in autosomal dominant inheritance. It is defined as a Diamond-Blackfan anemia that has its material basis in a heterozygous mutation in the RPL26 gene on chromosome 17p13.1. DBA11 is also exactly synonymous with RPL26-related Diamond-Blackfan anemia.

Diamond Blackfan Anemia 16 is a type of Diamond Blackfan Anemia and an autosomal dominant disease that, at least in part, has its material basis in some form of autosomal dominant inheritance. It is defined as a Diamond-Blackfan anemia that has its material basis in a heterozygous mutation in the RPL27 gene on chromosome 17q21.31. Furthermore, Diamond Blackfan Anemia 16 is exactly synonymous with DBA16 and RPL27-related Diamond-Blackfan anemia.

Diamond Blackfan Anemia 15 with Mandibulofacial Dysostosis, also known exactly as DBA15, is a type of Diamond Blackfan Anemia and a specific autosomal dominant disease. This condition is characterized by features of Diamond-Blackfan anemia combined with mandibulofacial dysostosis, which includes micrognathia, downslanting palpebral fissures, a submucosal cleft palate or bifid uvula, and malar hypoplasia. The underlying cause of DBA15 is a heterozygous mutation in the RPS28 gene located on chromosome 19p13.2. Moreover, it is considered a type of condition that fundamentally has a material basis in some form of autosomal dominant inheritance.

Diamond Blackfan Anemia 1 (DBA1), also known as RPS19-related Diamond-Blackfan Anemia, is a specific type of Diamond Blackfan Anemia and a form of autosomal dominant disease. It is defined by having a material basis in at least some form of autosomal dominant inheritance, specifically through a heterozygous mutation in the RPS19 gene located on chromosome 19q13.2.

Diamond Blackfan Anemia 18 (DBA18), also known precisely as RPL18-related Diamond-Blackfan anemia, is a type of autosomal dominant disease and a specific form of Diamond Blackfan anemia. It is characterized by a condition that fundamentally arises from autosomal dominant inheritance. DBA18 is defined by a Diamond-Blackfan anemia that is due to a heterozygous mutation in the RPL18 gene located on chromosome 19q13.33.

Diamond Blackfan Anemia 14 with Mandibulofacial Dysostosis, also known precisely as DBA14, is a specific type of Diamond Blackfan Anemia. It is characterized by the features of Diamond-Blackfan anemia, including bilateral microtia and cleft palate, which result from a hemizygous mutation in the TSR2 gene located on chromosome Xp11.22. This condition falls under the category of X-linked recessive diseases, indicating that its material basis involves some form of X-linked recessive inheritance.

CK syndrome is a type of X-linked recessive disease and a lipid metabolism disorder, which implies that it has a material basis in some X-linked recessive inheritance. It is defined as a lipid metabolism disorder characterized by increased methylsterol levels in cells and cerebrospinal fluid, along with mild to severe cognitive impairment, seizures, microcephaly, cerebral cortical malformations, dysmorphic facial features, and thin body habitus. This disorder has its material basis in a hemizygous mutation in the NSDHL gene on chromosome Xq28. Additionally, CK syndrome has the exact synonym "X-linked intellectual disability-microcephaly-cortical malformation-thin habitus syndrome."

X-linked thrombophilia due to factor IX defect is a type of thrombophilia and a specific form of X-linked monogenic disease, which falls under the broader category of conditions that have a material basis in some form of X-linked inheritance. This thrombophilia is defined by normal levels of F9 antigen but very high levels of F9 activity, attributed to a hemizygous gain of function mutation in the F9 gene located on chromosome Xq27.1. Furthermore, X-linked thrombophilia due to factor IX defect is exactly synonymous with THPH8.

Autosomal dominant thrombophilia due to protein S deficiency is a type of autosomal dominant disease, a type of protein S deficiency, and a type of condition that at least has a material basis in some autosomal dominant inheritance. It is defined as a protein S deficiency characterized by reduced serum protein S levels and recurrent venous thrombosis that has its material basis in a heterozygous mutation in the PROS1 gene on chromosome 3q11.1. Additionally, it has the exact synonym THPH5.

Heparin cofactor II deficiency is a type of autosomal dominant disease, thrombophilia, and something that at least has a material basis in some autosomal dominant inheritance. It is characterized by an increased risk of thromboembolism, resulting from a heterozygous mutation in the HCF2 gene on chromosome 22q11.21. This condition is also precisely known by several synonyms including HCF 2 deficiency, HCF II deficiency, THPH10, and thrombophilia due to heparin cofactor II deficiency.

Thrombophilia due to activated protein c resistance is a type of thrombophilia and an autosomal dominant disease that at least has a material basis in some form of autosomal dominant inheritance. This condition is characterized by resistance of F5 to cleavage and inactivation, leading to an increased tendency for thrombosis, which is caused by a heterozygous mutation in F5 on chromosome 1q24.2. It is also known by several exact synonyms, including APC resistance, PCCF deficiency, PROC cofactor deficiency, THPH2, activated protein C resistance, thrombophilia V, and thrombophilia due to deficiency of activated protein C cofactor.

Thrombophilia due to HRG deficiency is a type of autosomal dominant disease and a specific form of thrombophilia. It is characterized by a condition that fundamentally has a material basis in some autosomal dominant inheritance. This particular thrombophilia is defined by decreased histidine-rich glycoprotein (HRG) plasma levels and a predisposition to develop thrombosis, which originates from a heterozygous mutation in HRG on chromosome 3q27.3. Additionally, thrombophilia due to HRG deficiency is also known by its exact synonyms: THPH11, hereditary thrombophilia due to congenital HRG deficiency, and hereditary thrombophilia due to congenital histidine-rich (poly-L) glycoprotein deficiency.

Autosomal recessive thrombophilia due to protein C deficiency is classified as a type of autosomal recessive disease and a type of protein C deficiency. It is also identified as a condition that fundamentally arises from autosomal recessive inheritance. The condition is specifically defined as a protein C deficiency characterized by typically early onset of venous thrombosis, although in some cases, it may have a milder, later onset. This is due to a homozygous or compound heterozygous mutation in the PROC gene located on chromosome 2q14.3. Furthermore, autosomal recessive thrombophilia due to protein C deficiency is precisely synonymous with THPH4, autosomal recessive PROC deficiency, and autosomal recessive protein C deficiency.

Autosomal recessive thrombophilia due to protein S deficiency is a condition that falls under the category of autosomal recessive diseases, protein S deficiencies, and conditions that inherently have a material basis in autosomal recessive inheritance. This specific protein S deficiency is characterized by thrombosis and secondary hemorrhage, typically beginning in early infancy, and is caused by homozygous or compound heterozygous mutations in the PROS1 gene located on chromosome 3q11.1. Additionally, this condition is also known by its exact synonyms: THPH6, autosomal recessive thrombophilia due to congenital protein S deficiency, and severe hereditary thrombophilia due to congenital protein S deficiency.

Thrombophilia due to decreased release of plat is a type of thrombophilia characterized by an impaired capacity for the release of fibrinolytic activity from the blood vessel walls. It is also known by the exact synonym THPH9.

Thrombophilia due to thrombin defect is a specific type of thrombophilia and an autosomal dominant disease, which is defined as a condition characterized by recurrent thrombophilia that arises from a heterozygous mutation in the F2 gene located on chromosome 11p11.2. This condition is also linked to autosomal dominant inheritance at its material basis. It is known by several exact synonyms, including THPH1, prothrombin-related thrombophilia, and thrombophilia due to factor 2 defect.

Thrombophilia due to thrombomodulin defect is an autosomal genetic disease and a specific type of thrombophilia, which is characterized by an increased risk of developing arterial but not venous thrombosis. This condition has a material basis in a mutation in the THBD gene located on chromosome 20p11.21. It is also known by several exact synonyms including THBD-related bleeding disorder, THBD-related coagulopathy, THPH12, thrombomodulin-related bleeding disorder, and thrombomodulin-related coagulopathy.

Autosomal dominant thrombophilia due to protein C deficiency is a type of protein C deficiency and represents a form of thrombophilia that at least has a material basis in some autosomal dominant inheritance. This condition is characterized by reduced serum levels or impaired activity of PROC, and in some patients, it leads to recurrent venous thrombosis. The cause of this condition is traced back to a heterozygous mutation in the PROC gene located on chromosome 2q14.3. It is also known by its exact synonyms THPH3, autosomal dominant PROC deficiency, and autosomal dominant protein C deficiency.

Spermatogenic failure is a type of male infertility, which is characterized by the disruption of the process of sperm development from diploid cells into mature haploid spermatozoa. It is also known by its exact synonym, SPGF.

Spermatogenic failure 34, which has the exact synonym SPGF34, is a type of spermatogenic failure and an autosomal recessive disease. It is defined as a spermatogenic failure characterized by multiple morphologic abnormalities of the flagella, resulting in immotile spermatozoa and infertility, which has its material basis in homozygous or compound heterozygous mutation in the FSIP2 gene on chromosome 2q32.1. This condition is also described as a type of disorder that at least has a material basis in some form of autosomal recessive inheritance.

Spermatogenic failure 41 (SPGF41) is a type of spermatogenic failure, an autosomal recessive disease, and is characterized by oligozoospermia and multiple morphologic abnormalities of the flagella. This condition has a material basis in homozygous or compound heterozygous mutation in the CFAP70 gene on chromosome 10q22.2. It is also defined as a type of condition that at least has a material basis in some autosomal recessive inheritance.

Spermatogenic failure 30, which has the exact synonym SPGF30, is identified as a type of autosomal recessive disease and a specific kind of spermatogenic failure. It is also recognized as something that fundamentally arises from autosomal recessive inheritance. It is characterized by a spermatogenic failure, specifically nonobstructive azoospermia or cryptozoospermia, which has its material basis in homozygous or compound heterozygous mutations in the TDRD9 gene located on chromosome 14q32.33.

Spermatogenic failure 35, also known exactly as SPGF35, is a type of spermatogenic failure and an autosomal recessive disease. It is characterized by a condition that fundamentally has a material basis in some form of autosomal recessive inheritance. Specifically, spermatogenic failure 35 is defined as a spermatogenic failure characterized by multiple morphologic abnormalities of the flagella, resulting in severely impaired sperm motility and infertility. This condition is caused by homozygous or compound heterozygous mutation in the QRICH2 gene located on chromosome 17q25.1.

Spermatogenic failure 33, which has the exact synonym SPGF33, is a type of autosomal recessive disease and a specific form of spermatogenic failure.
