It is defined by a spermatogenic failure characterized by multiple morphologic abnormalities of the flagella, resulting in immotile spermatozoa and infertility. This condition has its material basis in homozygous or compound heterozygous mutation in the WDR66 gene located on chromosome 12q24.31. Additionally, spermatogenic failure 33 is described as something that inherently has a material basis in some form of autosomal recessive inheritance.

Spermatogenic failure 28 is a type of spermatogenic failure, which is an autosomal recessive disease with a material basis in some autosomal recessive inheritance. It is characterized by nonobstructive azoospermia and a Sertoli cell-only phenotype in testes due to homozygous or compound heterozygous mutation in the FANCM gene on chromosome 14q21.2. Additionally, spermatogenic failure 28 is exactly synonymous with SPGF28.

Spermatogenic failure 43 is a type of autosomal recessive disease and spermatogenic failure, which at least has a material basis in some form of autosomal recessive inheritance. It is characterized by multiple morphologic abnormalities of the flagella, resulting in the absence of forward motility in spermatozoa and infertility. This condition has its material basis in homozygous or compound heterozygous mutation in the SPEF2 gene located on chromosome 5p13.2. Furthermore, spermatogenic failure 43 is exactly synonymous with SPGF43.

Spermatogenic failure 40, which has the exact synonym SPGF40, is a type of autosomal recessive disease and spermatogenic failure. It is also described as something that at least has a material basis in autosomal recessive inheritance. This condition is specifically defined as a spermatogenic failure characterized by multiple morphologic abnormalities of the flagella resulting in severely reduced to absent sperm motility and abnormalities of the sperm head. The condition's material basis is in homozygous or compound heterozygous mutation in the CFAP65 gene on chromosome 2q35.

Spermatogenic failure 38 is a type of autosomal recessive disease and spermatogenic failure that at least has its material basis in some form of autosomal recessive inheritance. It is specifically characterized by multiple morphologic abnormalities of the flagella, which result in infertility and asthenoteratozoospermia; this condition has its material basis in homozygous or compound heterozygous mutation in the ARMC2 gene on chromosome 6q21. Furthermore, spermatogenic failure 38 is exactly synonymous with SPGF38.

Spermatogenic failure 25 (SPGF25) is a type of autosomal recessive disease and spermatogenic failure that has its material basis in autosomal recessive inheritance. It is defined as a spermatogenic failure characterized by maturation arrest at the primary spermatocyte stage, resulting in severe oligozoospermia or azoospermia, small testes, and infertility. This condition has its material basis in homozygous or compound heterozygous mutation in the TEX15 gene on chromosome 8p12.

Spermatogenic failure 36 is a type of spermatogenic failure and an autosomal dominant disease, which is a condition that at least has a material basis in some form of autosomal dominant inheritance. It is defined as a spermatogenic failure characterized by spermatozoa showing anomalies of the head, acrosome, and nucleus of the sperm, leading to reduced fertility, and this condition has a material basis in a heterozygous mutation in the PPP2R3C gene located on chromosome 14q13.2. Spermatogenic failure 36 is also exactly synonymous with SPGF36.

Spermatogenic failure 31, also known exactly as SPGF31, is classified as a type of autosomal recessive disease that specifically leads to male infertility due to acephalic spermatozoa. This condition inherently has a material basis in autosomal recessive inheritance and is characterized by oligozoospermia with a high proportion of acephalic spermatozoa. The underlying cause is found to be homozygous or compound heterozygous mutations in the PMFBP1 gene located on chromosome 16q22.2.

Spermatogenic failure 42, which is also exactly synonymous with SPGF42, is categorized as a type of spermatogenic failure, autosomal recessive disease, and specifically as something that fundamentally arises from autosomal recessive inheritance. It is defined as a spermatogenic failure characterized by multiple morphologic abnormalities of the flagella, leading to severely impaired sperm progressive motility and infertility. This condition has its material basis in either homozygous or compound heterozygous mutations in the TTC29 gene located on chromosome 4q31.22.

Spermatogenic failure 26, also known exactly as SPGF26, is a type of autosomal recessive disease and a form of male infertility due to acephalic spermatozoa. This condition is characterized by acephalic spermatozoa resulting from breakage at the midpiece of the sperm, which has its material basis in homozygous or compound heterozygous mutation in the TSGA10 gene on chromosome 2q11.2. It is associated with autosomal recessive inheritance, indicating that it arises from a specific type of genetic inheritance pattern.

Spermatogenic failure 32, which has the exact synonym SPGF32, is a type of autosomal dominant disease and a specific kind of spermatogenic failure. This condition is characterized by a particular kind of autosomal dominant inheritance. It is defined as a spermatogenic failure that is featured by nonobstructive azoospermia, the absence of spermatogenic cells, and a Sertoli cell-only phenotype in the testes. This condition's material basis is in a heterozygous mutation in the SOHLH1 gene located on chromosome 9q34.3.

Spermatogenic failure 39, which is exactly synonymous with SPGF39, is recognized as a type of autosomal recessive disease and spermatogenic failure. It is characterized by a condition that inherently has a material basis in some form of autosomal recessive inheritance. Specifically, this spermatogenic failure is defined by multiple morphologic anomalies of the sperm flagellum, the absence of outer dynein arms in the flagella, and asthenozoospermia. This condition results from homozygous or compound heterozygous mutations in the DNAH17 gene located on chromosome 17q25.3.

Spermatogenic failure 37 is a type of spermatogenic failure and can also be classified as an autosomal recessive disease. It is described by a specific condition that at least has a material basis in some form of autosomal recessive inheritance. The definition of spermatogenic failure 37 encompasses a spermatogenic failure characterized by multiple morphologic abnormalities of the flagella, asthenoteratozoospermia, and infertility, which has its material basis in homozygous or compound heterozygous mutation in the TTC21A gene located on chromosome 3p22.2. Additionally, spermatogenic failure 37 is exactly synonymous with SPGF37.

Spermatogenic failure 27, also known precisely as SPGF27, is a type of spermatogenic failure classified as an autosomal recessive disease. It is characterized by a condition that inherently has a material basis in some form of autosomal recessive inheritance. The detailed definition of spermatogenic failure 27 includes it being a spermatogenic failure typified by multiple morphologic abnormalities of the sperm flagella, such as the loss of the central pair of microtubules, absence of the inner dynein arms, and disorganization of the peripheral doublet of the flagella. This condition is fundamentally caused by homozygous or compound heterozygous mutation in the AK7 gene located on chromosome 14q32.2.

Spermatogenic failure 24, which has the exact synonym SPGF24, is categorized as a type of spermatogenic failure and an autosomal recessive disease. It is defined by a specific spermatogenic failure characterized by multiple morphologic abnormalities of the flagella, malformed sperm heads, and very low sperm counts, rooted in homozygous or compound heterozygous mutations in the CFAP69 gene on chromosome 7q21.13. This condition exemplifies a case where the disease has a material basis in some form of autosomal recessive inheritance.

Spermatogenic failure 29 is a type of spermatogenic failure and an autosomal recessive disease. It is defined as a spermatogenic failure characterized by nonobstructive azoospermia or oligozoospermia, immotile sperm, and sperm acrosome and head-neck junction abnormalities. This condition is caused by homozygous or compound heterozygous mutation in the SPINK2 gene on chromosome 4q12. Additionally, spermatogenic failure 29 is referred to by its exact synonym, SPGF29.

Syndactyly telecanthus anogenital and renal malformations syndrome, also known precisely as STAR syndrome and alternatively referred to as syndactyly with renal and anogenital malformations or toe syndactyly, telecanthus, and anogenital and renal malformations, is a type of syndrome and autosomal dominant disease. It is characterized by a syndrome that encompasses toe syndactyly, telecanthus, and anogenital and renal malformations, which has its material basis in a heterozygous mutation in the FAM58A gene on chromosome Xq28. This condition is also described as something that at least has its material basis in some form of autosomal dominant inheritance.

Severe congenital encephalopathy due to MECP2 mutation is a type of X-linked recessive disease, a physical disorder, and a brain disease. It is characterized by a material basis in X-linked recessive inheritance and is rooted in some abnormality of prenatal development or birth. This condition is defined as a brain disease characterized by severe neonatal encephalopathy, developmental delay, and microcephaly, having its material basis in a hemizygous mutation in the MECP2 gene on chromosome Xq28. Additionally, it is also known by its exact synonyms, neonatal severe encephalopathy due to MECP2 mutations, and severe neonatal-onset encephalopathy with microcephaly.

Phosphoglycerate kinase 1 deficiency is a type of disease that falls under several categories: it is an X-linked recessive disease, a type of glucose metabolism disease, and something that inherently has a material basis in X-linked recessive inheritance. The definition of this condition is a glucose metabolism disease characterized by an impaired ability to break down glucose. This results in a variable presentation that includes hemolytic anemia, myopathy, and neurologic anomalies. These symptoms are due to either hemizygous or homozygous mutations in the PGK1 gene located on chromosome Xq21.1. Phosphoglycerate kinase 1 deficiency is also known by several exact synonyms, including GSD due to phosphoglycerate kinase 1 deficiency, PGK1 deficiency, glycogen storage disease due to phosphoglycerate kinase 1 deficiency, and glycogenosis due to phosphoglycerate kinase 1 deficiency.

Immunodeficiency 38 is categorized as a type of autosomal recessive disease, a primary immunodeficiency disease, and is defined by a condition that arises from autosomal recessive inheritance. It is characterized by severe clinical disease following infection with weakly virulent mycobacteria and intracranial calcification. This condition results from homozygous or compound heterozygous mutations in the ISG15 gene located on chromosome 1p36.33. Immunodeficiency 38 is also known by several exact synonyms, including IMD38, Mendelian susceptibility to mycobacterial diseases due to complete ISG15 deficiency, autosomal recessive ISG15 deficiency, immunodeficiency 38 with basal ganglia calcification, and immunodeficiency 38, mycobacteriosis, autosomal recessive.

Immunodeficiency 16 is a type of disease classified as autosomal recessive and falls under the category of combined T cell and B cell immunodeficiencies. Additionally, it is characterized by being a condition that, at a minimum, has a material basis in autosomal recessive inheritance. This specific immunodeficiency is defined as a combined T cell and B cell immunodeficiency distinguished by childhood classic Kaposi sarcoma, weakened T-cell recall immune responses, and a reduced proportion of circulating memory B cells. The condition is caused by homozygous or compound heterozygous mutations in the TNFRSF4 gene located on chromosome 1p36.33. Immunodeficiency 16 is known by several exact synonyms, including IMD16, OX40 deficiency, combined immunodeficiency due to OX40 deficiency, combined immunodeficiency with childhood-onset Kaposi sarcoma, combined immunodeficiency with impaired immunity to HHV-8, and combined immunodeficiency with impaired immunity to human herpes virus 8.

Immunodeficiency 14 is a type of autosomal dominant disease and is also a type of combined T cell and B cell immunodeficiency. It is characterized by a condition that at least has a material basis in some form of autosomal dominant inheritance. Specifically, Immunodeficiency 14 is described as a combined T cell and B cell immunodeficiency characterized by B- and T-cell abnormalities and the onset of recurrent sinopulmonary and other infections in early childhood. This condition has a material basis in a heterozygous activating mutation in the PIK3CD gene on chromosome 1p36.22. Additionally, Immunodeficiency 14 is known by several exact synonyms including APDS, IMD14, PASLI disease, activated PI3K-delta syndrome, and senescent T-cells-lymphadenopathy-immunodeficiency syndrome due to p110delta-activating mutation.

Immunodeficiency 22 is a type of autosomal recessive disease and also a type of severe combined immunodeficiency. It is characterized by a condition that at least has a material basis in some autosomal recessive inheritance. Specifically, Immunodeficiency 22 is defined as a severe combined immunodeficiency characterized by severe combined immunodeficiency, selective CD4 lymphopenia, and lack of CD28 expression on CD8+ T cells, which is caused by homozygous or compound heterozygous mutation in the LCK gene on chromosome 1p35.2. Furthermore, Immunodeficiency 22 is known by several exact synonyms including IMD22, SCID due to LCK deficiency, SCID due to lymphocyte-specific protein tyrosine kinase deficiency, severe combined immunodeficiency due to LCK deficiency, and severe combined immunodeficiency due to lymphocyte-specific protein tyrosine kinase deficiency.

Immunodeficiency 24 is a type of autosomal recessive disease and also a type of severe combined immunodeficiency, which at least has a material basis in some autosomal recessive inheritance. It is defined as a severe combined immunodeficiency characterized by impaired proliferation of activated T and B cells in response to antigen receptor-mediated activation, which has material basis in homozygous or compound heterozygous mutation in the CTPS1 gene on chromosome 1p34.2. Immunodeficiency 24 has the exact synonyms IMD24, SCID due to CTPS1 deficiency, and severe combined immunodeficiency due to CTPS1 deficiency.

Immunodeficiency 37, also known exactly as IMD37, is a type of autosomal recessive disease that is also classified as a combined T cell and B cell immunodeficiency. This condition is characterized by a specific kind, where its material basis is in some form of autosomal recessive inheritance. Furthermore, it is defined as a combined T cell and B cell immunodeficiency marked by hypogammaglobulinemia with significantly reduced memory B cells and memory T cells, alongside an increase in the numbers of circulating naive lymphocytes. This is due to either homozygous or compound heterozygous mutations in the BCL10 gene located on chromosome 1p22.3.

Immunodeficiency 42 is classified as a type of autosomal recessive disease, primary immunodeficiency disease, and is characterized by a material basis in autosomal recessive inheritance. This condition is defined as a primary immunodeficiency disease that manifests in infancy with an increased susceptibility to mycobacterial and candidal infections, caused by homozygous or compound heterozygous mutation in the RORC gene located on chromosome 1q21.3. It is precisely known by several exact synonyms: IMD42, autosomal recessive MSMD due to complete RORgamma receptor deficiency, autosomal recessive mendelian susceptibility to mycobacterial diseases due to complete RORgamma receptor deficiency, and autosomal recessive primary immunodeficiency due to RORC mutation.

Immunodeficiency 20 is a type of primary immunodeficiency disease, specifically an autosomal recessive disease, which inherently has a material basis in autosomal recessive inheritance. It is characterized by a defect in spontaneous NK cell cytotoxicity, which is due to homozygous or compound heterozygous mutation in the FCGR3A gene on chromosome 1q23.3. This condition is known by several exact synonyms, including CD16 deficiency, IMD20, autosomal recessive primary immunodeficiency with defective spontaneous NK cell cytotoxicity, and autosomal recessive primary immunodeficiency with defective spontaneous natural killer cell cytotoxicity.

Immunodeficiency 25 is a type of autosomal recessive disease and a type of T cell deficiency, which is also categorized as something that at least has a material basis in some autosomal recessive inheritance. It is characterized by a T cell deficiency marked by decreased T cell counts, normal B cell counts, and eosinophilia, which stems from homozygous or compound heterozygous mutation in the CD247 gene on chromosome 1q24.2. Furthermore, Immunodeficiency 25 is precisely known as IMD25 and immunodeficiency due to defect in CD3-zeta.

Immunodeficiency 48, which is also exactly known as IMD48, combined immunodeficiency due to ZAP70 deficiency, and zeta-associated-protein 70 deficiency, is a type of autosomal recessive disease, a type of T cell deficiency, and a type of condition that at least has a material basis in some form of autosomal recessive inheritance. It is characterized by a selective T cell defect where circulating T cells exclusively express CD4, CD3, and T-cell receptor-alpha/beta, and not CD8, on their surfaces. This condition has its material basis in homozygous or compound heterozygous mutations in the ZAP70 gene on chromosome 2q11.2.

Immunodeficiency 31b is a type of autosomal recessive disease, primary immunodeficiency disease, and something that at least has a material basis in some autosomal recessive inheritance. It is characterized by impaired cellular responses to interferons A, B, and G, resulting in increased susceptibility to mycobacteria, Salmonella, and viruses. This is due to a homozygous or compound heterozygous mutation in the STAT1 gene on chromosome 2q32.2. Immunodeficiency 31b is also known by its exact synonyms IMD31B, autosomal recessive STAT1 deficiency, autosomal recessive immunodeficiency 31B, mycobacterial and viral infections, predisposition to severe viral infection due to STAT1 deficiency, and susceptibility to viral and mycobacterial infections due to STAT1 deficiency.

Immunodeficiency 31a is a type of primary immunodeficiency disease, which also falls under the category of autosomal dominant diseases. It is specifically characterized as a disease that inherently has a material basis in autosomal dominant inheritance. The definition of immunodeficiency 31a delineates it as a primary immunodeficiency disease characterized by an impaired response to IFNG, but not to INFA or IFNB, leading to an increased susceptibility to mycobacterial infection. This condition is attributed to a heterozygous mutation in the STAT1 gene located on chromosome 2q32.2. Furthermore, immunodeficiency 31a is known by various exact synonyms including IMD31A, MSMD due to partial STAT1 deficiency, MSMD due to partial signal transducer and activator of transcription 1 deficiency, Mendelian susceptibility to mycobacterial diseases due to partial STAT1 deficiency, Mendelian susceptibility to mycobacterial diseases due to partial signal transducer and activator of transcription 1 deficiency, and autosomal dominant immunodeficiency 31A, mycobacteriosis.

Immunodeficiency 31c is a type of autosomal dominant disease and a primary immunodeficiency disease, characterized by its material basis in some autosomal dominant inheritance. It is defined as a primary immunodeficiency disease that manifests in infancy or childhood with chronic mucocutaneous candidiasis and increased IFNG activation, stemming from a heterozygous gain of function mutation in the STAT1 gene on chromosome 2q32.2. Immunodeficiency 31c is also known by several exact synonyms, including CANDF7, IMD31C, autoimmune enteropathy and endocrinopathy-susceptibility to chronic infections syndrome, autosomal dominant chronic mucocutaneous familial candidiasis, autosomal dominant immunodeficiency 31C, and familial candidiasis 7.

Immunodeficiency 21 is classified as a primary immunodeficiency disease, which is a type of autosomal dominant disease. It specifically arises from a heterozygous mutation in the GATA2 gene on chromosome 3q21.3 and is characterized by a profound decrease or absence of monocytes, B lymphocytes, natural killer (NK) lymphocytes, and circulating and tissue dendritic cells, while having normal or nearly normal T cell numbers. Furthermore, immunodeficiency 21 is known by several exact synonyms, including DCML, GATA2 deficiency, IMD21, MonoMAC, combined immunodeficiency with susceptibility to mycobacterial, viral and fungal infections, dendritic cell, monocyte, B and NK lymphoid deficiency, monocyte-B-natural killer-dendritic cell deficiency syndrome, monocytopenia and mycobacterial infection syndrome, and monocytopenia with susceptibility to infections.

Immunodeficiency 46, also known exactly as CID due to TFRC deficiency, IMD46, TFRC-related combined immunodeficiency, and combined immunodeficiency due to TFRC deficiency, is characterized as an autosomal recessive disease and a type of combined T cell and B cell immunodeficiency. It is described by a condition that essentially arises from autosomal recessive inheritance. Specifically, immunodeficiency 46 is defined as a combined T cell and B cell immunodeficiency marked by hypo- or agammaglobulinemia, normal lymphocyte counts, intermittent neutropenia and thrombocytopenia, reduced numbers of memory B cells, impaired ability for immunoglobulin class-switching, and diminished proliferative responses of T cells, all attributing to homozygous or compound heterozygous mutations in the TFRC gene on chromosome 3q29.

Immunodeficiency 36 (IMD36), also known as activated phosphoinositide 3-kinase delta syndrome 2, is a type of autosomal dominant disease characterized by a combined T cell and B cell immunodeficiency. This condition involves recurrent respiratory tract infections, lymphoproliferation, and antibody deficiency, which originates from a heterozygous mutation in the PIK3R1 gene located on chromosome 5q13.1. Additionally, immunodeficiency 36 is categorized as a disease that fundamentally has a material basis in some form of autosomal dominant inheritance.

Immunodeficiency 29 is recognized as a type of autosomal recessive disease, a primary immunodeficiency disease, and is characterized by having at least a material basis in autosomal recessive inheritance. It is defined as a primary immunodeficiency disease characterized by undetectable IL12B secretion by leukocytes and increased susceptibility to intracellular bacterial infections, which is due to homozygous or compound heterozygous mutation in the IL12B gene on chromosome 5q33.3. Immunodeficiency 29 is known by several exact synonyms, including IL12B deficiency, IMD29, MSMD due to complete IL12B deficiency, MSMD due to complete interleukin 12B deficiency, Mendelian susceptibility to mycobacterial diseases due to complete IL12B deficiency, Mendelian susceptibility to mycobacterial diseases due to complete interleukin 12B deficiency, and immunodeficiency 29, mycobacteriosis.

Immunodeficiency 40 is an autosomal recessive disease characterized by a combined T cell and B cell immunodeficiency, which indicates a material basis in some autosomal recessive inheritance. This condition is defined by a reduced number of T cells and diminished function, alongside variable defects in B-cell and NK-cell function. These impairments lead to the early onset of invasive bacterial and viral infections. The disease is caused by homozygous or compound heterozygous mutations in the DOCK2 gene located on chromosome 5q35.1. Immunodeficiency 40 is also known by its exact synonyms, DOCK2 deficiency and IMD40.

Immunodeficiency 57 is a type of primary immunodeficiency disease, which is also classified as an autosomal recessive disease. It is further described as a condition that has a material basis in autosomal recessive inheritance. This disease is characterized by recurrent infections starting in the first year of life, lymphopenia, altered production of various cytokines, inflammatory polyarthritis, and chronic active inflammation of the digestive tract. These symptoms are due to homozygous or compound heterozygous mutation in the RIPK1 gene on chromosome 6p25.2. Immunodeficiency 57 is also known by its exact synonyms: IMD57, immune dysregulation-inflammatory bowel disease-arthritis-recurrent infections-lymphopenia syndrome, and immunodeficiency 57 with autoinflammation.

Immunodeficiency 23 is a type of autosomal recessive disease, specifically a combined T cell and B cell immunodeficiency. This condition is characterized by marked atopy and autoimmunity, which results from increased T(H)2 and T(H)17 cytokine production by CD4(+) T cells. Patients experience T-cell lymphopenia, reduced memory B-cell numbers, recurrent respiratory and skin infections beginning in early childhood, increased serum IgE, and variable developmental delay or intellectual impairment. The material basis of this disease is found in homozygous or compound heterozygous mutation in the PGM3 gene on chromosome 6q14.1. Immunodeficiency 23 is also known by several exact synonyms, including CID due to PGM3 deficiency, IMD23, PGM3-CDG, and PGM3-related congenital disorder of glycosylation, all of which refer to combined immunodeficiency due to PGM3 deficiency.
